<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / International Company News: LTV unveils restructuring plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LTV, the third largest US steel manufacturer, yesterday unveiled a plan
aimed at paving the way for it to emerge from the protection of the
bankruptcy courts - but the package immediately ran into strong criticism
from its creditors.
The company estimates that its unsecured creditors will be paid a maximum of
only 25 per cent of their claims, while LTV pays large amounts of available
funds to its largest creditor, the Federal Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corporation.
The official LTV Steel Creditors' Committee said it believed the plan
substantially overestimated the amounts creditors might recover and also
meant a 'grossly unfair' allocation in favour of the PBGC and the company's
pension plans.
LTV sought Chapter 11 protection in 1986, when the US steel industry was in
the throes of a severe shake-out. It was weighed down by underfunded pension
liabilities and high debt and health care costs.
A restructuring programme has been delayed by a long-running dispute with
the FBGC, the US pension insurance agency, over payment for LTV's pension
liabilities. But a breakthrough agreement between the two sides was achieved
in February, clearing the way for yesterday's announcement by LTV of its
first restructuring proposal.
Under the pensions deal, LTV would contribute Dollars 880m in cash and
assets to three pension funds and from 1993 would make annual fixed payments
of Dollars 100m, plus 50 per cent of available cash flow above that figure.
The agency's claims total over Dollars 2.3bn.
LTV would raise Dollars 300m in new cash as part of the initial Dollars 880m
and is considering asset sales to meet this commitment.
Secured creditors would get 100 cents on the dollar but unsecured creditors
would only get up to a quarter of their claims, and would be paid in new
common stock. Current holders of common and preferred stock would also
receive new paper, in the ratio of 1.11 new shares for each 100 previously
owned. The company estimates the value of the new stock at Dollars 1bn to
Dollars 1.25bn.
</TEXT>
