<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Midland sells Australian offshoot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MIDLAND BANK is selling Dominguez Barry Samuel Montagu, its Australian
merchant banking business, to Swiss Bank Corporation.
Swiss Bank will buy a 60 per cent interest, with the re-mainder being bought
by DBSM management and employees.
The Australian bank employs 260 people and has total assets of ADollars 409m
(Pounds 183.41m). It made ADollars 13.4m before tax in 1990.
No price was revealed for the sale, but it is believed to have brought
Midland a premium over DBSM's net asset value, which was ADollars 24m at the
end of 1989.
Midland stressed that DBSM is a successful business, but the sale was part
of its strategy of divesting itself of non-core activities outside Europe.
Swiss Bank Corporation said that the acquisition would enable it to expand
its international investment banking presence.
Midland is combining its French corporate finance activities in a company,
Samuel Montagu France, with a capital of FFr2.25m (Pounds 225,027). The
activities were previously separated into Samuel Montagu and the Midland
Bank.
