FT  02 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Fenner profits halve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FENNER, the diversified Hull-based manufacturing and distribution group,
yesterday announced an abrupt end to a period of sustained growth with
pre-tax profits nearly halved from Pounds 7.26m to Pounds 3.71m for the
first half of 1990/91.
The shares fell 4p to 132p underlining the severity and suddenness of the
recession which hit UK heavy manufacturing last autumn. Profits in the year
1989/90 rose 21 per cent to Pounds 16.1m, but analysts now expect the total
for the current year to be about Pounds 8.5m-Pounds 9m.
Turnover for the first half slipped from Pounds 102.5m to Pounds 100.5m.
The interim dividend is held at 3.45p. Mr Peter Barker, chairman, said this
reflected the strengths of the businesses. Fenner has cut 350 jobs, or some
15% of its workforce, in the current year. This would be reflected by a
Pounds 6m provision.
On the outlook, Mr Barker said 'signs are apparent that demand levels are
now stabilising,' but the economic recovery widely forecast for the latter
part of 1991 was unlikely to come in time to influence the outcome in the
current year.
</TEXT>
