<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Olympia &amp; York 'resilient' says credit rating agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A CANADIAN credit-rating agency has concluded that the financial condition
of Reichmann-controlled Olympia &amp; York Developments - which has interests in
London's Docklands - remains resilient despite some severe setbacks to its
vast property and natural resources investments.
O&amp;Y, involved in London's Canary Wharf development, has seen the market
value of its listed investments fall 18 per cent in the past year. The group
has taken a hard knock from the property slump in New York, London and
Toronto.
But the Toronto-based Dominion Bond Rating Service said in a report to
clients yesterday that O&amp;Y appeared to have adequate equity to support its
debt. Furthermore, it said that some of the Reichmanns' holdings in listed
companies could probably be sold at a 25 to 30 per cent premium to their
market value of CDollars 5.4bn (Pounds 2.75bn).
These holdings include an 82 per cent stake in newsprint-maker
Abitibi-Price, and a 35 per cent interest in Trizec, North America's biggest
listed property developer.
In reviewing one of O&amp;Y's commercial paper programmes, the rating agency
concluded that 'whatever O&amp;Y's credit strength was one year ago, it is
weaker today. Nonetheless, it is still strong enough to maintain (its)
rating', equivalent to a double A.
O&amp;Y is a private company, and Dominion emphasised that it had never seen the
group's financial statements. The agency's report was drawn up in
consultation with O&amp;Y executives, including Mr Paul Reichmann, the family's
master strategist.
On Canary Wharf, O&amp;Y told the rating agency that signed leases and deals
'close to completion' cover almost 3m of the 4.7m sq ft that will become
available over the next 18 months.
According to O&amp;Y, 'there has been a substantial increase in tenant interest
now that full visual impact has become apparent'.
The Reichmanns predict that up to 85 per cent of the space will be committed
by the time the first tenants move in.
However, the agency's report expressed several concerns about O&amp;Y's property
exposure in New York, where it is the biggest office landlord, and in London
and Toronto.
The concerns include these cities' heavy reliance on the financial services
industry, and a concentration of tenants in its portfolio.
</TEXT>
