<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Sound Diffusion
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The accountancy debates of the 1980s are obviously going to rumble on into
the 1990s. The issues behind accounting for leasing profits are so
complicated that one could write a book on them; indeed at 255 pages, the
DTI inspectors of Sound Diffusion have. But shareholders must feel that if
there can be such wide disagreement between inspectors and two leading firms
of auditors, they have little hope of keeping track. Given the 1980s'
problems in the computer leasing sector, leasing companies are not likely to
be too welcome on the stock market for a while. It is perhaps unsurprising
that GPA is private.
In the circumstances, one can feel more than a twinge of sympathy for the
two non-executive directors, Mr Macdonald and Mr Howard, brought in to sort
out the complicated mess and ending up only with brickbats from the
inspectors for their pains. The criticisms may well re-open the issue of
whether inspectors should be allowed to be so trenchant. And given that the
report took two years to complete, only to conclude that no single factor
was responsible for the group's failure, the taxpayer might wonder whether
the expense of these investigations is justified.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1861</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAF6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Buy-outs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MFI's debt rescheduling and Tuesday's Pounds 108m deal for Devro will
doubtless revive bitter-sweet memories of a bygone age. The furniture
group's buy-out will probably go down as one of the worst-timed transactions
of its kind; the Scottish sausage skin company's spin-off from Johnson and
Johnson will be seen as a hopeful sign that the market may shortly splutter
back into life.
That is almost certainly an optimistic view. It is true that small deals
involving funds of Pounds 10m to Pounds 20m are still being done. But the
huge buy-outs which were such a feature of the late 1980s - MFI, Magnet,
Isosceles - have all but dried up. The problem is not a shortage of equity,
for there are funds aplenty eagerly seeking out opportunities to invest. The
reason for the low level of activity is the newly-cautious attitude of the
banks. As in other areas of lending, they have drawn in their horns, alarmed
in this case by the dozen or so buy-outs which have gone into receivership
in the last year (equivalent to 6 per cent of the total funds invested in
buy-outs since records began). Whereas the average deal in the half year to
December 1989 involved one part equity to six parts mezzanine finance and
debt, the average ratio during the second half of last year was just one to
two.
Though none of the 20 most highly-leveraged bids of the 1980s has yet
failed, there is every reason to applaud more conservative structures after
the excesses of the recent past. But the irony is that - for buy-outs, at
any rate - the pendulum has probably swung too far the other way.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
