<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Scottish banks
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank of Scotland has made something of a habit of rights issues, without
ever meeting the positive reception accorded yesterday's Pounds 194m call.
But the successful issue and 12 per cent dividend increase, timed to
coincide with what the bank hopes is the bottom of the economic cycle, will
probably not act as an incentive for other clearing banks thinking about
propping up their ailing capital ratios. Despite the unfortunate symmetry of
the Pounds 202m of bad debt provisions in its full-year figures, Bank of
Scotland knows it can tell a better story than its competitors. The contrast
with the rights issues in recent years by Midland, Standard Chartered, or
for that matter Barclays, is obvious.
The market believes Bank of Scotland will make good use of the rights
proceeds despite a slide in second-half profits which augurs badly for the
first six months of this financial year. It is probably right. The loan book
expanded by a fifth last year and will grow again this year by more than 10
per cent as it uses its strengthened capital position to pursue the
higher-margin business now available. Underlying profits were respectable
enough to justify the dividend increase; yet more reason for the other banks
to be envious.
As for the Royal Bank of Scotland, its performance was slightly more typical
of the sector. The maintained interim dividend simply emphasised how much it
over-estimated the outlook by raising its final payment nearly 17 per cent
last November.
</TEXT>
