<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Distance lends enchantment
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,508.4 (+22.2)
London rose obediently in response to Wall Street's welcome for the April
purchasing managers' report, which came in above expectations. On Monday,
the Chicago purchasing managers, usually read as a leading indicator for the
big one, fell; but the national reading rose for the third successive month.
There is a message here, but it may not be quite the one London is reading.
The main industrial news in the US is that car output is rising - witness
the very bullish Michigan report, now showing a positive balance of 25 per
cent. This was bound to happen; output was some 20 per cent below even the
depressed level of sales, which has so far recovered only marginally.
Housing is just off the bottom, but is unlikely to rise much above it. The
rest of the construction scene is dismal.
In the words of the new Beige Book, activity is weak, but there are some
signs of bottoming out. Wall Street comment is rather more bearish about the
economy, but likes lower rates and a falling dollar. Modified rapture.
The question for UK investors is how much any US delight should influence
views on this side of the water. A British turnaround is still the subject
of speculation, margins are being squeezed, the currency is uncomfortably
strong and stuck. Higher output in Detroit means little in London. We march
with Wall Street, say the brokers; but recently they have only been
following it upwards. The Dow is still 3 per cent off its peak; after
yesterday London is very near the top.
</TEXT>
