<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Letter: Advice to banks - try paying more visits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr F X O'MALLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, P H Nunnerley, in his letter of April 23, states that 'we constantly
remind our customers to come to their bank manager at the first signs of
problems'. Sadly, despite all the glitz and rhetoric of the marketing men,
this is the same old tongue-in-cheek message preached by many bank managers
up and down the country.
Since problem detection in this manner can be a highly subjective exercise
(how many small business owners, totally immersed in the running of their
business, would elect to soldier on in the sometimes mistaken hope that the
matter would self-correct, rather than admit they had a problem?), would it
not be both more productive and desirable for the bank manager TO GO AND SEE
HIS CUSTOMER? By so doing, he would be demonstrating a real interest in his
customer's affairs as well as acquainting himself first-hand with some of
the problems and frustrations of trying to do business in the real world.
To maintain, as Mr Nunnerley does, that banks 'are largely in the hands of
the companies themselves', smacks of appalling smugness: try telling that
with a straight face to a small business owner, mortgaged to the hilt and
with a debenture around his neck.
In the final analysis, there can be no substitute for the good old-fashioned
virtue of customer service and in a world where long-established beliefs and
conventions are rapidly being swept aside, bank managers would do well to
spend more time in the field with their customers and, as a corollary, less
time in the relative comfort of the bank worrying about the size of their
provisions.
F X O'Malley,
PO Box 2,
Farnsfield,
Newark,
Notts.
</TEXT>
