<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Still struggling to get out of a spin: British textile
companies must invest to be competitive in the 1990s
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This spring the City of London has turned its attention to the dark satanic
mills of the textile industry as Tootal, one of Britain's oldest textile
groups, battles against a Pounds 252m hostile takeover bid from Coats
Viyella.
Tootal is fighting for independence at a time when the British textile
industry is under intense pressure. In the past two years hundreds of mills
have closed and scores of companies have folded. There were nearly 100 job
losses in textiles and clothing every working day last year.
The critical questions for Tootal, Coats and their competitors is when will
the industry - which employs 475,000 people and has a turnover of Pounds
14bn - recover and what will it look like at the end of the recession?
Recession is scarcely a new phenomenon for the textile industry, which has
been in decline since the early 1900s when it held a quarter of world trade.
Its development since the second world war has been dominated by its
struggle to find a role in a global market polarised between the Germans and
Italians with their high-technology mills at the upper end and the low-cost
Asian producers at the lower end.
The recession of the late 1970s and early 1980s finally convinced British
companies they could no longer compete successfully against the Asians. They
then invested in modern spinning and weaving systems to try to upgrade their
products and catch up with the Germans and Italians.
For a few years they seemed to have succeeded. Productivity rose by 40 per
cent between 1980 and 1988, when the industry invested Pounds 3bn in new
equipment. By the mid-1980s, when consumer spending was buoyant and sterling
was competitive against the US dollar (with which many Asian currencies are
linked) British textile companies basked in the benefits of rationalisation
and re-investment.
'A few years ago I really believed that all the work we had done had made
sure we could compete against anyone anywhere,' said Sir David Alliance,
chairman of Coats. 'But I was wrong.'
By the late 1980s when consumer spending started to slow and the pound
strengthened, the textile sector returned to recession. The crux of its
problems is that, despite all the investment of the mid-1980s, it is still
less competitive than the Germans and Italians. A report by the National
Institute of Economic and Social Research showed that British clothing
companies lagged behind the Germans in almost every area from training to
machinery maintenance.
The industry is now suffering on the domestic front not only from the
slowdown in consumer spending but also because of the financial instability
of its retail customers. At the same time the strong pound has made it more
difficult for British products to compete against imports.
The industry is also prey to the vagaries of the global textile trade. It is
vulnerable to unpredictable swings in fashion and to unexpected changes in
raw material prices. There are also sudden surges of imports, like a recent
influx of cheap Chinese cotton knickers. And there is growing competition
from subsidised industries, such as the Indian and Turkish spinning sectors.
The whole industry has suffered in the recession, but the worst-affected
areas are those that faced additional pressures. The knitting industry has
been hit by the trend away from traditional knitwear and by a rapid rise in
imports of socks from Indonesia and knitted babywear from Thailand. Its
workforce has fallen by 17,000 to 65,000 and 150 knitting companies have
closed in the past 18 months.
In the short term the rationalisation is likely to continue. Coats's main
aim in bidding for Tootal is to merge their international thread businesses.
But Coats also hopes to combine their interests in the UK where Tootal
employs 6,500 people and is a leading supplier of shirts and trousers to
Marks and Spencer.
This integration would probably involve combining administrative operations
and some cuts in production capacity. Coats has said that, if the bid
succeeds, there could be up to 500 job losses. Even if the bid fails, Tootal
will continue with its own cost-cutting.
As the takeover struggle continues there is no evidence of improvement in
the general trading environment. The domestic market does seem to have
stabilised in terms of demand, albeit at a low level. However, last month's
rise in the rate of value added tax to 17.5 per cent is a serious concern.
Higher clothing prices could not only depress demand, but will also
intensify pressure on profitability. Retailers are trying to pass on the VAT
increase to their clothing suppliers which in turn are seeking to hand it on
to their yarn and cloth suppliers.
Most companies are resigned to the recession continuing at least until the
autumn. They should then see the first signs of revival if, as most
forecasters expect, consumer spending recovers and the stronger dollar
alleviates the pressure from Asian imports.
'Next year we should see a virtuous cycle of stronger demand and more
favourable currency,' said Mr Martin Taylor, chief executive of Courtaulds
Textiles, which has extensive spinning and clothing interests. 'That will be
nice but it will not secure the industry's future. For that we need to build
a robust business.'
The dominant issue for the industry is whether the recession has impeded its
attempts to become more competitive in the international market.
Even when the recession does end, one of its results will be that many
companies will have cut capital expenditure at a time when the Germans and
Italians - who already had more modern plants - have carried on investing.
British investment peaked at Pounds 549m in 1988 and fell to about Pounds
450m last year.
However the recession has been beneficial in some respects, notably by
weeding out the least competitive areas of the industry. Small family
businesses have borne the brunt. Most of the 150 knitting companies which
closed were small 'sweatshop' concerns.
Similarly many of the plants making cheaper products have disappeared,
particularly in spinning and weaving. This means the surviving mills
concentrate on the more expensive products that are less vulnerable to
fluctuations in exchange rates.
A further consequence of the recession has been to accelerate changes within
individual companies. One of the most important trends is
internationalisation. Traditionally most textile groups have concentrated
production in Britain. They are now manufacturing an increasing proportion
of their merchandise overseas - mainly in lower-cost Asian countries -
either in their own plants or from sub-contractors.
This means a women's wear manufacturer, such as Dewhirst, cuts costs by
sourcing the first batch of an order from Asia. It then makes later batches
in its British factories which offer a speedier service by reducing delivery
times.
The trend towards overseas sourcing seems set to continue. William Baird,
one of the largest clothing companies, staged a Pounds 39m rights issue this
week to raise money for expansion. One of the main areas for investment will
be Asia.
'We are still committed to investment in the UK,' said Mr Donald Parr,
chairman. 'But our overseas interests will be the focus of expansion for the
next five or six years.'
Overseas sourcing is scarcely a panacea for the British textile industry.
But it can not be a coincidence that the most resilient companies during the
recession have been those with extensive overseas interests and strong
investment records.
Courtaulds Textiles, which began the 1980s as a traditional British-based
group, ended the decade as a portfolio of specialised international
businesses. It has suffered in the recession. It cut its workforce by 3,200
to 28,200 last year. But it still managed to maintain profits at Pounds 40m
on sales of Pounds 984m in 1990 thanks to disciplined management and a broad
international base.
This is the type of company that is best placed to benefit when the industry
pulls out of recession. It would be foolish to pretend that the 1990s offer
anything to the British textile industry other than a continuation of the
same struggle for international competitiveness.
But Courtaulds Textiles' record suggests that if the surviving British
companies are prepared to invest in technology, management and international
expansion they should be able to secure a future in the volatile world of
textiles.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
