<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Observer: Small business
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is rare for a general chamber of commerce to become a political hotbed.
But that's what has happened in Hong Kong where big-business interests keen
to quieten anti-China dissent have squashed the colony's self-styled
spokesman for small business, 67-year-old expatriate Jimmy McGregor.
A former director of the chamber and its representative on Hong Kong's
legislative council since 1988, he has just declared he will not stand in
the next council elections. The reason, he claims, is that the big
businesses dominating the chamber's general committee have 'stacked the
cards' against him, favouring his opponent Paul Cheng. Cheng, an executive
director of Inchcape Pacific, already sits on the legislative body as a
government nominee.
'It stinks,' says the abrasive McGregor, who defeated an establishment
candidate for council membership in 1988, and has called for faster
democratic development as well as greater resistance to China than the
chamber's big names could stomach.
One who has been particularly angered by his stance is Helmut Sohmen, who
runs the shipping empire of father-in-law Sir Yue-Kong Pao. Another is the
chamber's new chairman Vincent Lo, a construction and property entrepreneur
with close China connections.
McGregor's predicament is partly self-inflicted because he has gone his own
way without trying to build bridges with his critics. But Cheng, who
exemplifies Inchcape blandness and government orthodoxy, is a pale
replacement. Such machinations, although perhaps making China and big
business happy, do little for democracy - especially in a place like Hong
Kong where it has hardly begun developing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
