<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Economic Viewpoint: Reappearance of the 'growthmen'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The years after the first oil shock following the Yom Kippur war of 1973
were ones of very rapid inflation and slow average growth. But national
leaders thought they had learned something from this experience and the
1980s saw a somewhat better growth performance and a much lower average
inflation rate.
Policy was governed by what some people have called the 'new orthodoxy', and
what I once called the counter-revolution. Its intellectual underpinning
was, among other things, a demonstration by Professor Milton Friedman in
1967 that governments could not spend their way into desired rates of output
and employment without risking not merely an inflation, but accelerating
inflation.
This theme was put starkly by the then Mr James Callaghan to, of all bodies,
the 1976 Labour party conference when the UK was negotiating a rescue
package with the IMF. The Labour prime minister's words were repeated time
without number by Mrs Thatcher and her chancellors. One reason why Labour
still wants to dabble in industrial interventionism is that it is not
prepared to challenge this new macroeconomic orthodoxy, any more than
President Mitterrand's socialist government is in France.
The new orthodoxy does not mean that all policy is 'ineffective' - a
caricature view of what some later academics have espoused. It merely states
that macroeconomic policy will be most effective if it concentrates on
nominal aims - such as stable prices, exchange rate objectives, monetary
targets or Nominal GDP - the precise choice or combination of objectives
varying with time and place.
Who are the main opponents of the new orthodoxy? They are in ascending order
of importance: the technical monetarists who are so incensed by exchange
rate targets or any departure from their personally favoured monetary
aggregates that they threaten us with the spectre of world depression. In
practice their advice is not too different from that of the pockets of
unreconstructed Keynesianism that remain in academia, and more instinctively
among politicians and businessmen. A good example is the British House of
Commons Treasury Committee, which still sees salvation in reforming the
official forecasts and has now come up with the perverse idea of four
forecasts a year instead of two, with politicians not interfering - as if
that alone were a guarantee of impartiality. The chancellor is right that a
careful use of surveys can provide a better idea of turning-points than any
number of formal forecasts.
But the only unreconstructed group of growthmen who really matter are in the
US policy-making establishment - interestingly, the Republicans, even more
than the Democrats. The most unreconstructed of all appears to be President
George Bush, despite his avowed preference for foreign affairs (for which
many Kurds will be grateful).
Has the world been experiencing such a depression or growth recession that
it is reasonable to throw away the new orthodoxy and stimulate spending at
all costs? The large chart, taken from a DRI McGraw Hill study of The
International Outlook after the Gulf War*, shows that the slow-down in world
real growth has so far been mild by historical standards. On the other hand,
inflation, on present prospects, is unlikely to fall as far as it did in the
mid-1980s, when admittedly it was given a downward shove by a collapse in
the oil price.
The annualised rate of growth of US Nominal GDP has now slowed down from 8
per cent in 1988 to 3 1/2 per cent in the first quarter of 1991 compared
with a year ago (and 2 1/2 per cent compared with the previous quarter).
This is far from being a depression rate; but it is low enough to create
some presumption in favour of stimulation. The obstinate persistence of
underlying US inflation (measured by the GDP deflator) at 4 per cent
suggests caution about the dose and keeping an eye on the dollar.
Even if US nominal demand needs a stimulus, it is still difficult to see why
other countries have also to be pressurised into reducing interest rates.
This might have made sense in the US a few months ago when the weakness of
the dollar was cited by some Fed governors as a reason for resisting still
cheaper money. But after the dollar shot up why did the US administration
bother to launch its deservedly abortive Group of Seven initiative, rebuffed
by the Germans and Japanese? Unilateral US interest rate cuts are surely
more useful in achieving the administration's twin objectives of a brake on
the dollar and stimulating domestic growth.
US action only makes sense on the assumption that the administration was in
such a panic about economic prospects that it wanted to throw in every
weapon of which it could think: lower interest rates abroad; much lower
interest rates at home; a dollar depreciation to boot; and every kind of
pressure on its trading partners.
Normally, I abstain from second guessing the US economy from 3,000 miles
away. But an interesting light is thrown by some confidence surveys put
together by the London Business School. These show that US consumer
confidence, which had plunged alarmingly during the Gulf conflict, has now
returned to a near-level trend, despite a very slight kick-back in April.
Producer confidence, which normally lags, is still declining.
In the UK the profile has been different. Consumer confidence started to
deteriorate much earlier. The beginnings of a recovery were apparent in the
middle of 1990 but were nipped in the bud by the Gulf crisis; but since the
'end' of the war the improvement has resumed. Producer confidence is charted
by the CBI survey. The accompanying table shows key answers compared with
the corresponding period of the 1980 recession. Answers relating to past or
recent performance show a sharper deterioration than was expected at the
turn of the year. But forward-looking answers show what can only be
described as much less pessimism.
The two questions with the best record in plotting turning points are
business optimism and expected volume of output. Although there is still a
balance of pessimists over optimists, it is much smaller than in January and
much smaller than in the corresponding period of 1980. The same applies to
expected volume of output (and a similar picture is shown by the chart of
expected orders). Export pessimism is also much less than in January and in
the corresponding period of 1980. For there has not been the kind of upward
pressure on sterling that squeezed business so much a decade ago. But there
is still enough pressure on margins to put a dampener on producer prices.
The balance of companies expecting to raise their prices is now at its
lowest since 1967.
The most dismal answer relates to employment, where there is still a
substantial balance of respondents expected to lay off workers. The British
disease of putting all the pressure on staff numbers rather than pay costs
remains; and because unemployment is a lagging indicator it will continue at
varying rates well into 1992.
A broader perspective is supplied by the IMF chart showing the deviation of
output from trend in different groups of countries. In the three
English-speaking countries, the US, the UK and Canada, output rose in the
late 1980s to a non-sustainable level in relation to capacity; and in order
to keep inflation down, these economies will have to go through a period of
below-capacity operation, even when recovery of sorts begins. In France and
Italy, there was a smaller boom and a more moderate slump is in prospect. In
Japan and West Germany, the picture has been much more stable. The deep
growth recession of 1987 was probably an aberration.
The different experience of the English-speaking countries (which could have
included Australia) has to do with the high indebtedness incurred by
borrowers in those countries after financial liberalisation and the severe
retrenchment now taking place. It may be that both borrowers and lenders in
these countries will henceforth follow a course of 'once bitten, twice shy'.
In any case the fashionable calls for 'reregulation' would weaken these
countries in the sector where they have the clearest comparative advantage.
*1 Hartfield Road, Wimbledon, London, SW19 3RU, price Pounds 2,500.
Tel: (44 71) 543 1234.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Two UK recessions: Balance of CBI replies
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Percentage balance  Jan '80  Apr '80  July '80 Oct '90 Jan '91 Apr '91
Business optimism      -45     -41       -70      -47     -51   -17
Export optimism        -30     -21       -57      -26     -26    -8
Expected employment    -35     -40       -58      -37     -49   -39
Expected volume of
output                 -11     -14       -41      -17     -30    -8
Expected unit costs     76      72        63       46      44    21
Expected domestic
prices                  65      56        33       23      25    10
