<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Arts: Crisis brews for London arts funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The future of a hundred arts companies in London, including such established
names as the Almeida Theatre, the King's Head, the Photographer's Gallery
and Dance Umbrella, hangs in the balance following the decision of Ealing
Council on Tuesday to reject the proposed Pounds 29m budget for the London
Borough Grants Scheme, suggesting instead an expenditure of Pounds 26m.
A Crisis in London Arts Funding Steering Group had already been set up to
fight the lower than expected Pounds 29m budget, which reduced the arts
grants allocated by the LBGC (which also funds welfare projects) from Pounds
3m to Pounds 2m, involving the immediate loss of money to 16 companies
including the Almeida, (Pounds 55,000); the ICA (Pounds 55,000); The
Photographer's Gallery (Pounds 47,000); and Greenwich Theatre (Pounds
45,000).
Now the vote at Ealing throws the future of the reduced sum into jeopardy.
The LBGS meets again on May 8 for another attempt to fix a budget, which
requires a two thirds majority. Even if it re-establishes the Pounds 29m
budget, which is by no means certain, the cheques for the surviving arts
beneficiaries will not come through until June, three months into the
current financial year.
The confirmed loss of grants, and the uncertainty over the future, has
already resulted in staff cuts at 40 per cent of the companies who have had
LBGS funding axed.
Timothy Mason, for ten years Director of the Scottish Arts Council, is to
take over as Chief Executive of the new London Arts Board, which succeeds
the defunct Greater London Arts in October.
GLA lost the confidence of the Arts Council and the larger London arts
organisations who were to be allocated to it under the Government arts
devolution policy. By choosing such an experienced administrator the Council
will hope to restore faith in the concept of London having its own arts
board.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1882</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAFLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Arts: The Cunning Little Vixen - Coliseum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Newly refurbished for this revival (sponsored by British Fuels Group),
Janacek's little opera comes up fresh as paint, and irresistible. Nothing
has faded in David Pountney's production, nor in Maria Bjornson's witty,
pretty designs - all the visual jokes re-play very well; and Nick Chelton's
lighting has been beautifully recreated. I admit to preferring this Vixen to
the Royal Opera's more hi-tech version, handsome though that is.
It is not easy to imagine the new principals bettered. Lesley Garrett sings
as if the role of the Vixen were what she'd always aimed at: bright, utterly
confident and vital, appealing without a trace of cute whimsy. No vocal
squeaks, either, in a part full of perilous leaps; she delivers it with
flawless musical sympathy, and in the erotic passages - particularly candid
with these furry lovers - she twangs one's heartstrings.
Her Fox, Christine Botes, pleaded a sore throat on this first night, but
that can only mean that she will be even better later. She managed an
attractive sound anyway, shaped her phrases with the same authority as Miss
Garrett, and deployed her Jack-the-lad persona with a disarming, toothy
grin.
No doubt both these remarkable debuts in the roles owe much to Sir Charles
Mackerras, who knows the score as well as anyone in the world. Though he has
been conducting it for years, this was his first time with it at the English
National Opera. It sounded glorious: he had the violins dancing and
sparkling even in that cruelly high register where Janacek likes to push
them, and some kind of magic (partly electronic?) was worked with the great
burst of hunting-horns. Mackerras began the third act with the proper stark
menace; but everywhere else the music was steeped in affectionate warmth,
quite memorably in the courting-and-mating of Act Two.
If Norman Bailey is now slightly under-powered for the grand final
peroration, his sage, grizzled Forester is a masterly operatic portrait.
Indeed, though the character is no saint, Bailey gives him a kind of moral
weight which serves as anchor for everything else that goes on. He is
abetted with delightful skill by Terry Jenkins' woeful Schoolmaster and Mark
Richardson's gloomy Parson. The numerous other roles are vividly taken, and
a lot of excellent children do their foxcubs and other woodland creatures
with neat charm, coyness-free - more praise to Pountney and his
choreographer Stuart Hopps.
For newcomers to the opera, there could be no happier introduction. A
creditable amount of the English text is made distinct; adults can enjoy the
piece as much with children, for whom it will all seem perfectly clear, as
without. And long-standing fans of the Vixen will certainly discover many
moments in the opera which have not seemed so apt and telling before; and
above all, as I said, the central soprano pair are pure delight.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
