<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Accountancy Column: Secrecy and success in schizophrenic
institute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMAGINE THAT you are a bright young partner in one of the UK's top 20
accountancy practices. Like all young partners, you are eager to promote
your career. But, unlike the majority of this breed, you take a lively
interest in professional affairs.
You have impassioned views on the Caparo decision, you are fascinated by the
politics of accounting standards, you are proud of your profession. But
would you like to reach the pinnacle of the profession and become president
of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales?
Even if you would like to achieve this honour, would you know how to go
about it? The answer is probably no, for even ageing senior partners who
have decades of experience of the institute and its arcane ways have little
idea of how the president is elected.
The Accountancy Column can reveal exclusively that the president is elected
by the meeting of the institute's council members every June.
There are more than 80 of these distinguished personages, who collectively
take responsibility for running the institute. At the end of the June
meeting, one of them will be chosen for the presidency three years in the
future, because elections are held three years in advance.
This is not as simple as it seems. Even though council members vote for the
next president but two, they have no choice in the matter. There has never,
in the 111-year history of the institute, been more than one candidate for
this eminent position. In short, the election is predetermined.
The real election takes place several months before at a meeting - or a
series of meetings - of the so-called president's advisory committee. This
is the most secret of all the ICAEW's myriad committees  - so secret that it
goes under different names according to the different functions it fulfils.
On occasions this committee is known as the committee review subcommittee.
Under this name it decides who shall chair and take the main positions on
the institute's policy-making committees - the parliamentary and law
committee and the business law committee, as well as the district societies
standing conference and the financial and auditing committee.
As the president's advisory committee, it is responsible for producing a
candidate for the presidency.
Under normal circumstances, the membership consists of this year's
president, the deputy and the vice-president (presidents for next year and
the year after), and the institute's last six presidents. When in its
committee review sub-committee capacity, three, not six, past-presidents
attend, plus one other council member.
The veil cannot be lifted any further. It is not known what are the concerns
of the past presidents and the present president, and the next two
presidents to come, when they produce a name for the presidential candidate.
To its credit, the ICAEW has itself recognised the limitations of the
methods by which presidents are elected. Under Mr Arthur Green, a former
president and therefore a member of the most secret committee, a working
party has undertaken an extensive review of the ICAEW's constitutional
arrangements.
The report, published last month, recommends that the council be replaced
with an enlarged representative assembly and a slimmed-down executive board.
The board, which would take over many of the functions of the current
council, would also be responsible for electing the president.
The president's advisory committee would be replaced with a nominating
committee, the job of which would be to nominate candidates. Any person
getting the support of more than 10 per cent of the 150-person
representative committee would have to be among the nominees going forward
to the board for election.
This constitutional review is the latest example of head-scratching going on
at Moorgate Place. Highly successful though the 111-year old institute may
be, it is in some ways an institution looking for a role.
The ICAEW's success is demonstrable. It has 87,000 active members - half of
whom work in industry and the other half in professional practice - giving
it unrivalled sway over British commercial life.
Every year a queue of thousands of the UK's cleverest graduates embarks on
the arduous training which ultimately leads to membership of the institute.
But the ICAEW is today suffering the consequences of its success. Its
membership is vast and heterogeneous. Sole practitioners, partners in Big
Six firms and finance directors of public companies, have little in common
except their member-ship of the institute and shared memories of the rigours
of the training contract.
The institute fulfils a number of different and not necessarily consistent
roles. It is a training body committed to maintaining excellence in new
entrants into the profession; a trade association, lobbying for the
interests of its members; and a disciplinary body, concerned to preserve the
highest professional standards among its members.
Increasingly, under first the Insolvency Act 1986 and the Financial Services
Act of the same year, and now the Companies Act 1989, it is a regulator as
well.
To the dispassionate observer, it is not clear that all these aims and
objectives are consistent with one another. The greatest conflict is between
its role as trade association and its new function as regulator.
Acting in what it then perceived to be the best interests of British
accountants, the institute originally lobbied against the requirement for
auditors to be monitored under the Companies Act 1989. It lost the argument
 -and is now fighting to be approved by the government as the body
responsible for doing the monitoring.
The ICAEW believes that its new regulatory responsibilities take precedence
over its trade-association functions, and in this it is undoubtedly sincere.
But the more vigorously it monitors its member firms, the more it risks
alienating them.
There is already one senior partner of a Big Six firm who privately says he
is so disillusioned with the institute that he would rather the monitoring
be taken over by a government agency like the Securities and Exchange
Commission in the US. After more than a century of self-regulation, this is
a heretical position to take, even in private.
Perhaps this is a tribute to the vigilance with which the ICAEW is carrying
out its new duties. But it is also a warning: to command respect of the
profession, the ICAEW must not get lost in internal politics. The abolition
of the president's advisory committee would be a good first step.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
