<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Stores' legal skirmishes likely to continue: An Appeal Court
decision making the law 'virtually unenforceable'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE shops are likely to open this Sunday as a result of Tuesday's Appeal
Court judgment. But the long-running Sunday trading debate looks as though
it will stagger on for many months to come.
The Appeal Court ruling that councils could not ban Sunday opening at
specific shops without guaranteeing to meet sales losses if a court
eventually ruled against the ban may have meant the 1950 Shops Act is
'virtually unenforceable', but it still does not change the fundamental law
in England and Wales, as Mr Peter Lilley, trade and industry secretary,
pointed out yesterday.
No new legislation is going to emanate from the government this side of a
general election to clarify the situation, and the two camps will therefore
have to continue their skirmishes through the courts and the newspaper
columns.
The great unknown in the debate is how any repeal of the law would affect
the number of shops trading on Sundays. Would a change in the law open the
floodgates?
The Keep Sunday Special Campaign (KSSC) argues that unrestricted Sunday
trading would lead to higher prices and a reduction of competition as a
result of the eclipse of the smaller independent traders.
It points to an Institute for Fiscal Studies report from 1985 which
suggested that longer opening hours would be likely to accelerate the trend
of the disappearance of the independent retailer.
The KSSC also refers to a speech made by Baroness Young, a non-executive
director of Marks and Spencer, in the House of Lords in 1989, when she
argued that Sunday trading would only mean that six days' trading would be
spread over seven days.
A 1989 report on the implications of Sunday trading, released by the
free-market Adam Smith Institute, suggested that any changes in retailing as
a result of Sunday trading were likely to be evolutionary rather than
revolutionary.
It accepted small traders might be squeezed, but questioned if this would be
a bad thing. 'All economic change must involve, of necessity, gainers and
losers. Small shopkeepers would lose, but consumers would gain from lower
prices or more attractive shopping environments,' it said.
A study of the Swedish experience of 20 years of Sunday trading confirms the
impression that some smaller players find difficulty in competing.
In Sweden about 80 per cent of all department stores and hypermarkets now
open on Sundays, compared with the 22 per cent that opened in 1972 when
trading restrictions were first repealed.
Over that period, the hypermarkets and larger supermarkets have increased
their share of the market, as have the small convenience stores. The
medium-sized shops have been squeezed in between.
But the report, which was challenged by the trade unions, showed that
deregulated shopping hours had led to 'increased downward pressure' on
consumer prices.
Mr Kevin Hawkins, corporate affairs director for WH Smith, the multiple
retailer that jointly owns the 220-store Do-It-All chain with Boots, said
that as a result of the Appeal Court judgment it would open those stores
where it had previously undertaken not to trade.
'Where we have closed a store we have found that the trade we lose on a
Sunday is not recouped on any other day of the week. It is purely
discretionary trade which knocks on the head the view that there is just so
much money that can go around,' Mr Hawkins said.
'If we had complete freedom it would be a case of suck it and see. The
important thing is that we would be able to open and close according to
consumer demand - which would vary seasonally and locally.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
