<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / The Blue Arrow Trial: Confusion over County guarantee -
Court Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FORMER County NatWest director yesterday told the Blue Arrow trial that
his memory was confused over any guarantee given by County to County NatWest
Securities, its market-making co-subsidiary, in connection with CNWS's Blue
Arrow stake taken in the 1987 rights issue.
Mr James Riddell, then County's financial control director, first told the
court he had always believed that no guarantee had been given to CNWS.
However, he was challenged by Mr Nicholas Purnell QC, prosecuting, about
references to a guarantee in notes he had written in early November 1987
after discussions with Mr Alan Keat, a solicitor with Travers Smith
Braithwaite and one of the defendants.
Asked why he had written that a guarantee could not be given to normal
market-making stock, Mr Riddell said he did not know. He then said that it
was an 'overall statement' which did not go into detail.
Later he said: 'You have demonstrated that at the beginning of November I
knew that there was one, but the significance of it did not impinge upon
me.'
Mr Purnell also challenged Mr Riddell on another note written after the
discussion with Mr Keat. This said if CNWS had a guarantee its holding could
no longer be regarded as trading stock, the market-makers exemption from
disclosure would not apply and aggregation would follow.
Mr Riddell said he had not considered aggregation was an issue because
appropriate legal advice had been taken. He had been looking at the matter
in an accounting framework, rather than a legal context.
Later, he told Mr Purnell he had understood the guarantee covered any losses
in bonuses earned by CNWS traders.
Mr Riddell also said that in his discussions with Mr Keat about the
end-of-year accounts, he had considered transferring shares from County to
NatWest, the parent bank. Asked about a discussion concerning the possible
backdating of the documentation for this, Mr Riddell said Mr Keat had told
him such tampering with documents was a criminal offence.
County NatWest, NatWest Investment Bank, UBS Phillips &amp; Drew Securities and
seven individuals all deny conspiring to mislead the markets over the
outcome of the Pounds 837m issue.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
