<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Ruling on late VAT payment
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
PERSISTENT DELAY by customers in settling debts can provide businesses with
a reasonable excuse for not paying value added tax on time, the High Court
ruled yesterday.
Mr Justice Kennedy upheld a decision by a VAT tribunal to cancel surcharges
imposed by the Commissioners of Customs on Mr John Steptoe, an electrical
contractor of Barkingside, Essex, for late payment of VAT.
Judge Medd, QC, tribunal chairman, had said 95 per cent of Mr Steptoe's work
was for Redbridge council in London, which, in 1987-88, was 'an extremely
slow payer'. Mr Steptoe been left without sufficient funds to meet VAT
bills.
Judge Medd said this was 'one of those rare cases' where the taxpayer might
legitimately put forward as a reasonable excuse 'the un-expected and
continuing conduct' of the person who caused the prolonged shortage of
funds.
Dismissing an appeal by the commissioners, Mr Justice Kennedy said the
question of what could be regarded as a reasonable excuse in such cases
could safely be left to the discretion of VAT tribunals.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
