<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Scots see no sign of upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S economy may have passed the moment of steepest decline in the
current recession. That is the view of the latest quarterly survey conducted
by chambers of commerce throughout Scotland and interpreted by the Fraser of
Allander Institute at Strathclyde University.
It adds that there is no sign of an upturn, and shows a continuing downward
trend in orders and sales in all sectors except for wholesale distribution.
The survey says demand for manufactured goods in England is depressed, but
that export markets are holding up better. It speaks of a relative
improvement in general business optimism, though levels are still low. The
improvement is attributed to the ending of the Gulf war and the fall in
interest rates, and is not matched by companies' reported sales and orders.
Much of the increased optimism is reported in Glasgow, but the Aberdeen area
shows the greatest buoyancy thanks to the oil industry's strength.
