   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF two UK-based companies on a US Treasury blacklist expressed surprise
last night at being named as one of the 'entities and agents of the
government of Libya'.
The company's comments follow publication on Tuesday of a list of 48
organisations, mostly based in Arab and Mediterranean countries, which the
Treasury Office of Foreign Assets and Control named as circumventing the US
embargo against Libya.
'We abide by British laws 100 per cent,' said Dr M Ageli, chief executive of
the Libyan-owned Umm Al-Jawaby Oil Service Company, of Cavendish Square,
London. He said the company cleared any trade with the Department of Trade
and Industry and had never had trading links with US corporations.
The second UK company named, Arabian Gulf Oil Company (Agoco) of Windsor
House, Victoria Street, London, is a wholly-owned subsidiary of National Oil
Corporation (Libya). It could not be contacted for comment.
The DTI said there was no embargo on British companies trading with Libya,
except under the provisions of the Export of Goods Control Order.
