<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Iraq 'promises multi-party poll': Ruling council to be
scrapped, Kurdish leader claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A KURDISH leader claimed last night that Iraqi officials had agreed to
abolish the ruling Revolutionary Command Council and hold multi-party
elections within six months.
Jalal Talabani, a member of the Iraqi Kurdistan Front which has been holding
talks with Baghdad on Kurdish autonomy, told the BBC from his base in
northern Iraq that 'a freely-elected parliament will function instead of all
other bodies'.
The Iraqi government has been promising in recent weeks to introduce more
democratic systems but has not previously outlined specific proposals nor
suggested scrapping the Revolutionary Command Council, which is essentially
an instrument of the ruling Ba'ath party.
There was no confirmation of the report from Baghdad. The ruling party has
come close to admitting that it has failed to address ethnic and sectarian
problems but an official announcement of plans to democratise the country
would still be treated sceptically by many Iraqis, given the history of
repression at the hands of the Ba'ath party. Party officials were seized and
killed during the unsuccessful Kurdish and Shia rebellion against President
Saddam Hussein in March following the Gulf war.
Concessions to democracy in Baghdad would be regarded as a big step forward
by Kurds in their battle for autonomy.
Jalal Talabani also said he had won an amnesty for Kurdish and Shia
prisoners captured during the rebellion.
He said last week agreement in principle had been reached with Baghdad on
implementing a 1970 autonomy accord between the government and the Kurds,
who form a fifth of Iraq's 18m population. Distrustful of Mr Saddam, the
Kurds want international guarantees for any final agreement.
</TEXT>
