<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Bush acts to beat N America trade pact
opponents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUSH Administration yesterday sought to shatter opposition to the North
American Free Trade Agreement (Nafta) by sending to Congress a sweeping set
of promises to satisfy concerns over US job losses and the environment.
The Administration's 'action plan' was released one month before Congress
must vote if it is to defeat President Bush's request for 'fast track' trade
authority. The 'fast track' gives him a free hand to negotiate
amendment-free treaties in the Uruguay Round, and with Mexico and Canada.
'Fast track lets us open up new markets and new opportunities,' President
Bush told the Society of American Business Editors and Writers yesterday.
'Fast track is another term for good faith. It means we will not tinker with
trade agreements worked out by our negotiators and their foreign
counterparts.'
Good faith is what the President is striving to win from a Congress that has
often seen its tough trade laws ignored by the administration. Informal
polls have shown widespread uncertainty in both houses on whether to trust
the administration to negotiate a pact which would protect US workers,
health and safety rules, and the environment.
The AFL-CIO, the nation's biggest labour organisation and a leading Nafta
opponent, yesterday released the first national poll on the proposed pact.
It found 56 per cent of the American public believing that a US-Mexico pact
would result in job losses and 72 per cent opposed to granting 'fast-track'
authority.
Until yesterday, the anti-'fast track' coalition - environmentalists, farm,
labour and consumer groups, and textile and apparel makers, was thought to
be gaining in the House but to be behind in the Senate. A majority in either
house can deny the president 'fast-track' authority.
The 'action plan' contains concessions which may well satisfy many of the
undecided. It promises to consider long transitions before cutting tariffs
on import-sensitive products and to negotiate mechanisms which would
re-instate the tariffs if imports surge.
It pledges strict, clear rules of origin, especially for assembled
automotive products; an 'adequately funded' retraining programme for those
that lose jobs because of Nafta; negotiation of joint action plans with
Mexico on labour issues, including improved working conditions, child labour
law enforcement, and health and safety measures, to be implemented in
parallel with Nafta negotiations.
Environmentalists are promised positions on trade policy advisory
committees; a bi-national programme of co-operation on environmental issues;
and a plan to address air and water pollution, hazardous wastes, chemical
spills, pesticides and enforcement. Sen Max Baucus, Senate trade
sub-committee chairman, yesterday said the plan went 'a long way' to address
congressional concerns. But a system still had to be devised for monitoring
and enforcing Mexico's environmental pledges.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1925</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAEEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Swedes boost attack on US steel duties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DULLFORCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SWEDEN has stepped up its attack on US anti-dumping duties on steel imports,
after Washington this week declined for the fourth time to implement a
ruling by a Gatt disputes panel.
The Swedes opened a new case by complaining to Gatt's anti-dumping committee
on Tuesday that the US was refusing to review anti-dumping duties imposed
almost 20 years ago on imports of stainless steel plate from Sweden.
Also, the Swedes charged the US was 'blatantly ignoring' Gatt's anti-dumping
code in pursuing a case against imports of anti-friction bearings from SKF,
the big Swedish roller bearings group. This case also involves German,
French and British exporters.
The message from Washington was that Gatt's rules for settling trade
disputes did not apply to the US, unless it wanted them to, a Swedish
Foreign Ministry official said. A disputes panel ruled last September that
the US had not followed Gatt anti-dumping rules when imposing duties on
imports of seamless stainless steel products from the Swedish company
Sandvik.
The US administration had acted at the request of only a few companies and
had not satisfied itself the request had been filed on behalf of the
domestic industry affected. The panel told the US to revoke the duty and
reimburse the company for more than Dollars 8m (Pounds 4.7m) it had already
paid.
The US administration has contested some of the panel's arguments,
challenged the panel's right to prescribe a specific remedy, and claims US
law prevents it complying with the panel's ruling.
Sweden asked for bilateral consultations - the first step to raising a
dispute in Gatt - with the US on the new dumping case. Avesta, one of the
biggest US domestic producers, had exhausted all the means available,
including the US Court of Appeals, to obtain a review of the anti-dumping
duties imposed in 1973, the Swedish official said.
Imports of hot rolled stainless steel plate from Sweden represented 0.2 per
cent of US consumption. In justifying the dumping charge in 1973, the US
contended the Swedes had maintained their exports to the US market during a
decline in demand for stainless steel plate in western Europe, their biggest
market.
Swedish exports to the EC grew 266 per cent between 1971 and 1985. Yet the
US authorities continued to argue that the information presented by Avesta
was insufficient to warrant a review of the dumping duties, the Swedish
official said. The US accepted the Swedish demand for consultations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1926</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAEDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Fizz goes out of champagne exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHAMPAGNE exports have gone flat as recession, rising prices and the Gulf
crisis have taken the fizz out of buyers' appetite for high-priced bubbles.
Shipments to the British market - traditionally the largest export outlet
for champagne - halved in the first three months of this year, as total
exports fell by 28 per cent to 12.2m bottles.
Germany, whose champagne consumption has in the past run at little more than
half the UK's, was the only country to record higher shipments in the first
quarter, with a rise of 3 per cent to 2.6m bottles making it for the first
time champagne's biggest export market.
The shipment figures may be distorted by dealers' running down stocks. But
even the depletion figures, which reflect actual sales, are expected to show
that there has been a substantial slip in consumption.
'The first phenomenon is the Gulf: for the first three months of the year
the big hotels and restaurants of London, places like the Dorchester, were
virtually empty, and the same is true around the world in places like the
Mamounia in Morocco,' comments Mr Frederic Heidsieck, export director of
Louis Roederer.
Mr Heidsieck also fears that champagne prices in many countries may have
reached or exceeded the levels that the trade has long regarded as
psychological limits: Pounds 15, BFr1,000 or DM50 a bottle.
If these thresholds have as much power as some shippers fear, drinkers may
turn to the high quality sparkling wines now produced in countries like
Spain and Australia - often by traditional French houses in search of
diversification.
Grape in these countries cost only FFr2.50 or FFr5 a kilogram, whereas in
Champagne grapes rose last year to a minimum of FFr32 a kilo, following the
ending of a trade agreement that had governed prices for 30 years.
However, champagne makers are putting a brave face on the plunge in
shipments. They say that many brands raised their prices by 10 to 15 per
cent on January 1, so dealers who had stocked up before this increase
reduced their orders as they sold off their old stock.
'It is clear the champagne market is less easy than it was, but the
situation is still not dramatic, and in April we began to feel the first
tremors of a revival,' commented an official of Moet et Chandon, the
champagne market leader.
Mr Claude Taittinger, head of the champagne house that bears his name and
chairman of the federation of French wine and spirits exporters, says: 'The
first quarter was not good, but we are now entering a new phase with some
reassuring phenomena.'
In any case, dwindling demand will probably not force champagne prices down.
Frost, which hit around 30 per cent of the Champagne area's vineyards last
month, seems likely to curb this year's supply enough to prevent any price
slump - even if many of the affected vines may flower again, and even if the
worst of the frost was in the lower quality Aube and Aisne districts, not in
the grand cru areas of the Marne.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
