<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / US denies Nato slowing EC progress on security
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SLOW progress in the European Community's negotiations on common security is
not the fault of Nato, Mr William Taft, the US envoy to Nato, said
yesterday. He rejected a complaint by Mr Jacques Delors, the European
Commission president, that EC security discussions were being held up by the
slower pace of parallel work in Nato.
In an interview, the US ambassador said Nato had in fact delayed its
alliance summit from July to the autumn 'because this would co-ordinate
better with the work of the inter-governmental conferences' on a common EC
security stance and other issues.
'This (delay) was a consistent desire by the EC countries' that belong to
Nato, Mr Taft said, adding that 'perhaps Mr Delors was not aware of this'.
However, at last weekend's meeting of EC foreign ministers, Mr Delors' call
for Nato to speed up its talks was echoed by Mr Jacques Poos, Luxembourg's
foreign minister.
The real debate over European security now seems to be shifting from the EC
to Nato, to confront the arguments which are being put with increasing force
by the US and which are strongly supported by Community states like Britain
and the Netherlands.
'We have told the Europeans that in our view the development of a European
security identity ought to strengthen the alliance, not compete with it, nor
duplicate it,' said Mr Taft.
He said Mr James Baker, the US secretary of state, stressed to EC foreign
ministers two weeks ago 'the essential character of Nato's integrated
military structure, the need to avoid marginalisation of any of the allies
(European countries outside the EC) and the desirability of the European
political union developing a capacity to engage beyond Europe's borders'.
Nato has agreed to boost its own rapid reaction force, but only for use
within alliance territory. The US, along with Britain and the Netherlands,
now sees a European rapid deployment force, acting probably under Western
European Union (WEU) auspices, as filling the 'out of area' role that Nato
cannot agree on for itself.
Last weekend, Mr Douglas Hurd, Britain's foreign secretary, was urging his
EC colleagues to think of setting up a permanent planning cell in the WEU,
even in peacetime. However, Mr Roland Dumas, his French counterpart,
dismissed all talk of such mechanisms in the WEU as secondary to the great
question of principle: whether Europe had the political will for common
defence.
France, in fact, has gone very silent on the WEU over which it currently
presides. It used its six-month presidency to convene a special 15-minute
meeting of the organisation in the margins of the EC summit on April 8,
ostensibly to give the WEU the task of co-ordinating aid to the Kurds but
mainly to show how it could have life inside the EC womb.
In fact, the WEU role in aid co-ordination has been virtually nil. By
contrast, France has, albeit belatedly, joined in the strategic review in
Nato.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
