<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / East German bonus for public officials attacked as grotesque
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENEROUS extra payments to west German beamte (public officials) to persuade
them to work in east Germany have been criticised as 'grotesque' by Mr
Heinrich Weiss, head of the BDI employers' organisation.
His unusually outspoken attack on 'interest group selfishness' comes a few
weeks after the Bonn government decided to offer the beamte a tax-free
monthly income top-up of up to DM2,500 (Pounds 836) as part of the new
emphasis on establishing an efficient administration in east Germany.
This incentive was offered despite the fact that beamte are meant to be
prepared to serve wherever the state decides. Mr Weiss points out in a
newspaper interview published today that they already enjoy special job
security and pension benefits to compensate for the uncertainty created by
that duty to the state.
The west German beamte are often described as arrogant and insensitive by
the east German public officials with whom they work and the extra payments
may well have increased resentment.
West German companies which have acquired east German subsidiaries are also
usually paying incentives to managers to go east, but these tend to be
proportionately lower than the beamte incentive.
The Treuhand privatisation agency continues to have great difficulty
attracting west German managers to help manage the east German companies
which cannot be privatised.
However, it emerged yesterday that Mr Lothar Spath, former premier of
Baden-Wurttemberg, will probably take over as chairman of the prestigious
east German Carl Zeiss Jena group, now owned by the Thuringian government.
</TEXT>
