<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Muted Moscow May Day
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RED SQUARE, traditionally a sea of red banners and rallies on May Day, saw
an extraordinarily low-key version of the workers' annual celebration.
Yesterday's proceedings were devoid of long speeches and were over in record
time, confirming the break-up of Communist supremacy.
Key Politburo members, such as Mr Vladimir Kryuchkov, KGB chief and Mr Boris
Pugo, interior minister, remained at the foot of Lenin's mausoleum, leaving
only President Mikhail Gorbachev on top with trade union speakers.
The leadership line-up on the mausoleum used to be scanned by
Kremlinologists for signs of any shift in the balance of power. Last year,
as political opposition began to flourish, Mr Gorbachev abruptly left the
podium after being booed.
The only link with the past yesterday was the mass of security men who kept
spectators from the mausoleum.
The march through Red Square, involving a few thousand well-dressed workers
and a brass band, was organised by Communist-controlled trade unions instead
of by the party.
Gone were complacent banners proclaiming the party's greatness. Instead the
marchers sought to convey to Mr Gorbachev their recipes for economic reform
(or hyperinflation) and their discontent over recent price rises.
The most ferocious party stalwarts to be seen came embarrassingly from its
loony fringe. A few hundred people carrying portraits of Josef Stalin called
for a people's court to try the country's leaders and condemned the idea of
market reforms.
'No to privatisation. The Counter-Revolution will not succeed,' said one
banner. Another called for the country's leading economists, such as
Professor Stanislav Shatalin to be put on trial for allegedly obeying the
'diktat' of the International Monetary Fund.
In Leningrad, the most eye-catching feature was a march by conservative
nationalists who displayed anti-Semitic banners. One banner accused
President Gorbachev and Mr Boris Yeltsin, the Russian leader, of being
frontmen for international Jewish capital and said they should be tried for
treason. Another suggested that Mr Yeltsin should run for president of
Israel.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1 Photograph Alternative May Day celebration. Boris Yeltsin,
President of the Russian Federation parliament, was visiting striking
Siberian miners instead of attending yesterday's traditional parade in Red
Square, Moscow. He addressed a May Day rally in the central square at
Novokuznetsk in western Siberia (Omitted).
</PAGE>
