<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (35): Favourite son returns - Polish Pope's
third visit next month
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POPE JOHN Paul II, Poland's most famous son, returns to his homeland for the
fourth papal visit next month. It will be his first visit to the new
post-communist, sovereign Poland which he did so much behind the scenes to
foster.
Nobody will forget the Polish pope's first triumphant return to his native
land in 1979. Millions turned out to greet him in a spontaneous outburst of
national pride and religious fervour, which definitively settled Stalin's
famous question, 'How many divisions has the Pope?'
A year later, Solidarity erupted from the same well-spring of revived
national energy, led by an alliance of catholic workers and catholic
intellectuals, whose faith and determination contrasted with and shamed the
bankrupt communistestablishment.
His two subsequent visits in 1983 and 1987 were altogether more sombre
affairs in the Poland of martial law. But both his presence and his close
following of Polish events helped keep alive the sense that one day Poland
would again be free.
The church, traditional repository of Poland's historical continuity and
culture, thrived in opposition to atheistic Marxism, and grew strong in
adversity. But the Poland the Pope returns to next month is a country in the
throes of transition to a market economy, multi-party democracy and a
'normal' (that is to say, western) consumer society. It is fast becoming a
'normal' society warts and all, including sex shops, openly displayed
pornography and many of the grosser forms of nouveaux riches exhibitionism -
liberating and enjoyable to some, sinful to traditional believers.
He will, of course, be welcomed. But it is unlikely to be the same as
before. Under communism, there was a clear distinction between church and
state. But in the new Poland the church is jockeying for power and influence
in ways which more secular Poles find increasingly irksome.
Successful church pressure to introduce religious instruction in schools,
and above all its campaign to change the country's liberal abortion laws,
are all controversial issues on views. So, however, do defenders of civil
rights, such as veteran dissident and former labour minister Jacek Kuron,
who is prepared to push for a national referendum on the abortion question.
Such issues threaten to embroil the Pope in the domestic political scene,
only months before elections in October, from which the church hopes to see
emerge a strong Christian democrat-type party at the heart of Polish
politics.
At a time when many Poles face the previously unknown perils of unemployment
and further economic hardship, his words will also be carefully weighed for
any direct or implied criticism of the government's present commitment to
the speediest possible transition to a market economy.
The liberal free-marketeers, currently in charge, reject the old distorted
communist welfare-state mentality. But to many, the old social safety-net
sits easier with traditional Christian charity than policies which
inevitably favour the fleet of foot at the expense of the lame.
The Pope's travels will take him through rural Poland, where the church is
strongest, and close to the eastern frontier. Thousands of catholics from
the Baltic states, Byelorussia and the Ukraine are expected to flock over
the borders to hear their spiritual leader. The church has its ost-politik,
too, and is busy restoring ties and rebuilding congregations in lands which
not long ago were part of Poland.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI Photograph Catholic Poland waits for the Pope's visit next
month (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1948</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (33): Life uncushioned - Industry's
problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BROAD SWATHES of Polish industry are now being squeezed between the hard
place of an appreciating currency and the rock of European Community import
restrictions, and the collapse of the Comecon market.
What is more, privatisation has hardly scratched the surface of Poland's
largely obsolete industrial enterprises, and the factors which allowed many
to survive bankruptcy are fast running out.
There is little question that much industry will either disappear or be
radically revamped in the coming months. The most vulnerable are those
concerns that relied heavily on the Soviet Union for cheap energy and raw
material inputs, and on Soviet and East German markets.
At least 200 large factories were dependent on Comecon markets for over 35
per cent of their business. Many in the engineering, electronics and
consumer-goods industries - producing goods as diverse as helicopters, light
aircraft, grain-dryers, machine tools and industrial plant of various kinds
 -have little chance of finding alternative outlets.
At the same time, the sharp decline in domestic consumption and investment
demand, and increasing competition from imported consumer goods (thanks to
virtual abolition of import tariffs and appreciation of the zloty over the
last 16 months) have also pushed many large enterprises close to bankruptcy.
The Star truck plant, employing 12,000 people, is but one example.
This is precisely what the government wants. The harsh truth, told by
finance minister Leszek Balcerowicz, is that too many inefficient
monopolistic enterprises have been able to keep going by extending
inter-factory credits, running down stocks bought at former
artificially-cheap prices, shedding labour and taking advantage of the
former artificially-low exchange rate to export, even when, as in the Soviet
case, the purchaser cannot or will not pay.
Most of these cushions no longer exist, and the coming months should see a
remorseless weeding out of an industrial structure which, by western
standards, is grossly deformed, with too many large, energy-inefficient and
labour-intensive industries and too few service, high-technology and
consumer industries.
A recent study by Professors Jeffrey Sachs and David Lipton showed that the
average Polish state-owned industrial enterprise employed 378 people,
against 80 in a sample of western economies; while no less than 58 per cent
of all such enterprises employed over 1,000 people, against 19 per cent in
the west. Nearly 20 per cent of all Polish workers were employed in
enterprises employing over 5,000 workers.
What this means, in effect, is that many small towns in Poland are virtually
company towns, with one or two enterprises acting as the source not only of
employment but of all social services, from housing to health and welfare.
The social and political consequences of closure are magnified, especially
as the severe national housing shortage makes labour mobility difficult.
In spite of the difficulties, the present government is adamant that many
such enterprises will have to be privatised, restructured or closed, and
their assets sold - hopefully, to budding entrepreneurs who can better use
of them. If not, it is setting up labour exchanges, job re-training schemes
and making the recently introduced unemployment pay system more selective,
to concentrate on the worst problem areas.
Despite the problems, some Polish enterprises appear to be adapting well to
difficult circumstances. The Polar domestic appliances company outside
Wroclaw, for example, has found that its former east German competitors are
no longer in the market. It raised exports to the west by 30 per cent last
year, and intends to keep up the pace, even though at current exchange rates
exports are only barely profitable.
In Lodz, home of a depressed textile industry, the recently privatised
Prochnik enterprise needs 200 extra workers to manufacture garments for the
German market, using imported German fabrics. It can't find them, despite an
official 60,000 unemployment level in the town. Textile manufacturer
RenaKord, a few kilometres away, relies less on cheap labour, and is
squeezed by the high price of imported raw materials, EC quotas and US
tariffs. Its ancient factories include many recently imported German
machines, and it is negotiating with a potential US partner.
Up to now, however, Poland has not been very successful in attracting
foreign capital for the vital task of industrial re-generation; though the
hope is that, with debt re-scheduling agreed and new investment laws and
financial institutions, this picture will change.
Foreign companies that have taken the plunge and bet on Poland's long-term
economic prospects include Asea Brown Boveri, which is modernising the power
generating-equipment industry, and Philips, which has taken 51 per cent of
Polam, the largest light-bulb company; while Fiat and General Motors have
proferred competing plans for large-scale investment in modernising the
motor industry.
Despite its current difficulties, Poland has a very cheap and relatively
well educated workforce, proximity to EC markets and, above all, its own
domestic market of nearly 40m hitherto frustrated consumers. It is well
placed to absorb the large-scale investment, which is needed not only to
bring its industry up to international levels but also to improve the rail,
road, telecommunications and other infrastructures.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV Photograph Tadeusz Michlewski, managing director of the Lodz
textile company RenaKord (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1949</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (34): Catching up with information - Review
of changes in control of the media
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL Poland's newspapers were once owned by RSW Prasa, one of Europe's
largest publishing concerns. Their profits went to RSW's owner - the
Communist Party.
Newspapers, as well as radio and TV, were run by the Communist Party's press
department and the system was as simple as one-party rule itself.
Dismantling it has been a more complex business.
Disposing of RSW's assets has been the responsibility of a seven-man
liquidating committee set up by an Act of parliament last year. In its
heyday the concern employed 85,000 people, owned 22,500 newspaper kiosks and
25 printing works and brought out 160 newspapers and journals.
Breaking up this empire has been a controversial process with political,
financial and even foreign policy considerations all being brought into play
as editors and journalists, as well as hopeful owners and politicians, have
fought for control of the papers.
Mr Maciej Ilowiecki, the head of the SDP, a journalists' association, is
highly critical of the way the sales have been conducted. He argues that the
reasons for decisions have not been explained to the public. He is also
concerned that Poles often knew too little about potential foreign buyers
and their real intentions.
New political parties such as the Christian Democrat Centre Agreement have
schemed to win control of organs like the Express Wieczorny, the Warsaw
working man's favoured evening reading. The politicians primarily wanted
influence. But last year also showed that with the growth of revenues from
advertising newspapers have become profitable.
Mr Robert Hersant, the right-wing French publisher of Le Figaro, has emerged
as the most significant foreign buyer. He has taken substantial shares in
six newspapers, including Rzeczpospolita, once the government's own
newspaper.
He has also bought titles in key local centres such as Gdansk and Lodz and
intends to bid for dailies in Katowice, the country's largest industrial
area.
expensive. The Dziennik Baltycki in Gdansk, which showed a profit last year
of 4bn zlotys (USDollars 430,000), cost Mr Hersant 12bn zlotys. In this case
the group has a 51 per cent share. The balance is owned by Solidarity's
Gdansk region, a politically powerful if impecunious partner.
Mr Hersant's right-wing views have stood him in good stead on his shopping
spree in Poland's present political climate, and a measure of French
influence has been seen as a good thing in the light of residual fears of
Germany.
Mr Robert Maxwell, the British publisher, has had less luck. He has suffered
from his previous connections with high-ranking East European communists,
whose biographies he published in his World Leaders series.
He failed to buy a share in Zycie Warszawy, a leading Warsaw daily, which
was sold recently for 40bn zlotys after an epic political battle. The
successful bidder was Mr Kazimierz Woycicki, the present editor, who amassed
an impressive array of letters of support from President Walesa downwards.
Much of the finance came from STEI, a small media group from Sardinia.
The RSW sale is now almost over and when it ends some 102 journals will have
been sold and another 61 handed over to co-operatives formed by the
journalists themselves.
But as the dust settles another even more intense competition is about to
start as franchises are awarded for private radio and TV broadcasts.
Literally hundeds of applications have been sent to the ministry of
communications, and more are expected before the June 10 closing date.
The flow started ahead of draft legislation de-monopolising the broadcast
media which is on its way through parliament. It will vest decisions on the
granting of broadcast rights in a special committee - part appointed by
parliament and part by the president.
Foreign participation in any company wishing to broadcast in Poland is
limited to 33 per cent. But private channels wanting to compete with state
TV will need foreign financing. RTL of Luxembourg, as well as Silvio
Berlusconi's Fininvest group of Italy, have demonstrated interest.
'Foreign visitors tend now to be showing an interest in tall buildings,'
says Mr Andrzej Jonas, editor of the English language Warsaw Voice weekly.
They are looking for places to put their broadcasting equipment.
One domestic group bidding for a licence is Independent Polish TV (NTP),
which groups Polish companies ranging from publishers to film studios and it
estimates it will need Dollars 60m in its first year.
While newspaper readership has held up surprisingly well, given rising costs
and the collapse of the distribution network in the smaller towns and the
countryside, it is TV and radio which is literally providing access to every
household.
A recent survey done by OBOP, state radio and TV's research centre, shows
that 100 per cent of the population have access to a TV set, with 63 per
cent watching in colour. Around 97 per cent have access to a radio.
Meanwhile, 10 per cent of the population have access to satellite TV
programmes (often thanks to small local cable networks) a figure which has
grown from 1 per cent a year ago. Futhermore, 28 per cent of all households
have access to video recorders, more than double last year's figure.
Mr David Chase, a rich financier from the US, has embarked on an ambitious
venture to install cable TV throughout the country. He plans to invest up to
Dollars 1bn and once the project is under way is counting on an annual
revenue of around Dollars 340m. In the information sphere at least Poland is
catching up fast.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
