<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (32): Back to the start of his road -
Profile: Zbigniew Bujak - What has happened to Solidarity?  FT writers trace
the evolution of the movement and discuss the future of trade unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ZBIGNIEW BUJAK was an almost legendary figure in the 1980s as the
clandestine leader of the Solidarity underground in Warsaw during martial
law. On one celebrated occasion he wore a long, blond wig for a clandestine
TV interview to demonstrate the range of disguises which kept the secret
police always one step behind.
Like many other colleagues now in positions of authority, he has failed to
reap the rewards of the risks he took then. Indeed, he has found himself
once more at the beginning of his political road, as he seeks to build a
social democratic alternative to the government's policies.
'I am quite alone,' he says, sitting in a sparsely furnished office a floor
above the Stefan Batory Trust, a foundation set up by Mr George Soros, the
rich American-Hungarian financier, which Mr Bujak chaired until recently.
Mr Bujak, now in his mid-30s, first became involved in politics as a young
worker at the Ursus tractor factory in the late 1970s. He had links with the
dissident KOR movement set up by Adam Michnik, Jacek Kuron and others to
defend workers' rights during the repression which followed the 1976 worker
protests. When the Solidarity trade union suddenly burst upon the scene in
1980, he was elected its leader in Warsaw.
After martial law, he was one of the movement's national leaders until his
arrest in 1986. Then he espoused free-market views, and when the Solidarity
movement re-emerged in 1989 he wanted the trade union to do little more than
smooth the way to a purely entrepreneurial society.
'I was a liberal at the beginning, and I believed that this would be enough
to improve the situation of the companies and thus the employees,' he says.
He saw Solidarity as acting as a giant labour exchange, helping industry to
restructure and to defuse the discontent provoked by the economic costs of
transition.
He did not go into parliament but supported the previous Mazowiecki
government, adopting a fiercely anti-Walesa stance during last autumn's
presidential election.
Yet even before the election, he felt that the government was not doing
enough to support the formation of Polish capital, and that this was
contributing to the growth of fears about foreign capital.
But it was during the presidential campaign that Mr Bujak noticed the growth
of opposition to economic change. 'The situation of the workers and the
farmers wasn't improving, and this marks a threat for the whole programme,'
he says.
During the election he also noticed that he had lost contact with the shop
floor. 'My people at Ursus told me that, by supporting the Balcerowicz plan
(the Government's IMF-approved anti-inflation programme), I had betrayed
them.' He realised also that people were beginning to fear the privatisation
programme. Now, he argues that something must be done to help state-sector
companies to perform better and leave privatisation for later.
He explains his search for social democratic solutions as a way of trying to
rebuild support for the economic reforms before they are, in his view,
rejected altogether.
'Poland needs a programme which stands a chance of winning popular support
and that explains the social democrat option,' he says, adding that his
ultimate aim is still to rebuild a market economy.
He sees the left-wing parliamentary post-Solidarity 'Solidarnosc Pracy'
group, led by Mr Richard Bugaj, as a potential ally, as well as the
moderates in the small Polish Socialist party (PPS) led by Mr Jan Jozef
Lipski, another KOR veteran. He admits lack of funds means that these groups
have little influence at the moment.
But he is no longer afraid that his views mean he will be criticised for
being crypto-communist. He thinks that communism's negative connotations are
beginning to fade and believes it is no longer politically dangerous to be
considered left of centre. He even predicts that the SdRP, the
post-communist party, will get a 15 per cent share of the vote in the autumn
parliamentary election.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV Photograph Zbigniew Bujak addressing students in Warsaw
during the heady days of Solidarity in the early 1980s (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
