<DOCNO>FT911-1951</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (31): Guardian of the reforms - What has
happened to Solidarity?  FT writers trace the evolution of the movement and
discuss the future of trade unions / The resignation of Lech Walesa, so long
the symbol of Solidarity, to take up the post of president of Poland, was a
turning point for the union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOLIDARITY, the alliance of workers and intellectuals that was born in
Gdansk's Lenin shipyard in 1980 and helped to oust communism across eastern
Europe, has been forced to re-examine its role in the new democratic Poland.
It has decided to return to its roots as a trade union.
The election of computer scientist Marian Krzaklewski as Solidarity's new
chairman, at its February congress, was seen as an endorsement of that move.
Mr Krzaklewski said in his speech to the congress: 'I am convinced that the
union chairman should remain outside political arrangements and pressures by
various political centres.'
The resignation of Lech Walesa, so long the symbol of Solidarity, to take up
the post of president of Poland, was a turning point for the union. Mr
Slawomir Rogucki, secretary of Solidarity's newly-created presidium, admits
the union finds itself in a contradictory position.
'On the one hand, it has to be a union, and its charter says it has to
defend the workers. On the other, Solidarity is still responsible for the
fate of the reforms started two years ago,' he says.
'It's difficult to reconcile these two different roles, especially in a
situation where the quality of life of many workers has fallen.'
This can bring the union into conflict with the government. Solidarity is,
for example, pressing for the abolition of the punitive tax on excessive
wage increases - which has resulted in workers' wages falling in real terms
 -in the second half of this year, with enterprises allowed to link
tax-exempt wage increases with higher productivity.
The wage tax is a pillar of the finance minister Leszek Balcerowicz's
anti-inflation policy, the backbone of his whole economic programme.
As many people have suffered under the Balcerowicz plan, the pro-communist
trade union OPZZ and what Mr Rogucki describes as the 'post-communist
forces' still enjoy support in Poland. 'They use populist slogans,' Mr
Rogucki says. 'They don't feel responsible for the state of the country.'
In the light of this threat, Solidarity feels it cannot relinquish its role
as guardian of the reforms until Poland has reached full parliamentary
democracy.
'We started this process, we have to finish it. But we don't wish to usurp
the right of the government to rule. We don't wish to dominate. Solidarity
must point out the mistakes of the government,' Mr Rogucki says.
The difficulty is finding the balance, and not hindering the growth of
opposition parties. Mr Rogucki points out that in a state conditioned to
one-party rule, there is a danger that Solidarity might come to be regarded
automatically as the sole power.
Despite arguments from some delegates that Solidarity should take full
responsibility for the reform process in Poland, and field candidates for
all seats in the parliament, the union eventually voted to participate in
the elections later this year, but not field enough candidates to risk
winning an overall majority.
It will, however, support the political parties that have grown out of it.
Mr Rogucki sees Solidarity remaining as a single, united movement, rather
than splitting into separate unions representing different trades and
professions, although it is to be restructured. Fifteen different trade
secretariats, with secretaries belonging to a national executive committee,
will replace the current structure of 100-plus regional organisations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV Photograph Lenin shipyard, Gdansk, birthplace of Solidarity,
the alliance of workers and intellectuals that helped to oust communism
(Omitted).
</PAGE>
