<DOCNO>FT911-1952</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (30): A bout of schizophrenia - What has
happened to Solidarity?  FT writers trace the evolution of the movement and
discuss the future of trade unions / The right to set up and join a trade
union is retained in legislation now before parliament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORKERS, mobilised into the Solidarity movement, brought down Poland's
so-called 'workers state'. Yet, as the country reverts to capitalist free
markets and unemployment threatens to exceed 2m, the future of the trade
union movement is in dispute.
Both Solidarity and the communist-created OPZZ union federation, set up
during martial law to counter its influence, are, for differing reasons
suffering an identity crisis, and it could be some time before new unions
emerge.
Ironies abound. Solidarity, in its heyday in 1981 was a worldwide symbol of
free trade unionism. Now it is wracked by its dual role as it seeks to
defend the immediate interests of its 2.5m members and support the
Government's austerity policies.
The OPZZ had similar problems in the past. Under the Communists it made
militant gestures but was bound in the end by its party affiliation to
support the government.
Now the OPZZ is in opposition and could face the confiscation of its
property, as once happened to Solidarity, should the next parliament have a
strongly right wing hue.
The OPZZ has 5m members on the books, but only a fifth pay dues, and its
credibility is low, even though its expertise on bread and butter issues is
better than Solidarity's. Opinion polls show that its leader, Mr Alfred
Miodowicz, a former Communist Politburo member, enjoys little popular
confidence. In the factories Solidarity, although sometimes smaller is often
more effective.
Both movements want to play a more overt political role trade unions,
putting up candidates at the next elections and hoping to put together
coalitions to defend their interests.
Solidarity is now headed by Mr Marian Krzaklewski,a scientific researcher
from Silesia. He replaced Mr Lech Walesa at February's Solidarity congress
and is wary of his union allowing itself to be used by the fledgling
political parties now seeking his support.
Solidarity is suffering from a severe bout of schizophrenia. Its activists
feel responsible for the success of the economic reforms which they
initiated but which are now causing discomfort to their members as real
incomes fall.
On the other hand, the 20,000 or so full-time Solidarity officials at the
national and factory level feel they are the new establishment and are
becoming accustomed to giving orders.
'Remember, lady, this is Solidarity calling' an irate shop steward told a
minister's secretary when she informed him he could not be put through on
the telephone. But 'sometimes they know they have to threaten strike action
because the members want something done, but they're loathe to do it because
they see strikes as being aimed at themselves,' an official in Gdansk says
of his colleagues.
Strikes are not popular. Fear of unemployment and the precarious situation
of state sector companies mean that on the whole people do not see the
point. Instead Solidarity has had to rely on influencing the Government
through private channels while the OPZZ has organised a series of rallies
against Government economic policies. Neither method has been very
effective.
Indeed, the ballot box has been a better instrument of making people's views
known. At the presidential election last autumn, the defeat of Premier
Tadeusz Mazowiecki and a strong vote for Stanislaw Tyminski, a vehement
critic of the Solidarity establishment, showed many people's attitudes.
Despite the decline of the strike as a weapon, the right to set up and join
a trade union, as well as to strike, is retained in trade union legislation
now being amended by Parliament. This could cause embarrassment to foreign
employers like the Marriott hotel chain which has a policy of not permitting
employees to organise unions. But the maximum fine for the offence is a mere
Zl 5m (USDollars 537).
Still to be decided is whether employers will have the right to lock workers
out in the face of a wildcat strike.
During the debates in parliament the Solidarity leadership from Gdansk was
reduced to passively asking deputies and senators for support. This has
enhanced Solidarity's perceived need to get its own limited parliamentary
representation and led some to argue that it should go further and seek to
become part of future governments.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
