<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (29): Perilous pollution problem - The
scale of environmental woes is daunting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH in the Sudeten mountains, the forest is dying. One or two lone, grey
skeletons of trees stand stripped of their foliage, surrounded only by tree
stumps stretching away up the hillside.
Caught in the crossfire of air pollution from Czechoslovakia to the south,
and Upper Silesia to the north, the forest is a victim of rain with a pH
value measured at 2.8 on occasions - the equivalent of medium-strength acid.
Upper Silesia, the centre of Poland's coal mining and heavy industry, is
just one of five regions designated 'areas of environmental disaster' by the
Polish government in 1983.
Twenty-two others were classed as 'areas of environmental hazard'. Together
they account for 11 per cent of the land and more than a third of the
population.
The scale of Poland's environmental woes is daunting. Poles suffer an
abnormally high rate of chronic bronchitis and asthma from inhaling polluted
air. They are exposed to some of the highest dosages of carcinogens in the
world through eating food grown on soil contaminated with metal deposits.
By 1987, 95 per cent of surface water was unfit for human consumption, while
30 per cent was so heavily salinated by discharges from the mining industry
that it was as to be unfit even for industrial use.
Although the problems were recognised in the 1980s, only now is the
government able to start to confront them, helped by loans from the World
Bank, the European Community, the US and Sweden.
When the Paris Club of western creditor nations cut Poland's official debt
by 50 per cent earlier this year, the US unilaterally reduced a further 10
per cent, and agreed that another 10 per cent (Dollars 380m) would be
converted into Polish zlotys and spent on environmental projects.
The government hopes to spend a total of Dollars 1.5bn on environmental and
water supply investment in 1991, triple three times the former annual
expenditure. But the gap between what can realistically be spent in the
1990s and what is internationally called for is reckoned to be more than
Dollars 1bn a year.
To bridge the gap, Dr Maciej Nowicki, the environment minister, called in
March for a trust fund to be set up - with money diverted from servicing
Poland's foreign debt - to provide financial support to projects of
international importance. These would include controls on trans-boundary air
pollution and contamination of the Baltic Sea.
At home, new environmental laws are expected to be enacted by parliament
before the summer recess, and the government is already implementing its
environmental protection programme drawn up at the end of last year.
Underpinning the programme is the principle of 'sustainable development' to
attain a balance between social, economic, technical and environmental
conditions and development.
In practice this means investment in the treatment of pollution at source,
and the reduction of polluting industries when restructuring of the economy.
The programme stresses the efficient use of energy. Assistant Professor
Stanislaw Sitnicki, director of strategy at the Ministry of Environmental
Protection, believes that energy consumption could be cut by 20 per cent.
To this end, the Polish Foundation for Energy Efficiency was founded last
year, with sponsorship from the US government, the World Wildlife Fund
Worldwide Fund for Nature and the Conservation Foundation. Two centres in
Warsaw and Katowice will conduct research and provide training and
education, as well as advising on joint ventures.
The planned legislation will include punitive fines for polluters, and a new
'no excuses' approach. Previously many enterprises negotiated special
exemptions, or under the old accounting system were able simply to budget
for paying fines as part of their production costs.
More important, polluters will not just merely be fined, but will be held
financially responsible for the environmental damage they cause.
The ministry of environmental protection is embarking on an education
programme, which will stretch as far as mounting a special exhibition for
members of parliament.
Politicians are eager to talk about abortion, complains Mr Sitnicki, but are
not so interested in the environment. He adds that there is also a lack of
understanding of environmental problems among the general public, but not
necessarily of their scale.
Short-term priorities in the environmental programme are to tackle problems
which place human health - or life - at risk. Food production in areas such
as Upper Silesia, where the soil is affected by toxic substances, will be
gradually phased out, with compensation paid to farmers forced to switch to
different crops.
The 80 biggest polluters in Poland, identified in a government study last
year, have been set strict targets for reducing pollution by 1994-5. In the
medium term, it is hoped that Poland will come near to reaching EC pollution
targets by 2000. the turn of the century.
However, the picture is not all black. Twenty-seven per cent of Poland's
land area is virtually unspoiled, including one of the last areas of
primeval forest in Europe. to the east. Protecting these areas  - home to
bison, lynx and the occasional bear - is crucial. a major priority.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1954</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (28): A brick-shaped future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT THE Jaworzno colliery, in Upper Silesia, the director placed a small
cardboard box on the table.
'This,' said Mr Szczepan Perek, with pride, 'is the future of our coal
mine.'
Inside was a neat package of briquets of coal.
'Ecological fuel,' said Mr Perek triumphantly.
Smokeless fuel has been known for many years in the west, but in Poland it
is a new concept. In the case of the Jaworzno colliery, 20km west of
Katowice, it is hailed as a saviour, and proof that the future is not bleak
for all Polish mines.
Jaworzno, like the Polish constitution, celebrates its 200th anniversary
this year. But in February last year, after the colliery had been told that
the sulphur content of its coal was too high, it seemed that 4,000 of its
7,500 workers would have to be laid off.
Half a million tonnes of coal remained in store, deemed unfit for use under
Poland's stiff new laws.
Now the jobs have, apparently, been saved. The mine has exercised its right
to operate independently, and has become one of the first in Poland to
co-operate with western companies in safeguarding its future.
The mine is investing in desulphurising and enriching equipment, as well as
briquetting machinery, from Charbonnages de France, the German Helter
company, and Andritz of Austria. Along with credit from these companies, it
has received financial support from the State Coal Agency, and from the
national fund for environmental protection.
The new briquets are smokeless, low in sulphur, and, claims Mr Perek, burn
for five hours.
The product is aimed primarily at domestic consumers, and Mr Perek sees a
huge potential market, particularly in cities like Krakow, which has 240,000
individual chimneys from coal stoves.
Atmospheric pollution there is causing severe erosion of the historic
buildings.
Since the final quarter of last year, when the colliery announced that it
could in future supply desulphurised coal, Mr Perek says the Jaworzno
colliery has been inundated with orders.
When he speaks, Mr Perek already sounds like a manager in the west. 'We've
got the product, now we've got to find the market,' he says. 'We've wised up
to the market.'
Earlier, he had betrayed more than a trace of the old thinking. Unlike most
capitalists, who would be happy to talk about the signing of their latest
deal, Mr Perek and his colleagues had been most reluctant to talk.
Only after half an hour of small-talk over one or two bottles of Czech beer
did Mr Perek let out his secret.
Now he was warming to his subject.
'We are deeply convinced that we are moving in the right direction. We are
introducing new technology and helping the environment, and we feel good
about that.'
Despite the uncertainties facing the industry as a whole, Mr Perek displays
every confidence in the future of his own mine.
'We are a mine that has many years ahead. Our coal is good, and we have 270m
tonnes of reserves - that's enough for 200 years at current production
levels.'
Although the mine took its own initiative in buying new technology, Mr Perek
supports the controversial plans of the State Coal Agency to create a
national holding company.
'We are happy about it. We've seen it happen in other countries.
'Looking realistically, one mine cannot function on its own in the market.
We can do it in the Polish market, but in the EC pack we would be eaten
alive.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1955</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (27): Quality not quantity - Coal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COAL miners, once the proletarian elite of Polish socialism, now face an
uncertain future. The subsidies which severely distorted production and
consumption of Poland's main source of energy are to be phased out.
Reducing Poland's reliance on coal - it accounts for more than 75 per cent
of primary energy consumption compared with 24 per cent in western Europe
and 27 per cent in the US - is also a significant plank in the country's
environmental protection programme.
Output has already dropped to 147.4m tonnes last year from the claimed peak
of more than 190m tonnes in the late 1980s. This year production is likely
to be only 144m tonnes.
Mr Tadeusz Demel, general director of the State Coal Agency, says the
industry will shift its emphasis from quantity to quality - and
profitability.
Mines will no longer be kept open simply to provide employment. Many of
Poland's 68 mines are old and highly inefficient, and a study is under way
to establish which are no longer viable.
Mr Demel refuses to disclose how many mines might face closure. Last year,
48 enjoyed what he describes as a 'positive financial status' after paying
dividends and income tax. But that, he says, does not mean they are
profitable overall because the figures exclude investment costs.
Declining heavy industrial production has already meant a decline in
domestic demand. But exports also face a crisis.
Mr Jan Baranski, director of Weglokoks, the Polish coal export agency, says
rising production costs, the combination of a fixed exchange rate and high
domestic inflation, and a 20 per cent turnover tax on exports, mean that
prices may have to be increased this year.' We've reached break-even point,'
he says. 'If our costs increase much more, without a change in the exchange
rate, we'll have no choice but to increase prices.'
If this happens, Mr Baranski fears a large drop in sales - worth around
Dollars 1.5bn last year - with possible long-term consequences. Weglokoks
may try to ride out the storm by concentrating on markets closest to Poland,
thus reducing transport costs.
'To lose a market is very easy,' he says. 'To come back is very difficult,
even if it's possible at all. We must not burn the bridges we have built up
over many years.'
At home, miners who lose their jobs will face difficulties in moving to
other areas to find work because of Poland's acute housing shortage. Those
still in work have come to terms with the fact that they are no longer the
storm-troopers of socialism.
'I am first a Catholic, and then the general director of the coal agency,'
Mr Demel says. 'Closing these mines will not be easy for me. I'm not a
politician, I am just a mining engineer. I live here and I have to look
these people in the eyes.'
There is already unrest among miners. The wages tax or popiwek that
penalises employers who pay more than government-permitted wage increases
means that miners' wages have not kept pace with inflation. This has already
led to strikes and angry delegations to president Walesa.
However, without lower real wages unemployment would be greater, as in the
former East Germany.
The ending of subsidies is a key to establishing real cost and profit levels
in the industry. Last year, 9,600bn zlotys (Dollars 1bn) was spent on
subsidising coal output. This year, the subsidy will be reduced to 7,300bn
zlotys.
The goal is to end the system of flat-rate subsidies to all mines based on
output, and switch to limited subsidies to specific mines for specific
reasons.
Finally, Poland's coal mines, which gained their freedom to operate
independently last year, are to be taken under the wing of a new state
holding company, along the lines of those that exist in many western
countries.
'It is stupid to maintain that individual mines, of differing ages and
working in very different conditions, should compete against one another,'
Mr Demel says.
Understandably, some miners are strongly opposed to the move, suspicious
that it will mean a return to the bad old days of central planning. The
workers' councils are reluctant to give up their newfound freedom.
'Sometimes I speak at mines to explain my ideas, and the miners whistle and
stomp,' Mr Demel says. 'I say, I don't have to be here. Someone else, one of
you, could be here, and you would start to think the same as me.'
No-one wants to see a return to the old ways, especially as a few truths are
starting to emerge. There is some doubt, for example, over whether Poland's
coal industry was ever quite as big as was claimed.
'Speaking delicately, there were certain discrepancies when coal output was
measured, ' Mr Demel says quietly.
'During the times of central planning, mines would add stones to their coal
to make sure they met their targets. I have worked in the coal industry for
many years, I know what went on.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII Photograph Once the proletarian elite, coal miners now face
an uncertain future (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1956</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (26): Protest vote by miners - An analysis
of the so-called Tyminski effect
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOWHERE was the so-called 'Tyminski effect' more marked than in the
voivodship of Walbrzych, where in some areas more than 40 per cent of people
voted for him in both rounds of the presidential elections.
In the first round, Mr Stan Tyminski beat Lech Walesa in more than a quarter
of the 40 constituencies in the region. The president of the city's public
relations office carried out an investigation into who voted for him.
'He found that 80 per cent of those who voted for him were people who had
only primary education, or only a technical education,' according to Adam
Gierak, a journalist with the left-wing newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza who lives
in the area. 'He also found that people who voted for Tyminski often did not
have the courage to admit it, or could find no reason to justify it.'
Mr Gierak says Tyminski voters could be divided into two distinct groups.
The first was people in the worst economic situation, especially miners who
have been hit hard by the Balcerowicz plan, and who face likely redundancy.
He feels this group voted for Mr Tyminski out of desperation, as a protest,
rather than making a positive and constructive choice to do so.
The second group was more influential - members of the pro-communist trade
union OPZZ, as well as members of the old party nomenklatura, and even
secret police.
Such people were apparently looking to regain some of their former power, Mr
Gierak says, and decided to back Mr Tyminski because they felt he stood more
chance of winning the election than the Social Democratic (the former
Communist Party) candidate Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz.
'Tyminski said he would come here at 4pm,' Mr Gierak says. 'But in fact he
came early in the morning for a secret meeting with OPZZ and former party
officials.'
Mr Gierak found out about this secret meeting and went along. He managed to
tape the opening, before he was discovered, thrown bodily out of the
meeting, and locked in a room until the meeting was finished.
'Later in the day, Mr Tyminski had dinner at the home of one of the OPZZ
trade unionists,' Mr Gierak adds. 'The neighbours heard about the meeting
and gathered outside the house, demanding to see Tyminski. When he came out
they feted him like a hero.'
Mr Tyminski also held an election rally, which followed the same pattern as
those held in many cities in Poland. A frail old lady came forward from the
audience, complaining about how she could scarcely afford to live on her
meagre pension. She pledged her support for Mr Tyminski, kissing his hands
and calling him 'saviour'.
A friend of Mr Gierak who was at election rallies in both Walbrzych and
Wroclaw, 70 km away, said the same old woman came forward at both meetings.
In the second round of voting, however, there was a heavy swing to Mr
Walesa, who won every constituency.
Mr Gierak says this was due to heavy pressure from the church for people to
vote for Mr Walesa, as well as what he calls a 'resurgence of patriotism'.
When it came to the crunch, the people felt Poland should be run by a native
Pole.
He doubts whether there could be a repeat of the Tyminski phenomenon. Were
it not for the uncertainty about the future of the region, and Solidarity's
failure to come up with a programme of restructuring, he says, most people
would probably never have voted for him.
In the next election, Mr Gierak believes, the alternatives to Solidarity
will be better formed, and be able to present more coherent policies. 'Once
a credible opposition emerges, no one will vote for someone like Tyminski,'
he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
