<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (24): A step into yesteryear - Walbrzych
typifies problems faced by eastern Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WOULD be difficult to imagine a town with more problems than Walbrzych,
in south-west Poland - or one that better illustrates the scope of the
problems faced by eastern Europe.
Coal is the main source of employment and the main source of fuel, and here
lies the problem.
Four hundred metres beneath the town, miners toil in some of the most
primitive mining conditions in Europe, crawling along tunnels only 70cm
high.
'Stepping into one of those mines is like stepping back into the 19th
century,' says Mr Pawel Kuczynski, of the social and market research firm
Demoskop, which has been involved in drawing up plans for the restructuring
of the region.
The miners have long been well-rewarded for their work, proud to wear their
distinctive uniforms. But their glory days are over.
The coal mines are finally to be closed - more than 50 years late. Scheduled
for closure even before the second world war, when Walbrzych was the German
town of Waldenburg, the mines were kept open for the war effort and then,
when the land passed to Poland after the war, for 45 loss-making years to
provide employment.
More than 23,000 people - a quarter of the workforce, and nearly a sixth of
the town's population - must eventually lose their jobs.
Poland's shortage of housing means the miners cannot be relocated elsewhere,
even though there is work available in other parts of Upper Silesia.
For the miners, redundancy will represent a particular fall from grace. They
are used to being pampered by the state - especially during the martial law,
when their special shops gave them access to goods other people could not
get.
As they were paid so well, it is more common for a miner to be the sole
breadwinner in a family than in other industries, and very few wives work. A
big change in social attitudes will be required.
The rest of the region's industry is none too healthy. The textile factories
have lost much of their main market - the Soviet Union - while the
electronics industry is having difficulty competing with western imports.
Only one out of three porcelain factories in the area is near to being
profitable.
As some enterprises close, and others seek to streamline themselves in the
battle for profitability, thousands more jobs are likely to be lost. The
socio-economic problems are, however, only the beginning.
The town suffers from some of the most severe water and atmospheric
pollution in Europe. Gases and dust from coal-burning and the huge Walbrzych
coking plant - high on the government's hit-list of the most polluting
enterprises in the country - cause acid rain, as well as respiratory
problems.
A serious shortage of water means that in some parts of Walbrzych there is
running water for only two hours a day. Of the region's river water, 2 per
cent is of 'second-class' quality, according to Polish standards. The rest
is not even suitable for industrial use.
In such conditions, health experts say, there is a high cancer risk and
danger of outbreaks of food-related illness such as salmonella. Along with
the threat of cancer, some experts fear that the high quantities of
carcinogens in the air and in food grown in the region could damage
inhabitants' immunological barriers, by attacking the T-cells, or so-called
'soldier cells' of the body's immune system, in a similar way to the Aids
virus.
Then there is the subsidence. In their desperation to keep miners in work,
the authorities allowed them to mine into the supportive pillars beneath the
town of Walbrzych. The walls of residential blocks have started to crack,
and one railway bridge has already sunk 10 feet into the ground. The town
centre itself has been undermined, and even divine patronage has not been
able to prevent the spire of the Church of the Guardian Angels from starting
to lean.
Worst of all is the uncertainty. It has been announced that the mines will
close, and a liquidator has been appointed, but there has been no decision
on when this will be.
Neither the French consultants, nor Solidarity's special plenipotentiary,
nor the town or voivodship administration have been able to come up with any
concrete plan for restructuring the region.
Young people, deeply uncertain about their future, are turning to crime and
gang-fighting. One gang, the Depeszowcy, or fans of British pop group
Depeche Mode - a band not noted for its cheery optimism - recently killed a
heavy-metal fan by pushing him under a train.
As Adam Gierak, a local journalist with the newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza, puts
it: 'Better to have certainty about bad things than uncertainty.'
Mr Josef Gruszka, the harassed-looking Solidarity plenipotentiary, charged
with drawing up plans for the future of the region, jokes: 'Sometimes I
think to myself: should we buy ropes for everybody to hang themselves, so as
not to suffer any more?'
Yet the region does have possibilities. Closing the mines would free
considerable sums of money from subsidies and miners' wages, to be spent on
other things.
The authorities are considering a scheme to give ex-miners loans, possibly
interest-free, to set up small businesses.
If the pollution can be controlled, land in the north-eastern part of the
province is good for agriculture. Factories could be built to process and
pack the produce.
Without the pollution, the region could also attract tourists. To the south,
the Sudeten mountains provide excellent skiing. Before the war, the German
skiing team used to train near the town of Zieleniec, and there are nine
former health spas in the region.
Finally, the mines may yet provide a key to Walbrzych's recovery - but as
sources of methane, not of coal. Both American and French companies have
expressed interest in exploiting the sizeable reserves.
The great lack is foreign investment. Dutch, Italian, Austrian, French and
American companies have all been to the region to discuss investment or
joint ventures. None has yet come forward with any money.
One problem is that no framework exists yet for facilitating contact and
negotiation between western companies and enterprises in Walbrzych. Mr
Gruszka adds that local conditions and proposals must be clear before any
deals are made with the west.
'I'm not xenophobic,' he says, but capitalism is not a game of cricket, it's
poker.'
On a wall in an alleyway in Walbrzych, someone has daubed the words Chwytaj
dzien], the Polish equivalent of carpe diem ('Seize the day'). The town
might do well to adopt it as a motto. When it comes to tackling Walbrzych's
problems, there is no more time for dithering.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1959</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (22): 'Too busy for fun' - Problems of the
new rich
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROWS OF smart Mercedes cars gleam through the display window in a shop on
Warsaw's main Krakowskie Przedmiescie street, which once sold olive green
uniforms to the military.
When the showroom opened recently, it sold some 50 vehicles in the first few
days to rich Poles who no longer have to be shy about having money.
In contrast to the communists who hoped to work wonders with the working
class the present government has the creation of 'a middle class' written
into its political programme.
At times, though, displays of wealth attract open signs of anger. 'A woman
spat on my windscreen as I stood at the traffic lights in my expensive car,'
said one businessman. 'I don't really blame her, it cost more than she'll
earn in her life.
'But she doesn't realise I'm so busy I don't have any time to enjoy the
things I can now afford,' he adds bitterly.
Ms Malgosia Piwkowska from Sopot, a popular resort on the Baltic, who is
opening a menswear shop there in the summer, reckons she will be selling 100
Giorgio Armani suits a month.' But I won't just be selling clothes, I'll be
advising men what to wear and when to wear it,' she says of her project
which promises a monthly turnover of Dollars 30,000.
It's a service which could well be gratefully received as Poland's new money
looks for pointers on how to behave when dealing with their rich and
powerful foreign partners. These are the ones on the way up working hard to
make their first million dollars.
Several hundred, though, according to Mr Wiktor Kubiak, the owner of Batax
Ltd, a trading company, are already worth between Dollars 5m to Dollars 10m.
The capital was mostly accumulated, he says, over the past two years.
Mr Kubiak is rich, too, and he is one of the first of his kind to have
invested in the performing arts and is planning to buy a Warsaw theatre.
He says he has put more than Dollars 1m into Metro, a musical which he hopes
to promote on Broadway. In the meantime, it is playing to packed houses in
Warsaw to disapproving stares from theatre people used to a more staid
cultural diet. But state subsidies to the arts are being cut and private
money will be essential if many artists are to survive.
The arts are not the only sphere where the rich are beginning to dabble.
Politics is another.
When Mr Algirdas Saudargis, the Lithuanian foreign minister, arrived in
Poland last January charged with setting up a government in exile soon after
the tragic shootings in Vilnius, Mr Jan Walczyk, the owner of the Zajazd
Napoleonski hotel, and his rich friends helped him set up an office.
It may have been one of the first foreign policy initiatives taken
independently of the government by the newly rich.
Mr Slawomir Jaruga, a successful businessman from Lodz, provided an example
of domestic political ambitions when he split the UPR, a small free-market
party in an attempt to become its leader.
The rich are also beginning to take an interest in restoring crumbling
country houses once owned by the gentry.
Some money is being spent abroad. Indeed, children are beginning to be
educated at foreign schools and a few are already enjoying their own yachts
on the Mediterranean.
Art auctions are fashionable, and Mr Wojciech Fibak, the tennis player,
recently paid Dollars 47,000 for a symbolist painting by Jacek Malcewski at
a sale organised by the Unicum auction house at the Victoria
Intercontinental hotel.
The Warsaw rich tend to live in leafy suburbs in large comfortable houses
surrounded by high walls protected by large dogs and hired private
bodyguards. Horse riding, tennis, eating out and charity dances at the
Warsaw Marriott are all part of their lifestyle.
A ball next Saturday in the Gdynia Hotel should provide a review of a class
in statu ascendi. It is being organised by a local group of the Lion's Club
to celebrate the 200th anniversary of the first constitution. Mrs Danuta
Walesa, the president's wife, is an honorary patron as is Mr Jan Krzysztof
Bielecki, the prime minister. Dinner jackets will be worn.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI Photograph Wojciech Fibak left Poland for Milan in a battered
Volkswagen 14 years ago. He never rose higher than 13th seed in world
tennis, but became coach to Ivan Lendl and invested on Wall Street. He now
lives with his family in a castle in Connecticut (above), which was built
for the builder of the Empire State building, and reputedly he owns the
world's largest private collection of Polish art (Omitted).
</PAGE>
