<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (20): Structural changes inevitable -
Anthony Robinson examines Europe's last bastion of peasant farming
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND is the last bastion of peasant farming in Europe. Stalin, who
cynically recognised that 'imposing communism on Poland is like saddling a
cow', accepted that imposing Soviet-style collectivisation was beyond the
reach of local communists.
After the war, the big estates were seized and broken up. But most of the
large state farms were established in the western part of the country, on
former German land abandoned in the face of the Red Army's advance and then
incorporated into the new People's Republic. Around 75 per cent of the land,
split into 2.7m farms, has remained for more than 40 years in the hands of
peasant proprietors.
But, as a recent World Bank study of Polish agriculture underlines, 'the
rural sector, although mostly private, was, and still is, totally dependent
on the state and co-operative sectors for the procurement of all inputs and
services and for the sale of all production'. Reform of the farming sector
fundamentally means abolishing this artificial and distorting relationship
which meant that for 40 years farmers despised and mistrusted the state, yet
acquired a dangerous dependency upon it.
This 'withering away' of the Marxist state is now being tackled with gusto.
Dramatic changes are under way with the abolition of consumer subsidies on
food, a sharp fall in producer subsidies and growing competition from
imports - including politically sensitive subsidised imports from European
Community countries.
Nearly 30 per cent of the population is still employed in agriculture, so
reforming the agricultural sector is politically highly sensitive.
Farmers, still largely hooked on the attitudes of the past, continue to
demand minimum guaranteed prices and protection from imports. Like their
counterparts in the European Community they frequently blockade towns and
throw eggs (and worse) at politicians.
But, with 24 per cent of all farms less than two hectares in size and the
average size of private farms under six hectares, huge structural changes
leading to fewer, larger and more productive farms are inevitable.
At the same time, the voices of Poland's old landed aristocracy are to be
heard demanding the return of at least part, if not all, of their old
pre-war estates.
Many of the small farms will disappear naturally over time as their ageing
proprietors die out. Their farms will be absorbed and consolidated into
larger units, a process made infinitely easier in Poland by the very fact
that private property ownership - and hence its legal sale or transference -
was never abolished through collectivisation. Existing state farms are
likely to be converted into genuine co-operatives.
The hope is that dispossessed farmers will find alternative employment in
the expansion of underdeveloped rural services in food processing, transport
and marketing. It is here, in the privatisation of the former monopolistic
state marketing and processing sectors that the World Bank pinpointed the
greatest scope for investment, rationalisation and growth.
'Agricultural production should be on land that is essentially private.
Similarly marketing, transport, processing and storage activities should be
private. As for prices they should be determined by market forces', the Bank
report indicated.
It also underlined the need for Poland to have access to foreign markets.
'Agriculture should be free to use all trade possibilities, domestically and
internationally, since this is the only way it can fully exploit its
competitive advantage at any given time.' Brave words - totally contradicted
in the annex by this advice from the European Community, co-author of the
report. 'The government should allow itself all types of border measures
including quantitive restrictions to set the price of cereals where, for
political reasons, it would like it to be.' The EC also recommended that
domestic prices should be stabilised by a system of EC-style variable export
taxes/subsidies and corresponding import measures . . . 'and aim
deliberately for an agricultural production somewhat below
self-sufficiency.'
It is advice such as this which fuels the growing conviction that eastern
and central Europe will only achieve its desired integration into a larger
European Community after a huge battle for fundamental reform of the Common
Agricultural Policy (CAP).
Meanwhile, Polish farmers and the government face the immediate problem of
how to dispose of last year's surplus of grain, meat, potatoes, sugar beet
and other products. On his trip to Moscow last month, Prime Minister Jan
Bielecki offered the Soviets 1m tons of grain and 100,000 tons of meat. The
Soviets replied they had no cash, were not prepared to deliver more oil in
exchange but were prepared to supply more gas and consider barter deals
involving ferrous and non-ferrous minerals and other products. Talks
continue.
The trade issue is becoming increasingly serious - both because Polish
farming has become more productive over the last decade and because plans
for 4-5 per cent annual growth in agricultural production depend on export
outlets. Last year Poland produced a record 28m tons of grain, up 1.5m tons
from 1989, and 2.4m tons of meat. Sugar beet production was also 300,00 tons
higher at 2.1m tons. Farm exports last year at Dollars 2.1bn exceeded
imports of Dollars 897m to provide a Dollars 1.2bn net contribution to the
overall trade surplus.
Higher exports were also a function of lower domestic demand, itself a
function of the sharply higher prices which followed the abolition of
consumer price subsidies. The meat and food queues which were once the butt
of countless Polish jokes, and countless wasted queuing hours, are now a
thing of the past. So is the wastage associated with feeding cheap processed
food to pigs.
In the old days the joke was that the well-fed Czech dog would visit Poland
from time to time because in Poland, although there was nothing to eat, a
dog at least had the freedom to bark.
It is now possible in Poland to both bark and eat. The only question is how
to pay for it.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X Photograph About 75 per cent of the land, split into 2.5m
farms, has remained in the hands of peasant proprietors (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1962</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (21): Return of the landed aristocracy -
Profile: Count Jan Zamoyski
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNT JAN ZAMOYSKI, nearing 80, is the very model of a Polish gentleman. He
slips easily into English and French and feels just a little satisfaction at
having managed to outlive the communists to see the promise of better times.
His father, Maurycy, was Poland's largest landowner in 1918 when the country
regained its independence and he helped pay the largest part of the bills
for Poland's delegation at the Versailles Peace Conference which established
a shortlived post-war European order.
When the count inherited the family estate in 1937 it amounted to 61,000
hectares and 10 industrial plants including a brewery and a furniture
factory.
Now he is a leading light of the Polish Society of Industrialists which,
along with its fraternal Landowners' Association, is seeking to have
property confiscated by the communists restored or compensation paid at the
very least.' I'm not too interested in the farming part,' he admits, tacitly
recognising that any move to return the land given to the peasants by the
communists in 1944 and 1945 would be enormously unpopular.
'However, when I go into the forests we once had I still think of the trees
as being my own,' he says, his kind smile free of any rancour.
As to the prospect of having his family's businesses returned, he's a
'restrained optimist'.
And societies like his continue to attract support, including that of
President Lech Walesa, on the grounds that past wrongs should be righted.
Indeed, the government recently decided after much soul-searching that the
budget really could not afford any full-scale restoration of property and
what compensation there would be, would be in the form of vouchers
exchangeable for shares in soon-to-be-privatised state sector companies.
'I don't want the children to say that I didn't try,' Count Zamoyski says of
his efforts, which if successful would turn him once more into a wealthy
man.
It would be a far cry from the two rooms the seven members of his family
occupied in 1958 when he was released from prison after serving almost eight
years on a trumped up spying charge.
During the war, the Germans had allowed him to administer his estate and all
the while he had been an active member of the underground.
Before his arrest by the communists he worked for a western shipping line
and after his release for Swissair in Warsaw.
He decided against emigration, making a conscious decision to live at home
rather than abroad. 'I'm tied to this land,' he says.
It's a stance which is in line with the family's political tradition which
this century favoured the National Democrats (ND), a pre-war nationalist
right-wing party.
Indeed, Count Zamoyski is now actively trying to unite various disparate
small political groups in the ND tradition and recently became the chairman
of a renascent National Democrat party which he hopes will act as a nucleus
for a larger movement.
He also always took an active interest in and sought funds for the
restoration of Zamosc founded in 1580 by his namesake, who laid the
foundations of family's fortune in the 16th century.
Zamosc, in eastern Poland, is a rare example of renaissance town planning
and its present mayor, Marcin Zamoyski, is the successor to the family
title.
He is there because after the local elections in the spring of last year the
citizens asked the count to be their mayor. He suggested his son and they
accepted.
'I don't know how long he will be able to hold on to the job as the
honeymoon between the council and the mayor lasted two weeks,' he says.
Indeed, Marcin Zamoyski's trials in Zamosc are typical of Poland's first
encounter with local democracy. A fractious council is at odds with the
official it appointed in the first place, while a local clique with its
roots in the communist past is seeking to corrupt the new establishment.
For the moment, though, Count Zamoyski argues that the return of plant such
as the Zamosc furniture factory would be the simplest way of restoring it to
sound management.
He has been in touch with IKEA, the Swedish furniture group, on possible
joint projects and he has plans for 'his' local brewery, too.
But in the materialistic era that Poland has now embraced the count points
out that the aristocracy which he represents does have another role to play.
'We can show that there are cultural values, beside the mere material ones,'
he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1963</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (18): Eyes on west and east - A look at
foreign policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND is determined never again to be isolated, or to be treated as a mere
buffer zone between prosperous western Europe and a disintegrating Soviet
Union.
Behind its fierce determination to become a fully-fledged member of the
European Community lies the moral conviction that the west owes something,
not only to Poland but to all of central Europe, for the betrayal of Munich
in 1938 and for the Yalta agreements which left Poland and its neighbours
interned for more than 40 years behind the Iron Curtain. It was in this
spirit that Poland joined Czechoslovakia and Hungary at a tripartite summit
meeting in February at Visegrad castle in Slovakia to co-ordinate their
approach to the EC and lend each other mutual assistance in the building of
constitutional democracies in their countries.
But, as President Lech Walesa's recent trips to the United States and
forthcoming visit to Moscow indicate, Poland is also determined to be an
active participator in whatever wider world order emerges from the state of
flux.
Since his election last December, President Walesa, whose presidential
powers remain to be defined in a new constitution, has made clear that he
intends to play an active diplomatic as well as domestic political role. On
his visits to the US, Britain, France and the European Community
headquarters in Brussels, his basic message has been that Poles deserve
special credit for having played the decisive role in the events which led
to the crumbling of Soviet hegemony over eastern Europe and the virtually
bloodless end to the cold war.
His visit to the US, where Polish-Americans form an influential lobby, was
crowned by US support for large-scale debt relief, symbolised by the US
decision to reduce its outstanding debt by 20 per cent over and above the 50
per cent debt reduction agreed by the Paris club of official creditors.
When he goes to Moscow later this month, he will argue forcefully for the
prompt withdrawal of the nearly 50,000 Soviet troops in Poland and seek to
put political and economic relations with Moscow and the individual
republics on a new plane, as befits relations between sovereign states. On
the economic front, Prime Minister Jan Bielecki is leading efforts to
jump-start trade between the two countries, virtually paralysed since the
shift from rouble- to dollar-based trading on January 1.
Much patient work has already been done by the previous government, led by
Mr Tadeusz Mazowiecki, to create the conditions for a new, less strained
relationship between the two sides. This includes recognition by the Soviet
side that the NKVD, precursor of the present KGB, did indeed murder Polish
officers in the Katyn woods and other venues during the war, an admission of
great psychological importance to both sides.
But Poland is the only former Warsaw Pact country not to have signed a
formal troop withdrawal agreement and negotiations with the Soviets became
noticeably stiffer as conservative forces regained ground in Moscow. The
Soviet side have proposed withdrawing all forces by the end of 1993. But
during his election campaign Mr Walesa promised to get them out this year,
although a compromise which allowed a limited Soviet presence to supervise
the transit of Soviet troops from eastern Germany is possible.
Mr Walesa is the big picture man, determined to give a high profile to
Poland's main foreign policy objectives. Significantly, however, Mr
Krzysztof Skubiszewski, the foreign minister, was one of only two ministers
to be retained in the new government formed in January by Mr Bielecki. The
other was Mr Leszek Balcerowicz, the minister of finance. A respected former
academic, Mr Skubiszewski says that co-operation with the president is good
although 'competences are not always clear and defined'.
Much has already been achieved. German reunification means that Poland's
western border now abuts directly on to the European Community. Ratification
of the Polish-German border treaty earlier this year assures international
recognition of western borders. These incorporate former German land given
to Poland by Stalin in recompense for former Polish land incorporated into
the Soviet Union in 1945.
The subsequent agreement lifting visa restrictions between the two countries
on April 8 allows Poles free access not only to Germany but also to France,
Italy and the Benelux countries under the terms of the Schengen agreement on
visa-free travel. Talks on a fully-fledged friendship treaty between the two
countries, however, remain stalled over the rights of ethnic Germans and
other details.
The collapse of Comecon trade, the re-negotiation of foreign debt, the need
to attract foreign investment to breathe life into the privatisation process
and the long-term objective of entry into the European Community by 2000
have all given a substantial economic and financial content to Polish
foreign policy.
Although the foreign ministry is in overall charge of the EC negotiations
Warsaw recently appointed Mr Jacek Saryusz-Wolski as 'plenipotentiary for
European integration and foreign assistance' to harmonise and co-ordinate
the approach to Europe and report to the Council of Ministers. Similarly, Mr
Janusz Sawicki, the deputy finance minister, is in charge of the complex
multilateral and bilateral debt negotiations. Both are prime examples of the
highly-motivated, competent and tough-minded technocrats now at the
forefront of Poland's efforts to create the external conditions for its
transformation to an economically prosperous, politically 'normal'
democracy.
Meanwhile, many ordinary Poles are awaiting the third visit next month from
the Pope, who played such an important role in keeping hope for a brighter
future alive during the dark days of martial law. With unemployment rising
and little chance of greater prosperity for some time to come, many will be
looking for Papal reassurance that their struggles will lead to a better
future.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
