<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (19): Loving and hating the dead -
Present-day attitudes to the Jews
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY POLONSKY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TODAY, there are barely 10,000 Jews in Poland. These last remnants of one of
the largest and most vibrant Jewish communities in the world, a community
which in 1939 numbered 3.5m, are mostly elderly and it will be an extremely
difficult task to ensure the survival of Jewish life in Poland for another
generation
Yet, the impact on Polish life of the consciousness of this community, whose
traces can be found everywhere - in buildings, in cultural life and in
peoples' memories - is enormous. As in so many other aspects of life, the
Poles seem mesmerised by the past and still preoccupied by the issues which
dominated it.
On the Jewish issue, sharply divided and contradictory opinions can be
encountered among Poles, sometimes even in the same individual. On the one
hand, there has been, since the late 1970s, a revival of interest in the
Polish-Jewish past. Partly this is the result of nostalgia, in the largely
mono-ethnic and mono-religious Poland of today (though its homogeneity
should not be exaggerated), for the more colourful Poland of the past, with
its mixture of religions and nationalities.
Partly, too, it is the result of a growing awareness that it is impossible
to give a coherent account of Polish history and culture without taking into
account the contribution of the national minorities, in particular the Jews.
Above all,it is the product of a desire to come to terms with the less
attractive features of the Polish past, principally chauvinism and
anti-Semitism. This preoccupation, strong among a section of the Polish
intelligentsia, was stimulated by the higher sense of self-esteem created by
the emergence of Solidarity, which seemed to negate the western stereotype
of the Poles as impractical and incompetent dreamers. It was best
articulated by the literary critic Jan Blonski, who wrote in a widely
discussed article in 1987:
'We did take the Jews into our home, but we made them live in the cellar.
When they wanted to come into the drawing-room, our response was, Yes, but
only after you cease to be Jews, when you become 'civilised' . . . There
were those among the Jews who were ready to adhere to this advice. No sooner
did they do this than we, in turn, began talking of an invasion of Jews, of
the danger of their infiltration of Polish society. Then we started to put
down conditions . . . that we shall accept as Poles only those Jews willing
to co-operate in attempts to stem Jewish influence in our society . . .
'Eventually, when we lost our home, and when in its premises the invaders
set to murdering Jews, did we show solidarity towards them? How many of us
decided it was none of our business? There were also those (and I leave out
of account common criminals) who were secretly pleased that Hitler had
solved for us 'the Jewish problem'. We would not even welcome and honour the
survivors, even if they were embittered, disorientated and perhaps somewhat
tiresome. I repeat: instead of haggling and justifying ourselves, we should
just consider our own faults and weaknesses. This is the moral revolution
that is imperative when considering the Polish-Jewish past. It is only this
that can gradually cleanse our desecrated soil.'
At the same time, the end of communist rule in Poland has been accompanied
by a great increase in the expression of anti-Semitic sentiments. Partly
this is the result of the end of censorship. These views were probably
always present but now can be uttered openly with impunity. Partly, too, it
is the result of the dislocations caused by the difficult transition to a
market economy and a plural political system. The temptation to blame
present hardships on a 'hidden' Jewish or masonic hand has a long tradition
in Poland.
The belief that communism in Poland was a Jewish phenomenon and the
protracted conflict over the Carmelite convent in Auschwitz concentration
camp also fuelled anti-Semitism. The political conflict within the
Solidarity camp was a bitter one with many characteristics of a family feud.
President Walesa is certainly no anti-Semite. But in his presidential
campaign he failed clearly to condemn those of his supporters who attacked
the Mazowiecki government as being too subject to Jewish influence. He also
described himself as 'a full-blooded Pole with documents going back to his
great-grandfathers to prove it'.
Before the campaign began he argued that 'persons of Jewish origin should
not conceal this', a statement he justified during the campaign on the
following grounds:
'Chauvinistic and anti-Semitic views and manifestations . . . appear because
the present political set-up lacks clarity. There is confusion . . . as to
whose interest the administration represents. The personal configurations
and the question of responsibility are unclear . . . The functioning
mechanism of the state structure must be made transparent, cliques smashed,
and competence - not mafia arrangements - be relied on. Then this
suspiciousness (about Jews in government) will disappear.'
The conflict between the two sets of views about the Jews' role in Poland is
really an argument over the future of the country. Attitudes towards the
Jews are a touchstone for more fundamental views. What is at issue is
whether the Poland of the future will be inward-looking, prey to conspiracy
theories of politics and chauvinist, or pluralistic, western-oriented and
tolerant.
A number of recent developments give grounds for cautious optimism. The
pastoral letter of the Polish bishops of January 20, 1991, was the first
unequivocal condemnation by the hierarchy of anti-Semitism. Similarly,
President Walesa has gone out of his way to repudiate his own behaviour
during the presidential campaign. He has repeatedly attempted to reassure
the Jewish world of his hostility to anti-Semitism and has set up a
high-level commission to improve Polish-Jewish relations.
Speaking to a visiting Jewish delegation shortly after his election, he
affirmed: 'Anti-Semitism has been a serious problem here. We need to build a
pluralistic society. We must do this and we will do it.'
Let us hope he and his compatriots succeed.
The author is professor of international history at the London School of
Economics
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX Photograph (Omitted). Photograph The gates in Lodz of
Europe's largest Jewish cemetery. Lodz, like Warsaw and other Polish cities,
was the centre of a rich Jewish culture that was destroyed by the Nazis, who
built the largest concentration camps on Polish soil (Omitted).
</PAGE>
