<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRADAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (17): The prerequisites of prosperity - A
new respect has emerged for capitalist financial institutions and for
success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the unexpected side-effects of the collapse of authoritarian, command
economies throughout central and eastern Europe is a new respect for the
capitalist institutions which help create a 'level playing ground' - and a
new recognition of the linkage between democracy and prosperity.
Both points were forcibly made by Prime Minister Jan Krzysztof Bielecki in
his speech to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London after
attending last month's inauguration of the European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development (EBRD) - itself the first pan-European institution of the
post-cold war period.
A self-confessed 'liberal economist', Mr Bielecki argued nevertheless that
recent east German experience indicated that the classic
leave-it-to-the-market approach was 'inherently flawed' in relation to the
needs of the post-communist countries with their 'fragile, even non-existent
market controls'. Instead, he argued, governments themselves have to manage
the transition to a market economy 'by creating the legislative and
administrative machinery that underpins the market and which is taken for
granted in the west'.
In Poland's case, the creation of financial and other institutions based
largely on already existing institutions and methods in use by European
Community countries is proceeding apace. The deliberate aim is to create
that intricate web of laws, institutions and interconnected services which
Stalinist theory despised as non-productive but which capitalist practice
has demonstrated as the prerequisite of prosperity.
A stock exchange, that quintessential capitalist tool, opened to much
razzamatazz in Warsaw last month, although it will only really start
operating regularly from June. Sited in the building which once central
committee, its functioning is closely modelled on the Lyons bourse.
The combination of hard times in the City of London and the awesome size of
the potential demand for financial expertise in all aspects of
privatisation, evaluation, accounting and legal work has made Warsaw a
temporary Mecca for hordes of City firms and foreign banks.
International institutions such as the World Bank, the International
Monetary Fund, the International Finance Corporation (IFC) and the European
Commission have all set up shop-assessing projects, disbursing loans and
greatly improving the quality and availability of statistics and analysis.
Meanwhile, Poland is busy setting up its own Development Bank, modelled
closely on Germany's post-war Kreditanstalt fur Wiederaufbau. The bank is
headed by Mr Wojciech Kostrzewa and advised by Mr Matthew Olex, one of three
vice-presidents, who used to run capital market operations for Lloyds Bank.
Its main functions will be to act as a partner for the World Bank and other
institutions and concentrate on restructuring state enterprises and
investment in small and medium private companies. Three foreign banks, from
France, Austria and Italy, are expected to take a joint 10 per cent stake
shortly.
The recently created EBRD is expected to work closely with all these
institutions in part-funding projects and seeking out potential equity
investments in the rapidly privatising economy and newly-created Polish
companies.
Last year more than 500,000 new businesses were registered in Poland, mostly
in the retail trade, wholesale and warehousing, road transport and related
services and construction. Many failed in their first year. The great
majority are small and under-capitalised. But they are the seed corn out of
which will grow the middle class of the future.
This is the prospect which underpins the effort to create an insurance
industry, based largely on UK practice, build up unit trusts and develop a
competitive commercial banking system. More than 65 private banks have been
authorised over the last 18 months while the IFC and World Bank are involved
in a project to provide technical assistance to nine former branch offices
of the National Bank of Poland. These have been hived off to form nine
state-owned commercial banks. Two of the nine are slated for privatisation
this year and the IFC is busy setting up 'twinning arrangements' with
foreign banks.
A shake-up is also taking place in foreign trade financing where 15 banks
have now been granted foreign exchange licenses and a new Export Development
Bank has been set up. The new arrangement is expected to sharpen competition
for Bank Handlowy, which up to now has accounted for around 90 per cent of
Polish foreign trade financing. But the bank, under its US-trained new
president, Mr Cezary Stypulkowski, plans to streamline its traditional
business in the rapidly expanding foreign trade area and to add retail
banking, corporate finance and other operations to its services.
But the need to attract foreign investment and privatise and restructure
small- and medium-sized state companies has also created big opportunities
for entrepreneurial merchant banking services such as those offered by the
Polish Investment Company (PIC). Owned and staffed mainly by bilingual
Anglo-Polish professionals with a wide range of financial experience in the
City and elsewhere, the PIC, in which Swiss bank Corporation also has a 23
per cent stake, is in some ways a symbol of the new, professional Poland now
rapidly emerging.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
