<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (12): Flight plan of national carrier under
review - Profile: Lot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WARSAW'S new international airport, due for completion next year, could
become the regional hub for one of the world's most dynamic markets in the
21st century. The new runway and expanded terminal facilities being built by
Hochtief of Germany alongside the present crowded baggage and customs hall,
should relieve the growing congestion of western European airports and
provide a vital freight and passenger interchange in the geographical heart
of Europe.
This vision of the future is central to the privatisation plans of Lot, the
Polish state-owned national carrier. Mr Bronislaw Klimaszewski, who returned
to the company last year as general director after being sacked as
commercial director following the imposition of martial law in 1981, has
already begun preliminary talks with airlines such as Air France, Lufthansa
and El Al.
But before Lot has any realistic chance of becoming an attractive partner it
has to dispose of its fleet of uneconomic Soviet-built aircraft, cut back on
a payroll stuffed with retired military and security personnel and create a
new ethos for what used to be, in effect, a semi-military organisation.
There are only two potential buyers for Lot's seven long-range Ilyushin-62,
14 medium-range Tupolev 154 and seven Tu-134's - the Soviet Union itself and
China. Negotiations are under way with both. But a sale to China requires
agreement from Moscow, which would have to guarantee spare parts and other
services to the new owner. Moscow, desperate to keep its aircraft factories
busy, would preferto sell new aircraft directly to China.
On the other hand Aeroflot, the Soviet airline, is itself in the throes of a
major re-organisation. This should lead to the establishment of many
smaller, regional and republic-based airlines which could be potential
buyers of Lot's redundant fleet.
Meanwhile, Lot, which has already leased three Boeing 767's from the US
manufacturer, plans to lease two similar aircraft to replace its long-range
Ilyushin-62s and is negotiating with Boeing, McDonnell and Airbus for eight
medium-range aircraft to replace its 14 Tu-154s. A further eight
Franco-Italian ATR-72 turboprop aircraft are on order to replace obsolete
Antonov-24 aircraft and the ageing Tu 134s.
In the face of union protests, 1,500 of Lot's 8,000 employees are being
dismissed. Staffing should be further trimmed to around 5,000 once the
fuel-thirsty and expensive-to-maintain Soviet jets are replaced by efficient
western aircraft.
But getting to the point where Lot will be an attractive proposition for
foreign investors and potential partners will be hard and expensive. 'I
think that the combination of Lot and the new Warsaw airport will be an
attractive and interesting proposition within the next three to four years.
But we'll need government finance and subsidies until then,' says Mr
Klimaszewski who has called in the French bank, Credit Commerciale, to carry
out an audit and evaluation.
Until now, he adds, 'nobody had any idea of how to run the airline's
finances. Everything was distorted by artificial exchange rates, arbitrary
pricing and providing sheltered employment for retired submarine commanders
and the like.'
The first steps to privatisation are now under way as Lot is
'commercialised' by conversion from an amorphous state-owned company into a
joint stock company with all shares held by the Polish treasury. This is the
classic first stage in Polish-style privatisation of big companies. The rest
depends on the speed with which Poland and its neighbours create the
potential traffic which would make the revamped airline an attractive
investment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1969</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAC6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (15): Wallflower opens - Quest for foreign
investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE foreign investment dance of the post-communist countries Poland feels
that it has been a wallflower. By the end of 1990, according to Mr Zbigniew
Piotrovsky, head of the Foreign Investment Agency, founded in 1988, only
Dollars 160m had been invested by foreign partners in joint ventures that
were in operation.
Yet things are looking up, since this represented a four-fold increase over
the level at the end of the previous year. Furthermore, in 1990 the FIA
handled 1,752 applications to establish joint ventures, more than twice as
many as in 1989. Among these investors are such famous western names as
Philips and Pilkingtons, but by far the most important source of investment
applications is Germany, with more than a third of the total in 1990.
Poland hopes for much more. The recently signed multilateral agreement to
lower Poland's official external debt by 50 per cent is bound to help.
Also likely to help is a revised Foreign Investment Law, now before
parliament. The new law makes four main changes to present legislation:
The need for permits from the FIA is now to be limited to a very few
sensitive areas;
The previous minimum entry requirement of Dollars 50,000 and 20 per cent of
the capital stock is to be abolished;
Tax incentives are to be modified. The automatic three-year tax holiday is
to be abolished. The new law will retain a form of tax holiday, but for
substantial investors, with a minimum equity requirement;
Automatic guarantees are to be provided against expropriation and
nationalisation and full repatriation of profits, capital gains and
dividends.
All this should help, as should determined attempts to bring foreign
investors into the rapidly accelerating privatisation programme. But the
most important conditions are successful stabilisation of the Polish economy
and liberal terms of association with the European Community. The battle for
both is now fully engaged. If Poland succeeds, it should soon cease to be a
wallflower.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1970</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAC5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (13): Iron finance minister drives on -
Profile: Leszek Balcerowicz
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Polish programme of radical economic stabilisation and restructuring is
associated with the name of one man. That man is Mr Leszek Balcerowicz,
erstwhile academic economist, but since September 1989 executor of the
'Balcerowicz plan' in his capacity as deputy prime minister and minister of
finance. The more politically-minded may regret his rigour, but he himself
is determined to proceed.
Asked about his goal for inflation this year, Mr Balcerowicz agrees that
'nobody can be sure whether we can achieve 1 per cent a month or something
between 1 and 2 per cent. What's really important is for the rate of
inflation to drop and to stay at the lower rate permanently.
The original assumption for December to December inflation was about 32 per
cent. It may be a bit higher, though we hope not much higher.' But, as he
points out, 'this should be compared with annualised inflation of 2,000 per
cent in 1989 and of 250 per cent in 1990'.
Achieving that goal will be made no easier by the last jolt of price
adjustments, necessitated by a fivefold increase in the cost of imported
natural gas from the Soviet Union. The domestic price of natural gas was
raised by 80 per cent in January and still needs to be raised by another 120
per cent.
Asked about the timing of these increases, Mr Balcerowicz remarks that 'we
had assumed the election was to be in June or May. It turns out that the
elections are going to be in October and there is no time to wait. So the
decision has to be taken earlier'.
Naturally, this is not going to be popular, but 'if one wanted to minimise
inflation in the short term, one would have to give up price adjustments and
one would have to find sources of finance for gas and electricity.
So what helps to make tough decisions,' continues the Minister in words that
would delight Mrs Margaret Thatcher, 'is that there is no easy way out.'
Is the minister concerned about the loss of competitiveness as Polish wages
soar and the exchange rate remains fixed at 19,500 zlotys to the dollar? 'We
are not contemplating any radical devaluation,' he insists. 'Having said
that, it is quite normal that we are working on various concepts of exchange
rate determination, though not a radical devaluation. But our intention is
to use the exchange rate as an important stabiliser.'
Mr Balcerowicz is equally determined to retain the highly unpopular system
of wage control, according to which only 60 per cent of the inflation in a
given month can be passed into wages in the state sector. Equally, 'our
intention is not to have too great a budget deficit. This would probably
require painful adjustments of expenditure to lower than assumed revenues,'
which is made more difficult by the success already achieved in cutting
subsidies, from 15 per cent of gross domestic product in 1989, down to 5-6
per cent today.
With inflation rising above its trough of 1.8 per cent reached last August,
to monthly rates of 4 per cent or more since then, Mr Balcerowicz admits
that 'the results of the stabilisation turned out to be worse in the second
half of last year than we expected, for three reasons.
'The first was the oil price shock. It was a double shock for us, because
the Soviets started to increase the proportion of oil priced in dollars and
the dollar price also started to increase. The second was the election
campaign. A number of promises were made, including promises that if you
doubled wages, then production would double and the standard of living would
improve very quickly. I think this weakened the position of managers. The
third is that there may have been a relaxation of macroeconomic policies,
especially monetary policy.'
If the mistakes have made him more determined, Poland has certainly been
unfortunate, its present worry being the collapse in exports to the Soviet
Union. The earlier forecast was for 3 to 4 per cent GDP growth this year,
but 'if this tendency in trade with the Soviets continues we cannot hope for
that rate of growth,' admits the minister.
So, can the Government continue with its policies when enterprises are
hurting, unemployment is soaring and even the fates are conspiring against
it?
'So far as the government is concerned'' asserts Mr Balcerowicz, 'I think
there is a cohesion. I have not had any problem with the basic elements of
the economic strategy, contrary to some expectations. The difficulty is that
you cannot expect that everybody would understand the difficulties and
challenges of the economic situation. I am referring to the politicians. I
would hope that they would understand, but, of course, not everybody
understands why keeping wage controls is so crucial. But the people with
whom we are working have a full realisation of what it would mean to
sidetrack. It would be too dangerous not to continue.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
