<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (10): Beating on the EC's doors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'THE thrust of this agreement,' says the Polish government of the
association arrangement now under negotiation with the European Community,
'is to open Europe for Poland and Poland for Europe. It is therefore an
agreement of historical importance.'
So, indeed, it is. Correspondingly, the first and perhaps most fundamental
government demand has been that the agreement commit the EC to the principle
of Polish membership.
As a step towards that aim, but also to underpin its economic reforms,
Poland seeks a free trade area with the EC 'for essentially all products',
one that would ensure stability of market access for Polish exports (about
half of which already go to the EC) and would also enable Poland to maintain
the 'open import system that we now enjoy'. The latter is no trivial demand
since, at present, Poland's import regime is more liberal than that of the
EC.
Confronted with a political challenge of the first magnitude, the EC counts
ears of wheat and votes of farmers. In his statement to the EC of March 19,
1991, Mr Andrzej Olechowski, secretary of state at the Ministry for Foreign
Economic Co-operation, condemned the resulting proposals on trade, as 'a
highly unbalanced proposal.
'On one side, it asks Poland to commit itself to eliminate before the end of
the agreement all restrictions on imports from the EC, limit and discipline
the use of safeguard measures and strengthen protection afforded to
intellectual property. On the other side, it offers Poland removal of import
restrictions pertaining to about one half of its exports (since it excludes
most of agriculture, textiles and clothing, and steel) and the assurance of
GATT-consistent use of safeguards also covering only half of the products it
exports.
'There is no government in the world which would submit such a one-sided
agreement to its parliament for ratification,' concluded the Polish
negotiator.
In its response to the EC, the Polish government proposed the following:
Customs duties for all products to be removed at the latest by the end of
the agreement's second stage (after ten years), but the EC would consolidate
tariff preferences and remove duties for selected agricultural, textiles and
steel products upon initiation of the agreement, while Poland would remove
duties on all products that it does not produce;
Upon initiation of the agreement the EC would remove quantitative
restrictions for all products (so matching Poland), while Poland would
undertake not to introduce such restrictions on imports from the EC;
Gradual reduction of variable levies on agricultural imports from Poland and
gradual removal of minimum prices for agricultural and iron and steel
products, while Poland would undertake not to impose countervailing duties
on EC's officially dumped exports;
Adjustment of protection of intellectual property by Poland to EC standards;
and
Agreement on mutual liberalisation of public contracts.
How agonising it must be for the EC to confront a government that believes
in both the EC and in free trade] Shamed perhaps, EC foreign ministers did
decide on April 15 to go a little further towards meeting the demands of
Poland (and of Czechoslovakia and Hungary as well).
In particular, membership of the EC may now figure in the preamble to the
agreements as 'an ultimate, though not an automatic' goal. The EC has also
dropped its call for a review half-way through the 10-year period during
which trade barriers are to be phased out.
Eastern Europeans will probably be allowed to sell more fruit, vegetables,
pork, game, but not - heaven forbid - cereals, beef, lamb or dairy products,
which will continue to receive the full protection of the Common
Agricultural Policy.
Northern EC members also overruled Mediterranean objections to giving
eastern Europe a little more on textiles and steel. All textile tariffs are
to disappear over the 10-year transition period, while steel import duties
and quotas will go within five years. But the country most concerned to keep
out Polish coal was Germany, which insists upon a special regime.
In spite of these steps forward, the agreement is likely to remain
'asymmetric' - on the EC's normal mercantilist logic - in the EC's favour.
The EC's response is, it appears, to suggest that Poland increase its
tariffs.
No wonder the US is grumbling that eastern Europe will be persuaded to make
a general increase in its tariffs, followed by a selective reduction only
towards the EC.
While an agreement is almost certain to be reached this year, the question
remains what sort of an agreement it will be. The entry of Poland into
closer trading relations with the EC could make the latter more liberal or
the former more protectionist. Poland is in grave danger of losing this
battle, to the disadvantage of both sides.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
