<DOCNO>FT911-1974</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAC1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (8): Polish-Canadian Walter Mitty -
Profile: Stan Tyminski
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE graffiti, stencilled on a Poznan wall in Russian reads: 'Warning. Stan
Tyminski' and the date, December 9. It was a thinly veiled warning to Polish
voters that a vote for the previously unknown Polish-Canadian businessman in
the second round of the presidential elections last year was a vote for dark
and mysterious forces with secret-service connections.
The graffiti reflects the classic conspiracy theory response to Mr
Tyminski's shock defeat of former Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki in the
November first round. But most of the Poles, around 23 per cent of the
electorate, who voted for him in the first round, stuck by him in the
second, while those from the Mazowiecki camp, who earlier bitterly opposed
Mr Walesa, were shocked into rallying round to ensure a 77 per cent support
for the Walesa presidency.
The polarisation of Polish politics around Mr Walesa, the former shipyard
electrician who sprang to national and then global fame almost overnight as
Solidarity leader during the Gdansk shipyard strike in August 1980, and Mr
Tyminski, who turned up, completely unknown, three months before elections
and defeated the prime minister, reflects the fluid, and sometimes bizarre
side of post-communist Polish politics.
Yet it is difficult, on acquaintance, to imagine that Mr Tyminski has a
long-term future as a significant player in Polish politics. It is even more
difficult to see him as a sinister character, a potential tyrant or populist
rabble-rouser if times got really hard again.
Perhaps Poland has been lucky in finding such an apparently inoffensive
repository for the fears, frustrations and hopes of millions of ordinary
Poles. Perhaps, to put it differently, Mr Walesa is right in claiming credit
for having flushed out such previously unsuspected depths of resentment in
the Polish electorate at such an early stage, before someone more sinister
appeared to challenge the basis of Poland's restored but fledgling
democracy.
Greeting visitors in the small garden of his mother's modest, Swiss-style
chalet in the outer suburbs of Warsaw, Mr Tyminski appeared smaller and
tubbier than his televised election presence. He smokes and smiles nervously
and is not an easy man to pin down on what he believes and what kind of
future he foresees for Poland.
Like Mr Walesa, he has a touching faith in computers. Unlike Mr Walesa he
actually knows something about them, having built up a small but modestly
profitable electronics parts factory in Canada.
Describing himself as a 'Pole and patriot', Mr Tyminski is now busy building
up a new party, called Party X, which will contest the parliamentary
elections expected in October. Thus far, he says, it has only 1,000 members
and Dollars 1,000 in the bank 'but we'll have from 50,000 to 100,000 members
in six months,' he predicts. And the programme? 'It's all here,' he says,
profferring a pamphlet containing a Polish translation of the 1773
Declaration of American Independence.
All here? 'Yes. Like the Americans we're fighting the red coats. All those
who used to be subservient to the communists.' But his enemies are not only
the communists, who his opponents believe are actually secretly supporting
him, but also individuals such as the US millionaire Mr George Soros, he
says.
He accuses Mr Soros 'whose influence goes from Russia through Poland to
China' of financing the Sachs-Lipton plan, drawn up by economists Jeffrey
Sachs and David Lipton, which is the basis of 'the Balcerowicz plan for free
market domination'.
'I'd like to see a Polish plan in action, compatible with the needs of the
people', he adds in words which to some ears carry the veiled tones of
foreign interference, and deeper undertones of old-style Jewish conspiracy
theory.
He denies any anti-Semitism but proffers an English translation of Hitler's
Mein Kampf as an example of the books sent to him by supporters 'but which I
don't have time to read'.
Much of the 43-year-old Toronto-based businessman's support comes from
younger Poles who grew up during martial law and were too young to
participate in the euphoric rise of Solidarity a decade ago which gave
legitimacy to the present generation of Polish politicians. Often living in
small towns and depressed industrial areas they want a quick, painless way
out of Poland's deep and painful economic trough.
For such people Mr Tyminski offers opposition to the government's wage
restraint - 'wage controls are very ugly with 300 per cent inflation', he
says. 'The government should have stopped printing money and making
unfavourable trade deals with the Russians. They should open the books of
state enterprises and publish a profit and loss account for each one.'
He promises 'my party will create the conditions for growth. We'll take an
inventory of state assets, change the accounting laws, abolish the popiwek
wages tax and change the tax system. Everyone will pay 50 per cent of his
income in tax, but will earn much more money. Poles think 50-50 is fair,' he
says.
Few, if any, of his ideas, stand up to conventional economic analysis. But
they sound good enough to millions of Poles for whom the rapid transition
from rags to riches, personified by Mr Tyminski's own modest fortune and
exotic past, is infinitely more appealing than the hard grind promised by
the new post-communist establishment. For Stan Tyminski read Walter Mitty.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV Photograph Warning] Stan Tyminski, electoral graffiti in
Russian (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1975</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Survey of Poland (7): Shaping up for the first free,
multi-party elections - Christopher Bobinski and Anthony Robinson examine
the emerging post-communist political geography
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI and ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BY ONE of those ironies of fate Poland, which was the first former Warsaw
Pact country to break away from communist rule, is now the last to hold
free, multi-party elections. Even Albanians have been to the polls, while
post-communist Poland's political geography will become clear only after
elections this autumn.
This means that parliament is still dominated by deputies from the old
communist establishment who were guaranteed a two-thirds majority in the
lower house by the so-called 'round table agreement' between the Solidarity
movement and the Communist party two years ago.
Mr Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the first non-communist prime minister, decided to
keep this agreement intact and patriotically concentrated on solving
Poland's pressing economic and other problems rather than dissolve
parliament and call new elections. But he fell foul of the presidential
ambitions of Mr Lech Walesa and mounting economic difficulties as his
government pushed ahead with a tough IMF-backed economic stabilisation plan
named after Mr Leszek Balcerowicz, the finance minister.
So instead of parliamentary elections Poland held presidential elections
last November and December at the insistence of Mr Walesa, Solidarity's
historic leader. After an unexpectedly tough challenge from Mr Stan
Tyminski, a previously unknown Polish-Canadian businessman, Mr Walesa won 77
per cent of the vote in the second round to become Poland's first elected
president. He inherited the powers of his communist predecessor, General
Wojciech Jaruzelski.
Mr Mazowiecki's government resigned and the new president virtually
hand-picked a new government. It is led by Mr Jan Krzysztof Bielecki, a
former Solidarity underground activist and 'liberal' free marketeer from
Gdansk, but retains Finance Minister Leszek Balcerowicz from the old
government. His IMF-backed economic stabilisation plan, while fiercely
criticised during the presidential election campaign, is recognised as a key
element in Poland's international credibility.
The outcome of this autumn's elections will hinge largely on the eventual
shape of the electoral law now being debated in parliament. Behind an
apparently arcane debate on the relative merits of proportional or
first-past-the-post voting systems lie important political considerations
affecting the future division of powers between the presidency and the
parliament.
Mr Walesa makes no secret of his admiration for Poland's pre-war strongman,
Marshall Jozef Pilsudski, or his interest in the presidential powers once
wielded by General Charles de Gaulle. But the exact definition of
presidential powers remains to be finalised by the next parliament.
Proportional representation alone could lead to the proliferation of small
parties which would keep parliament relatively weak. But some of Mr Walesa's
closest advisers, such as Mr Jaroslaw Kaczynski, now argue that it would be
better to have a few large parties and fear that a UK-style
first-past-the-post system could also favour candidates like Mr Tyminski, in
multi-candidate elections. A rather complex compromise with greater emphasis
on the proportional aspect is now being considered.
The elections will see a contest between the various political groups and
parties which over the past 18 months have evolved out of the former
Solidarity movement.
Much divides the parties. But they share a fear of Mr Tyminski, who won a
quarter of the vote in the first round of the presidential elections,
beating Mr Mazowiecki, the then prime minister and Mr Walesa's main rival,
into third place.
'His appeal is so primitive that people of average intelligence only shrug
their shoulders in disbelief that anyone can take him seriously, but it
brings in votes,' says Mr Kaczynski, who, as well as being the head of Mr
Walesa's presidential office is also the leader of the Centre Agreement,
which hopes to develop into a right of centre Christian Democratic party
similar to West Germany's Christian Democratic Union (CDU).
Mr Tyminski's mixture of nationalism, nostalgia for the old communist-style
welfare net and promise of capitalist enrichment struck a sympathetic cord
with many threatened by unemployment and falling incomes. He is now busily
organising a new party called Party X, which opponents say is staffed by
shady characters from the old regime. He will not be able to stand for
parliament himself as the new electoral law includes a five-year residential
requirement for candidates.
The political spectrum aside from the X party is rich and varied and no
party can call President Walesa its own. Indeed, he stresses that he wants
to play an independent role above the political arena.
The old ruling communist party disbanded itself after its election debacle
in June 1989. But its post-communist successor, the Social Democrat (SdRP)
party, claims a 60,000 membership and hopes to win between 10 and 15 per
cent of the vote. It is internally divided, however, between a social
democratic fraction, led by Mr Alexander Kwasniewski, and a majority of
nostalgics led by Mr Leszek Miller who hanker after a re-establishment of
the party's former dominance.
The Solidarity trade union, Mr Walesa's old power base and the core of
opposition to the communists for a decade, is also looking for a new, albeit
more modest, political role and continues to feel that it is the ultimate
guardian of the process of change in the country.
The battle for the crucial centre ground is shaping up between Mr
Kaczynski's Centre Agreement and the ROAD group, which includes former
Solidarity activists such as Mr Adam Michnik and Mr Jacek Kuron, who backed
Mr Mazowiecki against Mr Walesa and who now support his Democratic Union,
the former premier's attempt to re-establish a presence in the next
parliament.
Away to the right are the nationalist groups, the largest of which is the
National Christian Union (ZChN), which is most prominent in support of the
Catholic church's campaign to abolish abortion. The Catholic church
continues as a political force even though it has been damaged a little by
its drive to reintroduce religion into schools and opposition to Poland's
liberal abortion laws. The church wants to ensure that the Christian
Democratic strain of Solidarity retains a powerful role.
Meanwhile, recent weeks have seen renewed attempts to forge a coalition of
rural parties angry at the government's farming policies. A united farm vote
could win some 20 per cent of the seats, block agricultural reform policies
and demand protection from foreign competition.
The political picture could change substantially over the next few months,
however, should President Walesa decide that the threat from Mr Tyminski is
strong enough to construct a purely 'presidential' party. Then many
political groups would coalesce around the Belvedere Palace.
</TEXT>
