<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Business Law: The end of the hostile bidder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEO HERZEL and RICHARD SHEPRO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERGERS AND acquisitions have returned to business news headlines in the US,
but the latest transactions are different from those of the 1980s. Large US
and foreign corporations have for the most part replaced leveraged buy-outs
(LBO) promoters and other financial buyers as bidders. The main reason is
that financing for large LBOs and other non-industrial acquisitions has
virtually disappeared.
Whether friendly or hostile, these new bidders do not seem to be primarily
interested in breaking up companies or drastically altering them for quick
financial returns.
The acquisitions that have been announced or completed so far in the 1990s
probably have much to teach us about the likely future of acquisitions for
the remainder of the decade.
The friendly acquisition of MCA by Japan's Matsushita is a key recent
example of an acquisition by a foreign company based on industrial rather
than financial considerations.
Among strictly US acquisitions, the hostile bid for NCR by AT&amp;T, already
more than five months old, has many features in common with the first
hostile acquisition of the 1990s, the successful bid by Georgia Pacific for
Great Northern Nekoosa.
Neither bidder had ever launched a hostile bid before and both were
motivated by industrial concerns. Moreover, both bidders were capable of
financing their bids from their own cash flow and assets. In other words,
they did not have the difficult burden of assuring their lenders of
untroubled access to the cash flow and assets of the target. In both
instances, intense legal battles and proxy contests ensued, but price was
the likely factor in the outcomes.
Although a patient, well-financed, 1990s' bidder is unlikely in the long
term to be thwarted in a hostile offer, hostile bids appear to be as
expensive today as they ever were in the 1980s.
A key reason is that takeover defences remain effective. State statutes and
court decisions strongly favour defence. In addition, there is a large
amount of legal and market pressure on target boards of directors to demand
high prices.
For bidders, on the other hand, there is the real risk of overpayment.
Friendly bidders are not immune from the overpayment problem. This is not
surprising since the markets for hostile and friendly bids are closely
connected.
Rupert Murdoch, for example, was recently quoted in the FT as saying he had
overpaid by Dollars 1bn (Pounds 0.50bn) in his Dollars 3bn acquisition of
Triangle Communications, the publisher of TV Guide.
There are still no perfect takeover defences and there are unlikely ever to
be any. Neither state legislatures nor courts would like to appear to be
blocking all takeovers without regard to price.
For example, in Delaware, by far the most important state for the
incorporation of large public companies, there is concern that if perfect
takeover defences were ever available, institutional investors might
successfully push the administration and Congress towards federal
intervention. This could take the form of a federal law of incorporation
which would eliminate one of Delaware's main sources of revenue.
In particular, it is highly unlikely that state legislatures or courts will
do anything that would eliminate the importance of proxy fights. For one
thing, in the US, the right to vote shares is closely associated with
freedom of speech.
Proxy fights during hostile bids have picked up considerably in importance
in the past few years. The advantage they offer is that they allow a bidder
to elect its own board of directors to circumvent takeover defences.
Much more important, boards tend to abandon defences and negotiate in the
face of a likely defeat in a proxy fight. The disadvantage of proxy fights
for bidders is that they are slow and expensive.
Staggered boards of directors, in which only a third of the seats become
vacant each year, are an obstacle in a proxy contest. In theory, it could
take two years or more to gain control of a target's board. In practice,
however, the prospect of losing a third of the board usually leads to
capitulation.
NCR has a staggered board. The AT&amp;T victory in the March 28 vote was an
important factor in convincing the remaining directors that it was futile
not to negotiate with AT&amp;T. None the less, the stiff NCR defence appears to
have gained its stockholders an additional Dollars 20 per share.
Last year, in a surprising move, the legislature of Massachusetts held an
emergency session to pass a special, highly unusual, law requiring companies
incorporated in Massachusetts to have staggered boards.
The legislation was an unabashed attempt to help a local manufacturer,
Norton, fend off a hostile bid from BTR. Although Norton's defence against
BTR was notably anti-foreigner, Norton, facing an unsuccessful proxy fight
with BTR, eventually allowed itself to be taken over, at a much higher
price, by a French white knight, Compagnie de Saint-Gobain.
On the bidders' side, legal rules also contribute to high prices. There is
no urgent legal pressure on US bidders to avoid paying high prices. While
directors or target companies have to worry about personal liability for
defending too blindly or accepting too low a price in a friendly deal,
directors of bidders have little reason to be concerned about personal
liability.
Moreover, indemnification and liability insurance affect the two kinds of
directors differently. Bidders' directors, even if found liable, are likely
to be indemnified by the corporation without question.
Target directors, on the other hand, face the likelihood after a takeover of
a costly fight with the new owners of the corporation and directors and
officers' liability insurers to obtain indemnification or insurance
coverage, unless they settle before the takeover is completed.
There is still no perfect way to protect an agreement for a friendly
acquisition of a public company from higher, competing hostile bids.
In the 1980s, anyone planning a friendly acquisition or merger had to worry
about competition from highly aggressive, effective financial bidders.
However, today, likely sources of competition are usually limited to other
industrial bidders and their number appears to be sharply reduced. For
example, Matsushita faced no competition in its bid for MCA. And no
competing bidder has emerged for NCR.
A quick comeback for financial bidders is unlikely for a long time. The
machinery for doing 1980s-style leveraged acquisition deals has been largely
dismantled.
Lenders' and investors' attitudes have turned chilly and the political
atmosphere for financial bidders is negative due to the insider trading
scandals and disillusion with leverage.
Prospects for the success of domestic and foreign industrial bidders are
much more favourable because of the elimination of the highly potent,
flexible competition from financial buyers.
However, a cheap dollar should not be considered an advantage for foreign
bidders. Cheap dollars paid by foreign bidders get cheap dollars back. For
foreign bidders who want to speculate that the dollar will appreciate, there
are simpler, less risky ways than acquisitions.
Nevertheless, a surge in hostile bids by foreigners in the US is unlikely.
In the past, most bidders from countries other than Britain wisely avoided
hostile bids in the US. A proliferation of hostile foreign bids would
probably result in a swift negative political response.
Companies in countries such as Japan or Germany are particularly vulnerable
because their industries are highly competitive with US industries and
widely believed to be protected from hostile foreign bids and, in the case
of Japan, other forms of foreign competition.
Hostile bids by foreigners, therefore, are likely to remain scarce. On the
other hand, there are plenty of opportunities for friendly, negotiated
acquisitions in the US, at high prices.
The authors partners in the US law firm Mayer, Brown &amp; Platt.
</TEXT>
