<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Philips gains 6.2% after
quarterly figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUYING interest focused on Philips yesterday, as most bourses were closed
for the May Day holiday, writes Our Markets Staff.
AMSTERDAM was pleasantly surprised by Philips' performance in the first
quarter of 1991. The shares rose Fl 1.70 or 6.2 per cent to Fl 29 after the
company reported much better-than-expected net profits.
Philips apart, trading was quiet after Tuesday's holiday and in the absence
of continental investors. The CBS tendency index lost 0.1 to 95.4.
Aegon, the insurer, recovered Fl 2.10 to Fl 124.80. The stock has been weak
since the insurer said recently that it planned to reduce the conversion
price on an convertible bond as well as issue a new convertible bond next
year.
COPENHAGEN was helped by an excess of liquidity, following Tuesday's
postponement of a bank strike set for May 10. The bourse index rose 2.08 to
346.95.
Novo Nordisk, which attracted demand in New York overnight, was the most
active stock, rising DKr7 to DKr424 with 108,600 shares traded. Danisco
gained DKr12 to DKr947 after announcing the purchase of eight sugar
factories in eastern Europe.
ISTANBUL recovered half the losses recorded earlier this week as investors
picked up bargains. A cheaper dollar and fresh cash inflow of around L1
trillion, after a government bond matured, contributed to the recovery. The
75-share index gained 235.06 or 6.6 per cent to 3,789.31.
South Africa was closed yesterday for Workers' Day.
