<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Australia is top bond
performer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA was the top-performing bond market in April, both in US dollar and
local currency terms, according to JP Morgan's Government Bond Index
Monitor.
All the government bond markets showed positive returns last month in local
currency terms, but Australia led with a 2.56 per cent gain. The Australian
market was boosted by falling yields, and headed the performance tables in
US dollar terms with a 3.43 per cent return, helped by a moderate currency
gain.
Over the past year, the Australian market has shown a 26.67 per cent return
in local currency terms (31.9 per cent gain in US dollar terms), making it
the second best performing bond market after the UK.
Apart from the UK gilts market, all the European government bond markets
showed strong returns of more than 1 per cent in April.
Japan was the worst performing bond market in local currency terms, with
only a 0.15 per cent increase. However, the strong appreciation of the yen
meant that Japan showed a 3.25 per cent gain in US dollar terms and
therefore ranked second after Australia.
France, Spain and Australia have shown the strongest gains since the start
of 1991, with returns of 8.64, 8.26, and 8.03 per cent respectively.
Japanese government bonds showed the best return in April in sterling terms,
according to Kemper Investment Management Company.
For a sterling-based investor, the return on Japanese government bonds was
5.08 per cent in April. New Zealand showed a 4.84 per cent gain and
Australia a 4.4 per cent gain.
</TEXT>
