<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / International Company News: An uncertain future in Brazil -
A report on the effects of economic instability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUGGESTING someone invest in Brazil these days has all the connotations of
asking, 'Would you buy a used car from this man?' about a dubious character
in a scruffy raincoat.
The country, which in the 1970s was 'the' place to invest, with annual
growth rates of 10 per cent and in the 1980s was a place to sit tight and
occasionally reap very high profits, has in the 1990s become a sour taste in
the mouths of many multi-nationals.
After five economic shocks and price freezes in as many years and an
inflation record resembling a series of heart attacks on an
electrocardiograph, foreign companies operating in Brazil have grown used to
uncertainty.
But, as a result of President Fernando Collor's tight monetary policy and
the ensuing 4.6 per cent contraction in the economy, this year for the first
time has seen a wave of multi-nationals putting the blame for poor results
worldwide largely on their Brazilian subsidiaries.
There is little sympathy to be found in the corridors of Brasilia. Mr Marcos
Azambuja, director-general of Brazil's Foreign Ministry, protests:
'Multi-nationals have got too used to expecting Brazil to lay them golden
eggs every year.'
But, as recession deepens and Brazil reels from its latest economic
stabilisation plan, the situation is expected to worsen. After years of
faith in the future, many multi-nationals are now thinking seriously about
whether to stay. Some have already gone - generally those with smaller
investments or with factories elsewhere in Latin America. Those who have
stayed are currently slashing investment projects and laying off employees.
'It's wartime in Brazil,' said Mr Folke Asell, head of Electrolux Brazil.
So bad is the situation that in February a group of multi-nationals claiming
to represent 90 per cent of their colleagues presented a scathing report to
the economy minister, describing why Brazil was no longer an attractive
investment. It concluded: 'It is not possible to integrate with the first
world through third world policies.'
What happened last year to make multi-nationals so angry? Most, publicly at
least, had welcomed the free market ambitions of President Collor, who took
office last March promising a new Brazil and his ending of price controls,
even if privately some jibed at the idea of losing long-held monopolies.
The 41-year-old president's first mistake was to seize remittances of
foreign companies along with 80 per cent of national assets frozen in a
drastic liquidity squeeze, raising more than an eyebrow in headquarters
worldwide. Only after intense lobbying were the remittances freed last
autumn.
By then, the economy seemed to be moving again, after three months of almost
standstill. But an over-valued cruzeiro ruined competition of exports, and
by the last quarter the tight monetary policy, which is an integral part of
President Collor's anti-inflation plan, was having its effect, bringing
results most described as catastrophic.
Published results to November showed 38 per cent of companies were suffering
losses, and since then sales have fallen dramatically.
By the end of last year, when inflation was running once more above 20 per
cent a month and industrial activity in Brazil's largest city, Sao Paulo,
had fallen by 11 per cent, the Collor plan seemed all bad effects and no
good results. Real interest rates were, at more than 10 per cent a month,
perhaps the highest in the world. The unfavourable exchange rate meant
companies could no longer use the traditional escape route of exports and
those committed to contracts took a beating. When this was finally adjusted
with a rapid devaluation in November and December, it was too late for many.
In search of a scapegoat for the failure of their policies, the government
turned on multi-nationals, particularly Autolatina, the holding company for
Ford and Volkswagen, and the pharmaceutical companies, and summoned them
unceremoniously to Brasilia to explain 'abusive price-rises.' Mr Edson Musa,
president of Rhodia, Brazilian subsidiary of the France's Rhone Poulenc,
called the move 'economic terrorism.'
The final blow to the government's credibility was the introduction of a
plan in February freezing wages and prices, despite previous insistence this
would not happen.
A repeated criticism by foreign companies is the uncertainty of the exchange
rate. Last year, devaluation at 1,333.8 per cent failed to keep up with
inflation of 1,794.9 per cent. One company hard-hit by this was Autolatina,
which ended last year with losses and has been shedding workers in reaction
to a 20 per cent fall in sales since November.
Mr James Donaldson, the company's managing director, is fed up: 'Brazil has
gone backwards. Car production has dropped 25 per cent since 1980. So far is
Brazil from the solid export base we expected that we are now shifting some
production to Kentucky.'
Also affected was General Electric's subsidiary in Brazil - their second
biggest. With 40 per cent of its business made up by exports and most of the
rest by government contracts, the company suffered both sides with the
cutting of state spending. According to its financial director, Mr Don
McBride: 'We broke even with probably enough in dollar terms.' Owed Dollars
27m by the government, the company has cut production in three divisions and
Mr McBride said there may soon be lay-offs once it finishes its backlog of
orders.
Mr McBride is not optimistic about the future: 'We will restructure to the
size of the market and must at some point in the future decide if we want to
be in the market at all. . . It's a big market. It's hard to throw away.'
Black &amp; Decker, Phillips and Parker are among those companies which have
closed some operations. Parker finds importing pens from Europe cheaper than
producing in Brazil, while Black &amp; Decker can source the market from
elsewhere in Latin America. Foreign banks, such as First Chicago, hit by the
global recession, turned to Brazil first when it closed offices.
Others with large investments are holding on. The US company, Caterpillar,
the world's largest producer of earth-moving equipment, says it will stay,
though it is suspending investments and blaming its Brazilian subsidiary for
its 58 per cent fall in profits worldwide. The company's report stated: 'If
the current situation continues, return of our Brazilian operation to profit
is unlikely in 1991.'
Oil companies, too, suffered because the government kept fuel prices low as
part of its anti-inflationary policy. Shell, Esso and Atlantic have all been
operating in the red since November. Shell has cut investment plans this
year by 40 per cent.
Price controls are not the only government intervention multi-nationals
complain about. Brazilian tax on foreign investment is, according to the
multinationals' report, the highest in the world. The Brazilian subsidiary
of the Swedish company, Electrolux, is planning to challenge in court the
high tax on its profit, which in dollar terms translated to losses.
Even the lure of cheap labour and 152m potential market are no longer seen
as enough attraction. There are frequent complaints about shoddy workmanship
and General Electric, for example, has to use seven quality control checks
on just one production line.
Focusing all on defeating inflation at the expense of growth, Brazil is
losing out to other countries, such as Mexico, Venezuela and eastern Europe.
Foreign investment for the first half of 1990 was a negative Dollars 168m.
The situation has not been helped by Brazil's foot-dragging on negotiations
of its foreign debt.
Mr Joel Korn, president of Bank of America in Brazil, warned: 'The longer
Brazil takes to get back on track and project more credibility
internationally, the worse it will be, because some investment decisions
cannot wait.'
A sign that Brazil may finally be waking up to this came last month in the
form of new central bank measures allowing companies to remit profits
without going through the bureaucratic process of registration.
</TEXT>
