<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / International Company News: Aegon plans health care merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AEGON, the second largest insurance group in the Netherlands, plans to merge
its Dutch health care insurance subsidiary with Nuts, a domestic mutual
health group, in a bid to increase its market share and take advantage of
economies of scale.
The new insurer, to be called Nuts-Aegon, will be the second-largest private
health insurer in the Netherlands, after Zilveren Kruis, with annual premium
income of around Fl 570m (Dollars 300m). Aegon will hold slightly less than
50 per cent of the new company's shares, with Nuts owning the rest.
Together, Aegon and Nuts handle the health insurance of nearly 500,000
people in the Netherlands.
The planned merger, which is due to take effect in January 1992, follows the
breakdown of talks in late 1990 between Aegon, Nationale-Nederlanden and
Delta Lloyd on co-operating in health insurance. The talks foundered after
Nat-Ned announced plans to merge with NMB Postbank and to use its new
distribution channel to sell insurance alongside its traditional links with
independent insurance brokers.
Delta Lloyd, a subsidiary of Commercial Union of the UK, intends to use some
of Nuts-Aegon's services, starting with such areas as computer processing
and the buying of health care at hospitals and clinics.
</TEXT>
