<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / International Company News: Chrysler follows the trend with
Dollars 598m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHRYSLER, the financially stretched US motor manufacturer, yesterday
continued the American industry's dismal set of first-quarter results by
announcing a net loss of Dollars 598m.
Mr Lee Iacocca, Chrysler's chairman, said bluntly: 'The quarter was abysmal.
Industry volume simply collapsed and, as a result, we suffered our worst car
and truck retail sales since the first quarter of 1983.'
The US industry has been hit by a sharp downturn in consumer demand, due to
the Gulf war and recession, at a time when it was already suffering from
overcapacity. On Tuesday, General Motors announced a first-quarter loss of
Dollars 1.17bn, excluding special items, and Ford reported losses of Dollars
884m.
Chrysler, the smallest of Detroit's Big Three, is financially most
vulnerable to the downturn. It requires heavy capital expenditure over the
next two years to introduce a new range of cars which are needed to bolster
its market share.
The loss, representing Dollars 2.66 a share, compared with net income of
Dollars 71m, or 32 cents a share, in the same period last year. The loss was
Dollars 341m when the company excluded a one-time charge for a change in
accounting methods, but this lower figure was also affected by special
factors - on the negative side, Dollars 199m of costs for cuts in the
company's salaried workforce, and on the positive side a Dollars 242m
after-tax credit for a reduction in costs associated with its acquisition of
American Motors in 1987. Revenues dropped from Dollars 7.63bn to Dollars
5.8bn.
Mr Iacocca said retail buyers had simply dropped out of the market during
the quarter and the company was forced to take on rental business which
required very expensive marketing incentives.
Chrysler's assembly plants ran at less than half capacity during the
quarter, and it built 115,600 fewer units during the period than in the
fourth quarter of last year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 29
</PAGE>
