<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Book Review: A modern American morality tale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DAISY CHAIN: HOW BORROWED BILLIONS SANK A TEXAS S&amp;L By James O'Shea
Pocket Books, Dollars 19.95, 351 pages
THE GREATEST-EVER BANK ROBBERY: THE COLLAPSE OF THE SAVINGS AND LOAN
INDUSTRY By Martin Mayer Scribners, Dollars 24.95, 354 pages
Imagine more than a dozen financial scandals with the notoriety of the
Guinness affair, and involving the write-off of a third of the assets of the
building societies: you then have an inkling of the scale of the US savings
and loan disaster. It is the largest financial collapse - and taxpayer
rescue - in modern times.
The story remains little known across the Atlantic. Perhaps it is because
savings and loans, also known as thrifts, are an unfamiliar, peculiarly
American institution. The very size of the losses may also be a turn-off.
Some numbers are just too big to grasp. The US taxpayer will have to provide
at least Dollars 150bn (Pounds 88bn) and probably more (at current prices
and ignoring cumulative interest costs), even though the direct economic
impact will be smaller since most of the money is a transfer from the
taxpayer to protect existing depositors.
The disaster is one of the most fascinating business stories of the past
generation. It touches much of American society. There are plenty of
villains: crooks using every known device in the history of fraud to plunder
savings and loans; lax members of top accounting and law firms willing to
bend rules in search of fat fees; greedy Wall Street securities houses
putting money wherever the return is highest; weak politicians looking for
campaign contributions; blinkered ideologues in the Reagan administration;
and ineffective regulators.
Thrifts, with their inherent mismatch between borrowing short and then
lending long at fixed rates, were at first protected by caps on interest
rates for deposits and mortgages. But they faced growing pressure in the
1970s as rates rose and money market funds were devised to compete with
them.
The much-criticised deregulation of a decade ago was a response to that
initial squeeze. First, interest rates were uncapped, then thrifts were
freed to raise and invest money where they wanted.
The real problem was the Federal government guarantee of deposits up to
Dollars 100,000. As thrifts shifted from mutual to joint-stock operation,
for a new generation of owners this was an irresistible invitation to gamble
with little risk as the taxpayer stood ready to pick up losses. The early
Reaganites never accepted that, with such a one-sided guarantee, prudent
supervision was necessary to accompany deregulation.
These two books are among the liveliest of more than a dozen recounting the
saga. At one level it is a morality tale of the pitfalls of deposit
insurance. Despite a condescending, know-it-all style, Martin Mayer
revealingly explains how a problem of unprofitability in the early 1980s
turned into one of insolvency by the end of the decade.
The saga is also an absorbing yarn in the manner of the tabloids. James
O'Shea exploits this to the full by concentrating on the rise and fall of
Vernon Savings of Dallas, Texas, which, under the guidance of Don Dixon,
boosted its deposits almost 20-fold in five years and collapsed with 96 per
cent of its loans being delinquent.
Vernon fully lived up to the Texan self-image of the American Dream taken to
often grotesque excess. Dixon believed in living well - witness his
'gastronomique fantastique' tour of France to do research for a
'world-class' restaurant in Dallas (part of what was dubbed the
rent-a-Frenchman programme). There were jets, luxury houses, collections of
luxury cars and guns, and the hiring of prostitutes. Vernon was not alone.
Stanley Adams, regarded as eccentric even by Texas standards, once applied
to the state regulator to open a branch on the moon, saying 'what the hell,
they laughed at Da Vinci too'.
Vernon was rated one of the most profitable US thrifts. Something was
obviously wrong. Vernon was exploiting to the full, and beyond, lax
accounting rules about what it could declare as profits. Developers were
given loans well over the appraised value of a project to permit payment of
fees and interest. Losses were never written off and fictitious profits were
booked as a result of friendly 'dead horse for a dead cow' deals as dubious
projects were exchanged with fellow thrift owners in similar trouble.
When the oil price fell in the mid-1980s and the Texas property market went
sour, Vernon and other thrifts became engaged in desperate manoeuvring with
increasingly worried regulators in the hope of deferring the end. Friendly
politicians, to whom contributions had been made, were called in to help
persuade regulators to be sympathetic. In the similar case of Lincoln
Savings, Charles Keating donated more than Dollars 2m to five US senators in
the specific expectation that they would help him.
The resulting delays and some inept decisions by regulators raised the
losses, which for Vernon are likely to cost US taxpayers Dollars 1.3bn. Last
month Dixon received the lenient sentence of five years in prison for 23
counts of fraud and racketeering.
Amid all the retrospective hand-wringing, Congress is determined to avoid
making the same mistakes in the case of the banks. But there are big
differences in reform proposals. The US Treasury's plan for the banks
tightens, rather than relaxes, supervision and specifies that insured
deposits cannot be used in risky ventures. Yet many in Congress are
reluctant to contemplate sensible changes in banking structure, allowing a
wider range of activities which would attract more capital and avoid a
repetition of the savings and loan collapse. There is a risk that in
fighting the last war Congress may lose the current one.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23
</PAGE>
