<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Leading Article: Japanese cars and the EC
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
CLAIMS BY some members of the European Commission that its recent outline
proposals for limiting Japanese car sales are a victory for free-trade
principles indicate how far its deliberations have descended into
double-think. The most likely outcome will be to cushion inefficient
European carmakers and ensure windfall profits for Japanese producers at the
expense of EC consumers.
In the name of unifying the EC market, Brussels proposes to negotiate
'transitional' restraints on the growth of Japanese car sales in the five
countries where imports are currently subject to national curbs. The planned
controls, intended to last until 1998 or 1999, would be enforced by Japanese
'monitoring' of deliveries. It is hardly surprising that the Japanese see
benefits in such arrangements. EC controls would enable them to set higher
prices and earn fatter margins than if there were free competition. That is
what happened after Japanese carmakers agreed to voluntary restraints on
exports to the US in 1981.
If the EC wants to give its car industry time to adjust to competition, it
would be more sensible to negotiate a temporary increase in tariffs on car
imports, as it would be entitled to do by international trade rules. That
would, at least, ensure that the benefits of high prices went to the
Community rather than to the Japanese. It would also establish a formal
institutional mechanism - lacking from Brussels' proposals - for ending the
period of protection.
Implicit control
Why did Brussels not choose that option? Partly because the controls it is
contemplating will extend beyond imports to output from Japanese-owned
assembly 'transplants' inside the Community. That has not been made
explicit, if only because it would violate the Rome Treaty. Yet in practice
Brussels aims to include both sources of supply when it comes to fixing
precise limits on sales. If growth of shipments from one source threatened
to breach the overall ceiling, the Japanese would be expected to adjust by
reducing supplies from the other. In short, the EC is out to create a
cartel.
Some defenders of EC policy claim no great harm will be done, because the
eventual limits will reflect the 'natural' sales growth which the Japanese
would have achieved if the EC market were fully open. Apart from the
difficulty of second-guessing sales trends for the rest of the decade, the
argument begs the question of why the restrictions are needed at all.
Arbitrary proposals
The arbitrary nature of the proposals also invites other distortions and
uncertainties. Suppose Honda acquired full control of Rover, with which it
already collaborates on model development: would Rover's output then count
as 'Japanese' or as 'European'? How would the EC treat output from 50/50
joint ventures owned by Japanese and European partners?
It may be argued that, unsatisfactory as the EC's means are, they are
justified by its ends - a completely open car market before the end of the
decade. However, that pre-supposes either that the Commission will have the
courage to resist political pressure to extend the restrictions when they
are due to lapse; or that European carmakers will have improved their
competitive position so dramatically that they no longer require protection.
Events to date do not inspire great confidence in either assumption.
Independent analyses suggest that the efficiency of the European car
industry lags so far behind the Japanese that it will need many years of
effort to draw even. Furthermore, few European carmakers have built a broad
international sales base, rendering them exceptionally vulnerable to keener
Japanese competition in their home markets.
Japanese cars sell well because customers want to buy them. Continued
restrictions not only deny consumers choice and distort the allocation of
economic resources; all the evidence suggests that they would deprive
European producers of the most powerful incentive to take the painful
measures essential to their long-term survival.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
