<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Leading Article: A flawed referendum
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TO JUDGE by the way the two larger parties have campaigned, today's local
elections are regarded by both the leader of the opposition and the prime
minister as a referendum, or super opinion poll, on whether the time is
right for Mr John Major to call a general election. There is a precedent for
this. The victories scored by Conservatives in the equivalent local contests
four years ago helped to convince Mrs Margaret Thatcher that June would be a
good time to go to the country.
The portents were right: the Conservatives won handsomely. Yet if a
judgement on the Tories' prospects of winning a fourth term in government
was all that was required the prime minister could make do with the far less
expensive series of sample polls available on a more or less continuous
basis. Local elections should be about more than that.
They do provide an opportunity to the electorate to hold local authorities
to account. Today more than 12,250 council seats will be contested in 296
district councils in England and 37 in Wales, as well as in the 36
all-purpose metropolitan authorities. London and Scotland are in a fallow
voting year, but this remains the biggest series of elections in the
four-year cycle of local contests. It is also among the most complicated: in
124 of the districts and in all the larger authorities only a third of the
incumbents must offer themselves for re-election each year.
Financial muddle
The complications extend beyond the generally opaque structure of local
administration. Finance is a worse muddle. Most potential voters will be
receiving Community Charge demands about now. The law provides that these
state the name of the precepting authority - that is, whether it is the
district, the county, the parish, or the borough. Citizens who possess
magnifying glasses and unlimited spare time, not to mention advanced
mathematical skills, may then calculate which council is responsible for
which portion of the poll tax.
This may be set against the individual's perception of the standard of
service provided for the money demanded - although that too will be
difficult if the unfortunate elector has not earned a degree in the
functions of local government and is therefore not precisely aware of which
service is the responsibility of which body. That hurdle surmounted, the
responsible local voter may then sit down to estimate how much local
expenditure is in fact locally financed and therefore likely to be affected
by her or his vote and how much is either a normal government grant or the
special Pounds 140 'vote Conservative' bribe proffered in the Budget.
Voter apathy
It is therefore hardly surprising that many voters do not bother to go to
the polling booth at all. If the average turnout today is 40 per cent or
more of the names on the registration lists the general verdict will be that
turnout has been pretty good. This is not to say that there is no element of
accountability. The expectation is that the Liberal Democrats, who have no
chance of becoming the next government, may score more heavily in votes cast
for them than they do in the current opinion polls. That implies that some
of the minority of voters who take part in local elections do draw a
distinction between local authorities and the standing of the parties
nationally.
This is not good enough. If Britain is to have a healthy local democracy it
must be accountable to those who vote for it. Both main parties now propose
to abolish county councils, which would be a useful simplification, but not
enough in itself. There must be a relationship between the provision of
services and their financing that the average voter can understand. The poll
tax was designed to achieve that; it failed.
In seeking a substitute the Liberal Democrats have proposed a local income
tax. Labour proposes that the local determination of business rates be
restored. But its proposals are heavily qualified. The Conservatives, by
restricting the future financing of local government to a single 'council
tax' that can encompass at best 11 per cent of costs, seem to have abandoned
the search for genuine accountability.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
