<DOCNO>FT911-2042</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEBBRAA4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910502
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Bill set to become law soon - War
crimes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE War Crimes Bill, rejected by peers on Tuesday night, will become law
without further debate in the next few weeks, under the rarely-used
procedures allowing the Commons to overrule the Lords.
A police unit of detectives and support staff has already been assembled to
investigate the handful of cases in which further investigations were
recommended by the inquiry report which led to the bill.
Some Tory MPs, however, yesterday pressed Mr John MacGregor, the leader of
the Commons, to provide time for a further debate, giving MPs an opportunity
to stop the bill taking effect.
Mr Bernard Weatherill, the Speaker, told MPs that following the Lords vote
by 131 to 109 to throw out the bill for a second time, the Commons would ask
for the bill back, so that it could be certified to receive royal assent.
The legislation would allow British citizens alleged to be war criminals, to
be prosecuted for atrocities in German-occupied territories during the
Second World War.
Both the Speaker and Mr MacGregor emphasised that the Parliament Acts
procedures, used for the first time by a Tory administration, came into play
automatically after the bill's defeat.
Mr MacGregor said that the process could stop only if the Commons so
decided, but added he did not intend to provide more time for a debate,
since MPs had made their views known on several occasions, passing the bill
twice with substantial majority.
Mr Ivor Stanbrook, and Mr Robert Adley, Tory MPs and opponents of the bill,
asked Mr MacGregor how the Commons could direct otherwise unless it had time
to debate the question.
Mr MacGregor was supported by Mr John Cunningham, the shadow leader of the
Commons, who called for the procedures to be followed 'without delay', so
that the elected chamber's supremacy would be made clear.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2043</DOCNO>
