<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Testing time for pragmatic Rimmer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CRUNCH comes today for Harry Rimmer, the moderate Labour leader of
Liverpool city council, where six Labour hard left rebels are standing
against official party candidates in the local government elections.
At present he heads a group of 33 moderates in the 67-strong Labour group.
Apart from five neutrals, the rest - who include the six unofficial
candidates - are part of a broad left caucus. All have been either expelled
from the party or suspended.
Mr Rimmer, formerly deputy leader to Mr Keva Coombes, has forced schism on
them by imposing rent rises on council tenants and demanding more than 1,000
redundancies to reduce council overstaffing and combat inefficiency.
After 47 Liverpool Labour councillors failed in their legal appeals against
disqualification from office for financial mismanagement, Mr Rimmer's were
the safe pair of hands in which Labour's moderates put their trust when the
47 eventually went. However, he lasted only five months.
He believed that the government had assessed Liverpool's spending needs too
low and wanted to appeal. The left stopped the process, arguing it gave
Whitehall too much say in Liverpool's budget.
Mr Rimmer resigned. Mr Coombes became leader, but his attempts to balance
left and right proved impossible. After last year's local elections, with
enough newly-elected moderates to back him, Mr Rimmer counter-attacked.
With half the left suspended from the Labour group for voting not to set a
poll tax, Mr Rimmer's camp had a majority, and he forced Mr Coombes out.
Since then he has met the left head on.
Yesterday he joined the board of the Merseyside Development Corporation, a
successful government agency hated by his opponents. Given it was May Day,
he could hardly have staged a better demonstration of pragmatism.
</TEXT>
