<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Criticism of Sunday trade rules is rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER Lilley, trade and industry secretary, yesterday rejected
suggestions that restrictions on Sunday trading in England and Wales had
been made unenforceable by a Court of Appeal decision on Tuesday.
Mr Teddy Taylor, Conservative MP for Southend East and an opponent of the
subordination of UK law to edicts from the European Community, complained in
the Commons that the Appeal Court's ruling had created fresh uncertainty.
The court lifted injunctions banning B&amp;Q, the do-it-yourself chain, and
Wickes Building Supplies from opening stores in West Yorkshire and Somerset
on Sundays. After the ruling, a lawyer for Kirklees Borough Council in West
Yorkshire, one of the councils involved, said the ruling made the Sunday
trading laws 'virtually unenforceable'.
Mr Taylor yesterday called on the government to advise shopkeepers whether
or not they were entitled to open on Sundays, and to inform local
authorities whether they were able to implement the law approved by
parliament.
Mr Lilley said he understood that the decision concerned only the question
of whether local authorities should give undertakings to the court to back
injunctions sought to prohibit Sunday trading.
'If that is right the decision would not appear to cast doubt on Justice
Hoffman's decision last year that the 1950 Shops Act was not incompatible
with the Treaty of Rome', he said.
He concluded that the Appeal Court's decision represented no change 'in the
underlying law' in England and Wales.
</TEXT>
