<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Concern at state cost of personal pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BURDEN on the Exchequer of people contracting out of the State Earnings
Related Pensions Scheme (Serps) is the equivalent of 1.5 pence on the basic
rate of income tax, according to a Commons Public Accounts Committee report
published yesterday.
The cross-party committee expressed concern that the Department of Social
Security had focused on its own staffing needs in assessing the impact of
personal pensions, rather than the 'potentially much more significant
implications for the National Insurance Fund'. It recommended frequent
appraisal of the cost of personal pensions to inform future policy-making.
The PAC report follows last year's findings by the comptroller and
auditor-general that the net cost of encouraging contracting out would
eventually reach Pounds 5.9bn at April 1988 prices.
Reducing the numbers in Serps would produce a saving for the National
Insurance Fund, but this would be greatly exceeded by the cost of the
National Insurance contributions rebate (5.8 per cent of relevant earnings),
the special incentive of 2 per cent of relevant earnings payable until April
1993 and tax relief on the employee's part of the rebate.
As a result of these costs, the National Insurance Fund was in danger of
falling below prudential balance, so the government switched three social
security benefits from the fund to general taxation. The cost of this
transfer for 1990-91 was Pounds 1.8bn, equivalent to a 1.5p rise in the
basic rate of tax.
In estimating the impact of contracting out, the DSS assumed that 500,000
people would take out personal pensions, perhaps rising to 1.75m in due
course.
By April 1990, 4m people had taken out personal pensions and the number was
thought to be still rising. The Government Actuary had prepared estimates of
the long-term savings to the National Insurance Fund based on 500,000, 2m
and 5m contracting out.
But the DSS had used such estimates only to forecast staffing needs,
choosing the lowest figure following the Actuary's advice that there was no
basis for a firm estimate. DSS officials told the committee that levels of
rebate and incentive had been decisions taken by ministers to cut costs of
pensions over the next 40 years.
</TEXT>
