<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / IMF/World Bank Washington 1991: Washington blocks increase
in capital for IFC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US has blocked agreement over an increase in the Dollars 1.3bn capital
of the International Finance Corporation, the private-sector arm of the
World Bank, Stephen Fidler and Peter Norman write.
The setback came in the Development Committee of finance ministers from
industrialised and third world countries, which gives guidance on
development issues to the International Monetary Fund and World Bank. The US
was alone on the 24-strong panel in refusing to agree the increase, but it
has a blocking vote.
The US blocked the capital rise because it wants more done to increase the
involvement of the World Bank itself in the private sector. It has suggested
that 50 per cent of the lending of the World Bank group, including the IFC,
should be directed towards the private sector by 1995.
If enough is done by the World Bank to this end, the US has suggested an
increase of Dollars 750m should be discussed. The US is clearly looking for
a greater response to its requests for more private-sector involvement than
the measures so far outlined by the bank.
Mr Barber Conable, World Bank president, expressed disappointment over the
delay. 'We'd like to move ahead as fast as possible,' he said.
The committee achieved more progress on other issues. In dealing with the
problems of the poorest and most heavily indebted developing nations, it set
a deadline of mid-1991 for the Paris Club of creditor nations to review
existing options for debt relief and produce proposals for additional debt
relief measures.
Britain has been pressing for acceptance of proposals known as the Trinidad
terms, which would result in a two-thirds write-off of the stock of official
debt owed by such countries and more generous repayment conditions, in the
hope of achieving agreement on this issue at the London economic summit in
July.
Mr Alejandro Foxley, the committee chairman and finance minister of Chile,
said after the meeting that developing country members felt concern because
of the slower economic growth in the industrial countries and the stalled
Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks.
</TEXT>
