<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Talks to resume soon over HK airport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS ARE to resume between Britain and China soon - possibly next week - in
a final attempt to break the deadlock over Hong Kong's plans to construct a
HKDollars 100bn (Pounds 7.5bn) airport, which would be opened soon after the
colony returns to Chinese sovereignty in 1997.
There is no sign of any new initiative from either side, but both countries
favour a resumption.
If the talks fail it is likely Hong Kong businessmen will quickly submit a
private sector-led plan as a catalyst to save the project, possibly by
creating a consortium that could include the Hong Kong and Chinese
governments. This might enable the two governments to move away from
entrenched positions.
Several of the colony's top business names - including Mr Li Ka-shing and
the Hongkong and Shanghai Bank - are holding private talks. But no plan will
be proposed unless there is deadlock at a diplomatic level.
Mr Gordon Wu, a Hong Kong entrepreneur, held discussions in Peking 10 days
ago with senior officials about plans he has been promoting for five years.
This infuriated the Hong Kong government, which has secured pledges from Mr
Wu and other local businessmen that they will not make further moves for the
time being.
China has been demanding since early last year a say over the airport for a
mixture of political and economic reasons. It is concerned about the size of
the project and the extent to which it will drain Hong Kong's HKDollars 72bn
fiscal reserves and build up debt repayments after 1997.
Mr John Major, the British prime minister, is believed to have reviewed the
current impasse at the end of last week with Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary, who failed to reach agreement during talks in Peking early last
month. Mr Hurd warned then that the project might be shelved if China
demanded an unacceptably large degree of control.
The diplomatic initiative has passed from Hong Kong to London because
China's right to interfere in the territory's affairs is limited by a 1984
Sino-British joint declaration on the 1997 handover.
Britain and Hong Kong argue that China is attempting to breach the
declaration by demanding effective control over the airport development. It
is also believed to be using the airport to establish a precedent to gain
power over other key government decisions, ranging from fiscal policy to the
appointment of judges on a new court of final appeal.
</TEXT>
