FT  02 MAY 91 / Turkey and Iran unite on need for refugee return
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TURKEY and Iran have agreed on the need for nearly 2m Iraqi refugees who
have flooded across their borders to return home as soon as possible, the
Turkish Foreign Ministry said yesterday, Our Foreign Staff reports.
As Kurdish refugees trudged down the mountains on the Turkey-Iraq frontier
towards the allied 'safe haven' around the Iraqi town of Zakho, President
Turgut Ozal was hosting a visit by President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani of
Iran.
'We have no divergence of opinion on this matter,' a Turkish Foreign
Ministry official said. 'Both countries think these people constitute an
element of instability caused by the (Iraqi) administration and they must be
repatriated as soon as possible.'
Thousands of Iraqi refugees, most of them Kurds, have returned to Iraq since
Monday, although their progress in vehicles and on foot was slowed yesterday
by heavy rains. 'It's bedlam in the rain,' said a British Royal Marine.
A UN official in Ankara, however, said the UN was concerned that the
repatriation was moving too quickly and without due regard for the wishes of
the refugees and their long-term security.
In Geneva, the International Committee of the Red Cross said it was setting
up seven reception camps to accommodate 100,000 refugees along the Iranian
border with Iraq.
Jalal Talabani (right) of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan and Masoud
Barzani of the Kurdish Democratic Party, arm-in-arm at meetings between
Kurdish leaders at Shaqlawa in northern Iraq
</TEXT>
