<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Hungary goes west with a new urgency: The
challenge is to compensate for a shrinking Soviet market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR LASZLO Csaba, adviser to Hungary's finance minister, calls it the
country's moment of truth: can it gain access to the west - which means the
European Community - quickly enough to offset the shrinking of eastern
markets?
Last year Hungary succeeded in increasing exports to the west almost as fast
as those to its eastern neighbours fell. But now it has to run even faster
just to stand still.
Some decline was feared when the region abandoned the old system of
state-to-state trading at the beginning of the year. But the extent of the
disintegration of the Soviet Union's economy has taken everyone by surprise.
There is, say Budapest officials, simply no one to talk to about trade and
not the hard currency in the Soviet Union to pay for it.
Exports to the Soviet Union, which was Hungary's largest trading partner,
have plummeted to a fraction of their former level. It is a collapse with
few peacetime precedents.
There is also doubt about whether the EC will match its supportive rhetoric
with what Hungary needs most: an association agreement which gives market
access, especially for agricultural products.
Moreover, economists are unsure how much longer Hungarian companies can keep
up their export drive to the west.
Eastern Europe's move to trading on a commercial basis in dollars from the
beginning of this year was a leap inthe dark. The new picture, now that its
outlines are emerging, are ugly.
The Soviet Union took only Dollars 85m, or 4 per cent, of Hungary's
hard-currency exports in the first quarter. The level of trade falls well
below contracted exports of nearly Dollars 1.5bn for the whole of 1991.
It is an even smaller fraction of the Soviet Union's former weight. In 1980,
the Soviet Union took 31 per cent of Hungarian exports; in 1989 the figure
was still as much as 25 per cent.
The only relief is that it is by definition hitting bottom and it is no
longer so painful to write off a recovery in Soviet demand.
The advice from Mr Csaba, who is Hungary's leading independent expert on
east European trade, to those still relying on the Soviet market is blunt:
'Forget it as quickly as possible.'
But companies dependent on Soviet customers and their allied bureaucrats
cannot forget so easily.
The old way of exporting to eastern Europe was comfortable. Exporters dealt
with undemanding customers who ordered in huge quantities. Not only that,
but they were paid in domestic currency by their own central bank as soon as
goods crossed the border. The central authorities were left to settle the
bills in a unit of account called the transferable rouble.
Hungary's exporters were so enthusiastic that they left the central bank
with a shaky trade claim of Dollars 1.8bn against the Soviet Union. Trade
officials, fearing for the 500,000 jobs dependent on the Soviet Union,
restrained exporters less than they might have.
The willingness to continue funding exports to an insolvent customer was
'fundamentally mistaken', Mr Csaba says. 'It was based on the premise that,
once the Soviet government says it will pay, it will be in a position to
pay.'
But, having been burnt itself, Hungary is now seeking help from the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development for a trade credit to bring
hard-currency exports to the Soviet Union to life.
Another hope, less fraught with danger, is that the Soviet authorities will
lift their ban on barter. Then deals of Ikarus buses in exchange for Tyumen
oil and management advice for marble could proliferate without the need for
rare hard currency to lubricate the exchanges.
But whatever happens, Hungarian economists are counting on a decline in
trade turnover of more than half.
The only market which could make up for the loss of Soviet orders is the EC.
Exports to the EC rose by a quarter last year, overtaking exports to eastern
Europe, which fell by a quarter. But Hungary needs to repeat that
performance.
So far the signs are good. Exports to the EC were Dollars 1bn in the first
quarter of 1991, 56 per cent up on the year-earlier period, impressive even
after discounting for seasonal factors.
The performance helped to give Hungary a Dollars 150m current account
surplus in the first quarter.
Nevertheless, most of the exports which could easily be re-orientated have
been. Further export growth will depend on Hungary's association and
asymmetric free-trade agreement with the EC, which is being negotiated and
is scheduled to come into effect in January 1992.
The EC has conceded symbolic ground to break an impasse on negotiations. But
the Community has made no concrete concessions on Hungary's agricultural
exports to it, which make up a third of deliveries. All it has said is that
products of particular national importance will be given better treatment.
Hungary hopes this includes beef.
But even an open EC will not save some Hungarian products - those so tightly
bound to the Soviet market that they will live or die with it, such as table
wines. Some were produced - by accident almost - from vines planted to
stabilise sandy earth.
The best that could be said of the products is that they are cheap and
serviceable, and in demand in the Soviet Union. Mr Csaba is less charitable
when he explains why they cannot be sold anywhere else: 'They are unfit for
human consumption.'
</TEXT>
