FT  01 MAY 91 / Setback for Perez government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOE MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE forced resignation of a key Venezuelan official this week points to
strong differences on economic policy among government agencies.
Ms Gabriela Febres Cordero, head of the Venezuelan government's Foreign
Trade Institute (ICE) resigned on Monday after she suggested in the press
that problems in expanding Venezuela's non-traditional exports were due
mainly to the lack of a coherent industrial policy.
Ms Febres Cordero's departure means that the government of President Carlos
Andres Perez has lost one of its most effective defenders of economic
reform.
One of the main goals of the Perez administration has been to boost
non-traditional exports in an economy dominated by the state-owned petroleum
industry. Non-petroleum exports have tapered off in recent months, making it
unlikely that the government can reach its goal of Dollars 4bn in
non-traditional exports this year.
