<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLAGTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Raid for Tootal stock
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPE'S largest textile group Coats Viyella mounted what could be the final
attack on its fellow textile company Tootal yesterday. Coats raised the
terms of its offer and then tried to win control more quickly by raiding the
market for stock. Around 10 1/2 m shares were believed to have been bought
at the same level as the new bid price, with Coats willing to purchase 65m
which would take its shareholding over 50 per cent. Trading volume in Tootal
jumped to 22m shares.
The only surprise about the latest offer was the cash element. All-paper
terms had been confidently anticipated, but Coats increased the original bid
of 65p cash per share to 80p and threw in for good measure the Tootal final
dividend of 3.05p; there is an alternative offer, comprising a mixture of
shares and cash.
Mr Mark Finnie of Hoare Govett echoed the sentiments of several analysts by
saying: 'At this level I would expect the deal to go through'. Tootal closed
5 up at 84p and Coats 3 down at 138p.
Allied-Lyons rise
The inconsistencies of the wider market failed to deter another flurry of
speculative activity in drinks and food major Allied-Lyons. Stories began
circulating again of a bid from Hanson, although a more plausible reason for
the upturn was a buy recommendation from an influential broking house.
A sector researcher described Allied as 'the best sitting duck in the
market'. When the risks and rewards are weighed up, he said, there are
likely to be outbreaks of speculative enthusiasm.
The early retirement of both the chairman and chief executive of
Allied-Lyons is awaiting confirmation. Cynics point to the group being
rudderless in terms of management, and this may have given rise to the
latest round of speculation. Allied settled 18 ahead at 545p on turnover of
4m shares.
Drug patent dispute
Glaxo fell 27 to 1097p as sentiment was depressed by a law suit from rival
SmithKline Beecham alleging Glaxo's anti-nausea drug Zofran infringed its
patent. Glaxo said it would defend its position.
Analysts played down the issue. Mr Robin Gilbert at James Capel said the
lawsuit was unlikely to return to the headlines for some time as the case
progressed through the US legal system. Mr Steve Plag at County NatWest said
the two companies would probably come to some royalty agreement which would
have 'miniscule' financial consequences.
SmithKline firmed a penny to 805p, a good performance given the dollar's
retreat during the session. Traders said Glaxo had actually gained ground in
dollar terms.
BET reaps reward
BET, the business services group, began to reap the rewards yesterday of
presentations to US investment institutions. According to the market, these
have been well received and transatlantic buying interest has since
increased to quite substantial volumes. American support contributed to high
turnover yesterday of 4.7m shares, although demand from UK investors also
rose.
The latter were starting to focus on the yield, exactly 10 per cent when
trading opened yesterday. This is high for a Footsie stock. BET said in
February when the shares were under attack that it saw no reason to expect a
reduction in total dividend for the year to March 31, 1991. The group should
report preliminary figures in mid-June. BET shares ended 9 higher at 182p.
The stoic performance of British Gas shares on Monday, in response to the
company's acceptance of Ofgas's revised pricing formula, gave way yesterday.
Domestic and overseas institutions were heavy sellers of the stock after the
bearish response by the press to the Ofgas moves. Gas shares dipped to 235p
and closed a net 8 off at 236p on 15m turnover.
Exploration and production (E &amp; P) stocks bore the brunt of persistent
selling pressure generated by a bearish review of the sub-sector by Strauss
Turnbull. The broker acknowledged it had taken a pessimistic view of E &amp; P
issues, with the emphasis on the large downside potential in Lasmo, 8 off at
350p, and Enterprise, 4 easier at 560p. Strauss's only positive
recommendations in the area were Premier and Clyde, whose shares have
already sharply underperformed, Strauss said.
Ultramar fell to 309 1/2 p before closing a net 7 lower at 312p, with an
attempted placing of around 2m shares at 315p only partially successful; the
Seaq delayed ticker showed a line of 768,000 shares traded for cash at 311p.
Suggestions that institutions had been unravelling the Water Package and
selling on some of the constituents ahead of tomorrow's local elections put
the water sector under renewed downward pressure.
Specialists said the selling had come from UK and overseas funds. The
Package dropped 43 to Pounds 2940. Of the individual stocks, there was
significant selling of Welsh Water, 7 lower at 319p, Yorkshire, also 7 off
at 305p, and Thames, 6 cheaper at 305p.
The electricity issues held up well, albeit in thin trading. Manweb was
prominent, up 4 at 237p, as was Seeboard, which climbed the same amount to
195p.
Kingfisher was boosted after the Court of Appeal lifted an injunction
banning B &amp; Q, its home improvements chain, from opening on Sundays. The
injunction against Wickes' building supplies was also removed. Kingfisher
firmed 2 to 497p, while Wickes gained 2 at 60p. Boots, which with WH Smith
(up 4 at 374p), jointly own the Do It All home improvements chain, put on 3
to 369p, although they were not involved in yesterday's legal action.
Asda continued to weaken as speculation about poor trading company's
meetings with brokers last week has done little to arrest the growing belief
that the food retailer is being squeezed by J. Sainsbury and Tesco. Asda
closed a penny lower at 119p; the shares have fallen 11 per cent since the
middle of April.
Unilever was off 10 at 738p as investors continued to switch out of the plc
and into the NV shares, which are quoted in the Netherlands and New York.
The shares were also depressed by suggestions that a broker would lower its
profits forecast.
There was an increase in activity in NatWest during the afternoon, with the
shares rallying to close a shade better on the day at 325p, after 320p;
turnover totalled 8.2m shares. Midland, ahead of tomorrow's annual meeting,
lost 7 to 215p on 3.5m. First National Finance fell 12 to 193p after a
broker's downgrading.
William Baird was affected more by the prospect of greater liquidity in the
stock, said traders, than the cash call of Pounds 39m through a rights
issue. The shares, previously tightly held, dropped 20 to 238p.
A confident statement and increased dividend distribution outweighed
slightly lower annual profits from Yule Catto, and at the close the stock
was 10 higher at 143p. The company expects to maintain momentum both in
earnings and dividend growth, providing recessionary conditions do not
deteriorate further.
The warning at yesterday's annual meeting that interim profits 'will fall
significantly short' of those achieved in the same period last year lowered
Torday &amp; Carlisle 36 to 118p.
Automated Security Holdings, the London-based security systems group,
slipped 6 to 223p after announcing its intention to issue Pounds 60m worth
of convertible capital bonds, yielding 9.5 per cent and convertible in 2006
at 250p a share. ASH accompanied the news with a confident statement on
current trading, which it said showed turnover in the first four months of
the year ahead of the same period last year.
ASH said it was raising the money to take advantage of growth opportunities
in Europe and the US, adding that it had applied for a US listing for its
ordinary shares.
Greycoat fell 11 to 327p as brokers continued to trim their forecasts ahead
of the final results expected in June. Smith New Court cut its net asset
value estimate for 1990/91 to 500p from 560p, bringing it in line with other
brokers. Office rental values in central London are still weakening and show
no signs of recovering this year, according to Smith.
Evered Bardon fell to 92 1/2 p immediately following the preliminary
figures, but later steadied to close a net 4 off at 94p. Specialists said
the group would struggle to achieve current year profits above Pounds 30m
and that a rights issue to reduce its gearing of around 60 per cent could be
expected in the not-too-distant future.
