<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Foreign Exchanges: Discount rate cut hits dollar
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR fell sharply after the US Federal Reserve cut its discount rate
to 5.5 from 6.0 per cent yesterday.
US President George Bush appeared pleased with the move. He said that 'this
will stimulate our economy' as it climbs out of recession, and added that
commercial banks are expected to follow suit with rate reductions.
By the time of the London close a small but leading US provincial bank, the
Southwest Bank of St Louis, had lowered its prime lending rate to 8 3/4 from
9 per cent.
Economic news also tended to push the dollar down, US factory orders showing
a fall of 2.8 per cent in March against a February decline of 0.6 per cent.
The Chicago Purchasing Management Association Index fell to 42.1 from 45.9
per cent, ahead of today's release of the National Association of Purchasing
Managers Index, indicating that the important industrial area of northern
Illinois and northwest Indiana remains in recession.
At the London close the dollar had dropped to DM1.7170 from DM1.7690; to
Y136.30 from Y137.60; to SFr1.4490 from SFr1.4840; and to FFr5.8025 from
FFr5.9650. Its index fell 1.3 to 65.9.
The D-Mark improved across the board after Mr Horst Koehler, German Finance
Ministry state secretary, said in Washington that he does not expect the
Bundesbank to cut rates. He said this before the US move, but sentiment in
Frankfurt suggests that Germany is still unlikely to ease policy in the
immediate future.
In London the D-Mark rose to Y79.40 from Y77.80 against the Japanese
currency, to FFr3.3795 from FFr3.3720 against the French franc and to
L739.65 from L738.25 in terms of the Italian lira.
A senior official at the Bank of Japan indicated that his country has no
plans to match the US rate cut. Earlier in the day Mr Ryutaro Hashimoto,
Japanese finance minister, said Japan has no need to change its monetary
policy.
Within the European exchange rate mechanism, the D-Mark was steady around
the middle of the system. The Spanish peseta remained the strongest member
and the French franc the weakest.
Sterling eased to fourth from third strongest position in the ERM, trading
below the peseta, Italian lira and Belgian franc. The pound improved against
the dollar and the Japanese yen, but otherwise showed mixed changes.
The US discount rate reduction led to an easing of wholesale rates in
London, and the market was nervous ahead of tomorrow's local government
elections in England and Wales. These may provide guidance on the timing of
the next UK general election.
Sterling rebounded 4.70 cents to Dollars 1.7240. It also rose to Y235.00
from Y230.75 and to SFr2.4975 from SFr2.4875, but dipped to DM2.9600 from
DM2.9675 and was unchanged at FFr10.0025. The pound's index gained 0.7 to
91.4. In New York sterling finished 75 points higher at Dollars 1.7315.
</TEXT>
