<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLAGOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Government Bonds: Treasuries
advance after Fed's surprise cut in rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON and SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOND prices firmed at both ends of the market yesterday after the Federal
Reserve unexpectedly cut the discount rate and signalled a lower Fed funds
rate.
In late trading the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond was up  5/32 at 96 1/2 ,
to yield 8.183 per cent. The two-year note was up  5/32 at 100 3/8 ,
yielding 6.779 per cent.
The Fed's decision to lower the discount rate from 6 per cent to 5 1/2 per
cent stunned the market, which had been convinced that the Fed's refusal to
cut rates a few weeks ago following bad jobless figures and good inflation
data, and its recent operations in the credit markets, indicated that the
authorities were determined not to loosen monetary policy any further.
The rate cut suggested that the Fed was more worried about the state of the
economy than the markets had previously thought, said analysts. Yesterday's
figures showing a 2.8 per cent decline in March factory orders and a weak
purchasing managers' index for April reinforced the view that the economy is
taking a long time to come out of its current slump.
The relatively subdued response to the rate cut from the long end of the
market was down to a reluctance among dealers to push prices up too high
before next week's big auctions of three-year, 10-year and 30-year bonds.
Although the discount rate move was unexpected, the Fed's pre-noon
intervention in the credit markets was anticipated. The Fed conducted
Dollars 3bn in customer repurchase agreements to add reserves to the banking
system, a move designed to push the Fed funds rate to a new target of 5 3/4
per cent. Fed funds did hit 5 3/4 per cent during the day, but by late
afternoon the rate had firmed to 5 15/16 per cent.
GERMAN government bond prices showed strong gains yesterday following the
0.5 per cent cut in US interest rates, which killed fears that the
Bundesbank might raise German interest rates at Thursday's council meeting.
Traders said that prices firmed across the yield curve and they expected to
see some buying of shorter dated bunds now that there was less chance of an
interest rate increase. They noted that there had already been some buying
of shorter-dated bunds before the US cut was announced as investors moved
out of longer-dated bunds.
The D-Mark firmed after Mr Horst Koehler, state secretary in the Finance
Ministry, said in Washington he saw no chance of Germany cutting interest
rates for the time being.
The Bundesbank yesterday accepted bids for a total of DM40.4bn in a
two-tranche tender for securities repurchase funds. It offered DM29.5bn of
34-day funds at 8.6 per cent and DM10.9bn of 62-day funds, mostly at 8.9 per
cent, which means that a net DM4.9bn will be drained from the market.
Traders said that yesterday's pay strike by more than 200,000 western German
engineering workers was a cause of concern to the market.
Critics of the engineering workers' wage demand say their 10 per cent claim
threatens to slow economic growth in western Germany and throttle the east
German recovery, and the union's demands have evoked strong criticism from
the Bundesbank as well as from employers.
JAPANESE government bond yields fell against the background of lower US
interest rates and rekindled hopes that the Bank of Japan would cut the
official discount rate soon.
The yield on the benchmark No 129 government bond dropped two basis points,
from 6.73 per cent to 6.71 per cent, in London as soon as the US discount
rate cut was announced.
The yield opened at 6.705 per cent in Tokyo and dipped to 6.69 per cent
before closing at 6.73 per cent. Traders said they expected to see a
flattening of Japan's inverse yield curve as yields at the short end came
down. The strengthening of the yen against the dollar should make it easier
for the Bank of Japan to countenance a cut in the official discount rate.
However, Japan's finance minister, Mr Ryutaro Hashimoto, yesterday echoed a
statement from a Bank of Japan official in Washington to the effect that
Japan would not match the US rate cut.
UK government bond prices rose yesterday with shorter maturity bonds gaining
more than long-dated gilts, in response to the US rate cut.
Trading began in a gloomy mood following the results of the Confederation of
British Industry industrial trends survey, which indicated that an upturn in
the British economy was still some way off. However, prices recovered after
the US announcement.
The benchmark 11 3/4 gilt due 2003/07 rose from 109 15/16 to 110 1/16 to
yield 10.245 per cent.
THE FRENCH Treasury said it would offer FFr6bn-FFr8bn of tap stock (OAT)
tranches at its next monthly auction tomorrow. The new 9.50 per cent OAT due
2001 will be one of the taps on offer and will become the 10-year benchmark
as its liquidity increases.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
