<DOCNO>FT911-2089</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLAGMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Company News: De Havilland bid awaiting
approval
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NAPLES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE JOINT Franco-Italian bid for de Havilland, the Canadian aircraft maker
owned by Boeing of the US, should be allowed to go ahead, despite strong
local political and union opposition to the deal, said Mr Fausto Cereti,
chairman of the Italian aerospace group Alenia.
He was speaking at the first shareholders' meeting of Alenia, the company
created by the merger in December of Aeritalia and Selenia, the Italian
state-owned aircraft and defence electronics companies. Mr Cereti confirmed
that Canadian government approval for the de Havilland acquisition was still
some way off.
Negotiations between Alenia and Aerospatiale, its French partner, and
Investment Canada, the Canadian federal body responsible for vetting foreign
investment projects, were 'in a preliminary phase', he said.
Presenting Alenia's first post-merger figures, Mr Cereti announced a sharp
cut in the dividend to L90 a share from the L130 paid by Aeritalia in its
last full year as an independent company in 1989. Selenia was not previously
quoted.
Mr Cereti blamed the decline on new uncertainties in Italian and
international defence spending following the collapse of the eastern bloc.
Changes in Italian defence policy have already damaged Alenia's cash-flow.
Working capital and net borrowing rose sharply last year after the
government's decision to pay a much lower proportion of the value of its
defence contracts in advance. Overall group sales amounted to L4,900bn
(Dollars 3.8bn), while net profits were L101bn.
</TEXT>
