<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Company News: Japanese to raise stake in
Brazilian steel mill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN obstacle hindering Brazil's first significant privatisation - that of
Usiminas, its largest steel mill - was removed yesterday with the signing of
an accord substantially raising the equity of the company's Japanese
shareholders.
After months of negotiations it was agreed that Nippon Usiminas, a Nippon
Steel-led consortium of 54 Japanese companies as well as the Japanese
government, would have its stake in Usiminas increased from 4.6 per cent to
13 per cent.
Usiminas was established in 1958 as a joint Brazilian-Japanese venture to
provide steel for the motor and naval industries. The Japanese put up 52 per
cent of the capital and retained 40 per cent of the equity, the maximum
allowed.
But government price controls on steel to subsidise other industries, and
more recently to keep down inflation, prevented it becoming the profitable
venture envisaged. So, as Brazil increased investment in Usiminas, the
Japanese cut their participation to hold only 25 per cent of the equity.
The real blow came in 1976 when all state steel companies were brought under
the control of Siderbras which, through redirecting tax reimbursements, cut
the equity participation of Nippon Usiminas from 25 per cent to 4.6 per
cent.
</TEXT>
