<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SQUARE D, the Illinois electrical equipment maker that is fighting off a
takeover bid by France's Groupe Schneider, yesterday postponed its annual
meeting for a second time. The meeting is now scheduled for June 21, rather
than May 24.
The company said the meeting was rescheduled 'so that the substantial legal
issues surrounding Schneider's offer and related proxy solicitation can be
resolved and shareholders can be informed.'
It also set a record date of May 23. A record date is the deadline for those
who want to vote at the annual meeting to acquire shares.
In addition, Square D said it had agreed to a request from Schneider that it
put back a hearing date before the US District Court of the Southern
District of New York on its allegations that Schneider's slate of nominees
for the board of directors would violate US anti-trust laws.
The hearing, originally scheduled for May 9 was fixed instead for May 16, or
such other date as the court decided, the company said. Another federal
court hearing, set for May 13, will weigh Square D's claims that Schneider
has violated confidentiality agreements with it.
