<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Budgens
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Judging by the swiftness with which a few institutional investors appear to
have rolled over Budgens' management, it is tempting to conclude that there
was not much left in the company worth fighting for beyond the chairman's
compensation package. Whether the institutions picked the right fight is
another matter.
At this point, it is unclear how the new team proposes to turn the company
around. The problems appear daunting enough to make one wonder whether the
shop doors are being closed far too late. Budgens lacks the critical mass
with which to compete against rival food retailers. In recent years, it has
spent far too much on fancy distribution facilities which are not being
fully utilised. As a consequence, the interest charge is rising and the
balance sheet is deteriorating. Much-needed sale and leaseback deals on its
properties will remain a distant prospect until the property market
improves.
It would be a shame if the move towards better corporate governance were to
be deflected by the odd mistake. But a year from now, it may just be that
the institutions will wish they had cut their losses and sold their shares.
</TEXT>
