<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Coats/Tootal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Shareholders in Coats Viyella and Tootal must be getting fed up. Their
investments have badly underperformed in recent years and the market for UK
textiles is as tough as anyone can remember. Yet far from knuckling down to
sort out their problems, the two companies are bogged down in a bitter
takeover battle which could become self destructive.
That said, Coats' improved offer has been cleverly pitched, even if it is
not exactly a knock-out blow. It still falls short of what Tootal believes
it is worth on the basis of the sector's average multiple. But then the
offer of shares and cash is not bad when you bear in mind that it represents
10 and a half times Tootal's own earnings forecast just two months into its
financial year. No-one is saying that Tootal cannot meet that forecast, but
there must be question marks over the 25 per cent tax charge in the longer
term. The offer is also substantially in excess of net asset value, which
will surely be noted by those who have suffered the successive
disappointments of the last decade.
There is a dilemma, though, even for those who decide that the price is
right. There should be no earnings dilution in the combined group, but the
balance sheet will end up looking stretched. A large goodwill write-off
implies that gearing (counting the preference shares as debt) could be of
the order of 75 per cent. That does not leave much room for manoeuvre if the
upturn disappoints and the US dollar goes the wrong way.
</TEXT>
