<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: The recovery is still on time
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,486.2 (-12.0)
George Bush is not due to face the US electorate until November 1992, over
four months after the latest date that the UK government can go to the
polls. You would not think so from the public frenzy with which the US
authorities are tackling their recession - most obviously in the G7
arm-twisting that preceded yesterday's discount rate cut. The UK
government's relative sang-froid is all the more striking given that some
forecasters are starting to use 4m as the likely unemployment figure next
year and that one manufacturing job in 20 has gone in the past 12 months.
The chancellor can find some comfort in yesterday's Confederation of British
Industry quarterly industrial trends survey. The survey suggests that while
the turning point in the economic cycle may yet be a few months away, the
turning point in business optimism is already with us. That might be enough
to leave the government's - and the market's - expectation of a second-half
economic recovery broadly on schedule.
But the nagging question for the market is whether the upturn will prove
quite as profitable as it has been expecting. Worryingly, the CBI survey
reports a collapse of margins earlier this year as rapidly rising unit costs
slammed into prices which appear to have been slowed much more sharply than
official indicators have suggested.
Looking ahead to the summer, manufacturers' expectations of domestic price
rises are the lowest for 23 years. Those sectors most exposed to
international competition are predicting actual price cuts. The rise in the
dollar may have left industry feeling better about its ability to compete in
export markets; but if the domestic market is to be undermined by lower cost
ERM-based competitors, some, at least, of the currently discounted recovery
in corporate profitability is at risk.
</TEXT>
