<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / ECGD unit may go to foreign buyer: Troubled government sale
branded 'a shambles' as it loses last British bidder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OVERSEAS companies emerged as the most likely winners in the privatisation
of part of the Export Credits Guarantee Department as the deadline for bids
expired yesterday.
The government's sale effort, which has been dogged by a series of
embarrassing setbacks, took another battering after Trade Indemnity, the
last remaining British bidder, declined to put any money on the table.
Trade Indemnity said it made a proposal to collaborate with the government
in export credit insurance but this did not involve a monetary offer to buy
ECGD's short-term export credit insurance business which is for sale.
Mr Peter Lilley, trade and industry secretary, will now have to abandon the
sale or allow the business to pass, probably at a knock-down price, to one
of the only two foreign bidders - Italy's Assicurazioni Generali and NCM of
the Netherlands.
Mr John Hollows, deputy chairman of the British Exporters Association, said
the privatisation was turning into 'a shambles'. He blamed the earlier
withdrawal of Eagle Star, Sun Alliance and Cobac, the privately-owned
Belgian company, on the government's refusal to make an irrevocable
commitment to continue underwriting credits to politically risky developing
countries after the privatisation.
Trade Indemnity's interest in buying the Cardiff-based division has waned
noticeably in recent weeks as it digested a Pounds 29m loss for 1990 amid
fears that its shareholders would baulk at the rights issue needed to
finance a bid.
However, potential bidders have also been disappointed by government sale
documents which reveal limited profit potential at the ECGD division. This
has added to their worries about the strength of its customer base in the
absence of an ability to offer political risk cover on the back of a
government reinsurance scheme.
The privatised company would also be impeded in Europe by tax regulations
treating mandatory reserve requirements on British credit insurance
companies less favourably than those of other community countries.
The government is expected to proceed with the next stage of the sale - an
evaluation of the offers received - followed in about a month's time by the
selection of a preferred bidder.
Although the deal is expected to yield only a minimal return, the government
has paid heavily in embarrassment. After quashing a Commons backbench
rebellion, it has now had to postpone debate of the legislation in the House
of Lords to fend off revolt there.
Mr Tim Sainsbury, trade minister, will discuss political risk with
exporters, who hope he will offer a commitment to an improved facility along
the lines of those open to companies in continental Europe.
False start, Page 8
</TEXT>
