<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / A responsible remedy for UK decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In his Economic Viewpoint (this page, April 18) Samuel Brittan claimed that
Labour's new programme is a return to the policies of the 1960s, was
contemptuous even of the idea of policies for industry, and, astonishingly,
attacked the importance Labour attaches to the best training qualifications
for young people. 'Can you imagine Isambard Kingdom Brunel bothering to
acquire an NVQ (national vocational qualification)? Would he have passed if
he had tried?' he asked.
First Brittan on Brunel: far from being a self-made man Brunel enjoyed the
most thorough of educations. He was sent to a carefully selected school in
Normandy; then to the Lycee Henri IV in Paris (the foremost mathematical
college of its day); then on to an apprenticeship with a leading designer of
scientific instruments.
Of course a hands-off-everything enthusiast for liberal economics would have
preferred him to have sat up late at home with borrowed books, tinkering in
the garden shed and then blossoming to genius without access to the
market-distorting influences of a national institution of higher technical
learning, but the facts are all against this view.
Just as Mr Brittan is wrong about the importance of education to Brunel, he
is wrong too - unlike industry itself and our competitors - about the
importance of education and training to the economy. The NCVQ - which
unifies a disparate and confusing jumble of qualifications - may not succeed
in discovering a hundred future Brunels in Brixton and Birmingham. But it
offers young people all over the UK a better chance than ever before of
reaching a nationally recognised level of training comparable to the
education they might - in many cases ought to - have received if they had
stayed at school.
Labour's argument is that in the late 20th century, when education and
training are even more important to industry than in the early 19th, Britain
is slipping dangerously behind its competitors. Inventions can be bought
across frontiers: only rarely can skills. Where the wealth of nations, and
their competitive advantages, used to depend on raw materials, and on the
inventions of a few, it now depends more and more on the skills,
adaptability and collective effort of the many and it is by the application
of technology through a skilled workforce that countries will succeed. To
trust the market simply as a matter of ideology and to imply that there is
no skills gap that industry, left to itself and the working of the invisible
hand, cannot solve on its own, is quite wrong. The evidence of our
deficiencies in training are there for all to see.
Yet despite all the experience of more successful economies we still hear
the argument that government does best when government does nothing:
likewise that there is no technological challenge the free market cannot
normally solve on its own; no long-term investment gap that needs any action
by government; and of course no long-term problem of regional imbalance that
cannot be settled by waiting until free market neglect begets free market
opportunity.
Yet, as the recent economic achievements of Germany, Japan and France
demonstrate, the facts are otherwise. The view that government should do
nothing is as obsolete as its opposite, that the government can and should
do everything. Nineteenth-century theories of competition have a diminishing
relevance to the 21st century search for competitiveness. For there is
clearly a national interest in working to achieve the best technology and
training - something which goes beyond the particular interest of one
employer and which cannot be left solely to the hazards of the market on its
own.
Mr Brittan accuses Labour of being trapped in the past; it is in fact Mr
Brittan who has failed to break out of the past, unwilling to recognise that
the starting point of Labour's approach is that neither the tired ideology
of crude free market dogma nor that of the command economy has any residual
relevance.
So when Mr Brittan argues that 'it is not possible for a market economist to
support Labour with a straight face', he fails to appreciate that the
difference between the Labour and Conservative parties is not over the
importance of markets but in Labour's recognition of their limitations and
governments' corresponding responsibilities.
Mr Brittan fails to mention the significance our new policy programme
accords to stability in macroeconomic policy - a far cry from the stop-go
economics which have bedevilled our country with two deep recessions despite
the opportunities of North Sea oil; nor the importance we attach to
membership of the Exchange Rate Mechanism.
Within these disciplines the job of government is not to replace
decision-making in industry but to work with industry to meet common
objectives - the specific tasks of improving our skills, upgrading our
technological capabilities, encouraging long-term investment and ensuring
regionally balanced economic growth. Our document is quite specific in
rejecting 'indiscriminate subsidies or second-guessing industry'. Indeed the
public interest is not in politicians trying to make decisions that
companies must make - as in our encouragement of technology trusts,
universities and industry, and of a national training strategy locally
delivered - but in ensuring that specific tasks vital to our long-term
economic effort are accomplished.
Mr Brittan's examination of our document has been so cursory that he
misnames the National Investment Bank as a Board and misunderstands its
role, which is to bring together the public and private sectors with a view
to encouraging new infrastructure investment.
Our Manufacturing Investment Initiative is not simply designed to end what
many agree has been discrimination against manufacturing through 12 years of
neglect; it recognises that a modern industrial economy, and the vitality of
the service sector within it, requires modern manufacturing strength.
Britain has lost more manufacturing capacity than any other western European
country in the last 12 years, falling near the bottom of the manufacturing
growth league.
To affirm manufacturing's importance is not to yearn irrationally for a
bygone industrial age but to recognise what our competitors understand: that
it is the principal trading part of the economy. Services and manufacturing
are not starkly exclusive alternatives: they complement each other and feed
on each other's success.
If Labour is so wrong, Mr Brittan must explain why so many overseas
governments of all complexions have pursued similar policies with success
and now regard what we say as commonplace and non-controversial. And if he
agrees with the policies of his one-time co-author, the current industry
secretary, he must also explain why at the end of 12 years of Conservative
government we have had the worst series of trade deficits in our history, a
contraction of industrial capacity as Britain slips further behind, and now
the fastest-rising unemployment in western Europe.
The author is Labour's shadow trade and industry secretary
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19 Photograph Gordon Brown (right), 'To affirm manufacturing's
importance is not to yearn irrationally for a bygone industrial age.'
(Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
