<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Bureaucrats in the heart of the battle: India's election
campaign has taken on an anti-establishment tone - and one target is the
elite civil service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HOUSEGO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As Indian politics has grown more embittered over issues of religion, caste
and regional autonomy, so the western-educated civil service that has
piloted the country since independence is cracking under the strains.
In the run-up to the general election during the week of May 20, the senior
bureaucracy has come under attack on different fronts in campaigns that have
a strong anti-establishment flavour: Former prime minister V P Singh's
left-wing National Front alliance is campaigning on a programme that would
reserve for the poor and lower castes up to 59 per cent of central
government jobs. Mr Singh's revolutionary aim is to wrest control of the
bureaucracy from the upper castes and thus diminish their grip on patronage
and wealth.
Hindu revivalists are angry at the Indian Administrative Service (IAS) - the
elite service that heads the bureaucracy - for upholding secular policies
that they regard as 'pampering Moslems'. The revivalists are contemptuous of
the pro-western, modernising legacy of Jawaharlal Nehru which is reflected
in the IAS.
A growing number of regional movements blame the IAS - often called the
'steel frame' of the Indian union because it provides the link between the
central government and the states - for the country's much-hated
over-centralisation.
The most recent factor in this growing impatience with the civil service is
the current state of the Indian economy. Mismanagement has brought the
country close to defaulting on its international debt and has focused
attention on the shortcomings of the administration in steering economic
development. The civil service is increasingly viewed as one of the major
obstacles to change.
Mr Sam Pitroda, the US-educated Indian electronics engineer who now heads
the telecommunications commission, says: 'There are many capable, highly
motivated bureaucrats. Individually they are innovative. But collectively
they are a roadblock.'
Most worryingly, senior officials seem themselves to have lost confidence in
the system. Under pressure from ruling parties to adopt an increasingly
partisan and political role, looked down on by business which feels that
they easily succumb to bribes, pushed around by criminals who are openly
seeking respectability by entering politics, the IAS has lost its reputation
as a neutral, non-partisan institution.
'Why is it that bureaucrats like to lick the boots of politicians?' one
senior official recalls being asked by one of the new, rough-necked
politicians who had just taken up a post as a central government minister.
In a recent issue of the Indian Journal of Public Administration devoted to
the declining morale in government service, Mr S K Sarkar, a former IAS
officer, begins an article by saying: 'As a member of the Indian
Administrative Service, I have felt considerable anguish in recent years as
a mute spectator to the impending collapse of the civil service in India . .
.'
One indicator of this downward slide is that the best and brightest of
Indian university students are seeking careers elsewhere in management, with
multinationals or in foreign banks. Above all, children of IAS officers shun
a career in a service that was regarded under British rule and until
recently as the pinnacle of achievement.
Most new recruits to the IAS are now coming from the two northern states of
Uttar Pradesh and Bihar - the largest of the 25 states and where corruption
is most endemic and the collapse of administration most apparent.
As the central government has grown weaker and more strife-prone, it has
fallen increasingly to civil servants to keep the wheels turning. But it is
increasingly clear that the civil service cannot function without political
leadership, and that left to itself there is a risk of disruption and
paralysis. If the election fails to produce a central government with a
stable majority, the civil service will fall increasingly prey to caste,
religious, regional, farmers or business lobbies. India has no tradition -
as does France or Italy, for example  - of a civil service providing
continuity in the face of political turmoil.
However, if a strong government or coalition should emerge, then it is
difficult to see how much-needed reforms - decentralisation, deregulation of
industry and improving the performance of the public sector - can be
achieved without an overhaul of the civil service.
The paradox is that the civil service contains many able people but its
performance has been poor. Its main defect since independence has been that
it has failed to adapt the elitist structure left by a colonial power to the
more diverse needs of a developing country democracy.
Britain ruled India through the Indian Civil Service (ICS) - a hand-picked
cadre of 1,000 men imbued with Victorian ideals of hard work, honesty and
dedication, who provided a secretariat for the viceroy and managed districts
the size of a small state.
Some of that ethos is still preserved at Mussoorie, the hill station academy
that trains recruits to the successor IAS service. They are still taught to
ride 'as part of the old belief that if you can't ride a horse you won't be
able to manage a district'. As a colonial service, the ICS was only
concerned with tax collection and law and order. Since independence in 1947
the IAS has taken over most of the welfare and economic responsibilities of
a modern state, including co-ordination of education, health and irrigation.
Its numbers have only increased to 5,000 for a population that has exploded
to 840m.
It is thus overstretched. It presides over a mammoth bureaucracy that
numbers 4m officials in the central government alone. Files can take months
to move back and forth. The IAS recruits a third of its intake by
competitive examination. Each year about 250,000 students apply to take the
civil service exams of which about the first 100 are admitted to the IAS.
In the hierarchy of the IAS, an officer moves up by seniority from a
district post to being a secretary of government (in charge of a department)
or even cabinet secretary. Each officer is attached to a state but is loaned
at different periods in his career to the central government - a structure
intended to minimise separatism in the union and establish a link between
the centre and the states.
Many senior civil servants blame venal, short-sighted politicians for
destroying the IAS's reputation as an honest, non-partisan service. Others
accept that 'civil servants have been their own worst enemies' - too often
sycophantic, fearful of taking a stand against abuses, and financially
profiting from their immense power.
Mr Ajit Mazumdar, a former secretary in the finance ministry, sees the
emergency imposed by Mrs Indira Gandhi in the 1970s to thwart opposition to
her as a watershed. During that time, the administration failed to resist
abuses of the law and constitution by the then prime minister. 'To our
eternal shame none of us resigned,' he said, 'though we felt that wrong
things were being done.'
Since then both state governments and the central government have
increasingly expected senior officials to promote the short-term political
and financial interests of the party in power - transferring those who
refused to toe the line.
As one of the main instruments of economic development, the IAS has tended
to be ultra-cautious - giving priority to issues of social justice and
equitable income distribution over the willingness to take risks that
accompanies higher economic growth.
Part of that reluctance to encourage the risk-taking enterprises that
promote a market economy is a legacy of British rule. After independence the
government left in place a system of war-time controls to regulate industry
and the economy. This went hand in hand with an acceptance of Fabian
socialist beliefs. Intervention was seen as the most efficient instrument
with which to accelerate economic development and to achieve social justice.
Neither has been completely abandoned.
But in the 1980s there were several attempts to shift towards a more market
economy. Mr Rajiv Gandhi began his term as prime minister in 1985 with a
reformist programme of economic liberalisation.
A year ago, when warning signals were already flashing of an approaching
fiscal and balance of payments crisis, Mr Montek Ahluwahlia, then chief
economic adviser to Mr V P Singh, circulated as a cabinet paper a
far-reaching programme of medium-term economic and structural change that
linked deficit-cutting to financial sector and tariff reform. Both ran into
opposition in the bureaucracy.
Change in India must proceed at a pace that is 'politically and socially
sustainable', says Mr Bimal Jalan, finance secretary at the time. Another
senior official says: 'The system is not a speedy system and just as well.
India is not a country on the fast track. It is too dangerous. There would
be risks of arbitrariness, lack of fair play and injustice.'
A gap in the system is that there is no mechanism for studying medium-term
policy options. India has no think-tank with the weight to influence
decisions, or a 'reforms commission' such as China introduced to co-ordinate
economic change. The planning commission - the closest equivalent - is
concerned with the long-term allocation of resources.
A further problem is an obsession with bureaucratic procedures that puts a
premium on civil servants finding fault and discourages innovation. 'I get
more credit if I pitch in with an objection,' complains one official.
The administration has found no way of rewarding performance and punishing
inefficiency. Mr P K Basu, a former permanent secretary, discovered that by
September 1989 cumulative delays on public sector projects in India had
reached a staggering total of 515 years. But no official had been punished.
Unlike France or Britain, where the best civil servants obtain rapid
promotion, India does not have a 'fast track'. An IAS officer cannot expect
to become a permanent secretary until he is 50 and he has to retire at 58.
Poor salaries have encouraged corruption. In the 1930s a senior member of
the ICS earned more than the chief justice of the US Supreme Court. But a
permanent secretary now gets about Rs10,000 (Dollars 500) a month  - and
retires on half the amount.
Many senior officials have remained conspicuously poor and honest. But the
service's reputation for corruption is such that the chance to make large
sums of money illegally is the motivating force behind many students who
seek to join the IAS from UP and Bihar.
One other cloud hangs over the future of the service. Whatever government
comes to power, popular pressure is such that the proportion of jobs
reserved for the poor and backward castes seems bound to increase - with the
consequent damage to efficiency that this type of protectionist measure
entails. Twenty two per cent of jobs in the central government are already
reserved for Harijans (untouchables).
Attempts at reform of the civil service have so far come to nought - and are
unlikely to succeed in the future without strong political leadership. The
gravity of India's political and economic difficulties has none the less
encouraged acceptance of new ideas. Prime Minister Chandra Shekar has talked
of the need for smaller states. Mr L K Advani, the leader of the Hindu
revivalist Bharatiya Janata party, has called for a presidential system. Mr
V P Singh's National Front is urging greater decentralisation.
But a big factor for change will be the pressure that the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and donor nations bring to bear on India to
carry through the structural changes needed to achieve a more competitive
industry and better export performance. As one Indian economist says: 'We
are past the stage of gradualist change.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
