<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Observer: Re-run
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Who was the bright spark at Samuel Montagu, financial adviser to the Pounds
245m Mirror Group Newspapers float, who decided at the last minute to reduce
the size of the limited circulation pathfinder prospectus because it would
make the mailing easier?
Had it not been for Robert Maxwell's eagle eye for detail yesterday's final
version might not have emerged in its full tabloid-sized splendour.
Widespread expectations that the pathfinder version would be produced in
similar Mirror newspaper-style were dashed earlier this month when the
document returned from the printers in ordinary A4 dimensions.
It is said that Cap'n Bob was infuriated when he saw the change, chiefly
because it made the text, arranged in newspaper-like columns, extremely hard
to read. The order went out to print off extra copies in full tabloid size.
Yesterday's final version, with the MGN titles emblazoned across the cover,
was exactly as he wanted to see it.
So no one can accuse him of trying to conceal something nasty in the small
print.
