<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Observer: Sales pitch
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The world's art and property markets may be suffering from indigestion at
the moment but Sotheby's, the ever-optimistic fine art auctioneers, still
thinks it can find someone to pay at least Pounds 55m for a house in Spain.
Admittedly, Barcelona's Casa Batllo is rather special. Designed by the
modernist Catalan architect Antoni Gaudi in 1904 for a wealthy textile
manufacturer, Josep Batllo, the eight-storey house is a national monument.
Its soft curving lines, ornate towers and rooms shaped like water-worn
caves, would make it an ideal home for an arts foundation or a trendy
retailer. Don't forget Barcelona is the site of the next Olympic games.
Iberia Seguros, the insurance company which owns the Gaudi extravaganza,
picked Sotheby's because it wanted someone who knows something about art.
Seguros' president Enrique Bernat, whose Chupa Chups is also the world's
biggest lollipop manufacturer, says the sale 'is like launching a balloon
into the air. It is impossible to put a price on a work of art like this and
we will see how high it will go.'
With that kind of sales pitch, one can see why there is no asking price. But
do I hear Pounds 70m, or 16bn yen?
</TEXT>
