<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Observer: Fighting talk
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Meanwhile, the Labour party's efforts on the City prawn cocktail circuit
seem to be paying handsome dividends judging by yesterday's outburst from
Fidelity's Barry Bateman.
In his first public outing as chairman of the Unit Trust Association,
Bateman savaged the government's wider share ownership policy, calling it as
misguided as the poll tax. 'But wider share ownership is not as big an issue
so it will be difficult to convince the government of the folly of their
ways. There are not many votes in it.'
Undoubtedly the unit trust industry has suffered because the instant profits
provided by successive privatisations have overshadowed the less spectacular
gains of steady long-term investments which suffer front-end charges.
Moreover the government has prevented unit trusts from exploiting the full
juicy potential of personal equity plans.
'If anything, the Labour party seems to know more about wider share
ownership and popular capitalism than the Tory party,' says Bateman.
However, even Bateman draws back from urging his members to put their money
where their mouth is and make a contribution to the Labour party.
</TEXT>
