<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Observer: MAI's left turn
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
If Lords Hanson, King and Sterling can do it, why can a Labour peer not hold
down a full-time job running a publicly quoted company besides moonlighting
in the House of Lords?
The question arises because Clive Hollick - chief executive of MAI, one of
Britain's last surviving financial conglomerates - has just been made a
working Labour peer. Given that MAI has big plans to add a TV franchise to
its rag-bag of money broking and outdoor poster interests, there is a danger
that young Clive, who has another 20 years to go before he collects his old
age pension, might be spreading himself a bit thin. The City has always been
suspicious of socialist chief executives with beards.
Hollick is unrepentant. Having salvaged the group from the 1970s secondary
banking crisis, he has come through the recession with a strong balance
sheet and gently rising profits. He avoided the pitfalls that snared such
bigger groups as Mercantile House and British &amp; Commonwealth, and is kept in
check by a reasonably strong board of non-executive directors led by the
rather elderly Sir Ian Morrow.
Having turned down the idea of buying the New Statesman, Hollick has made
his main political contribution as a driving force behind the Institute for
Public Policy Research. Set up as a rival to Tory think-tanks, it quickly
overcame initial scepticism and is now regarded as having greatly enhanced
Labour's more pragmatic approach.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
