<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Arts: Chamber Orchestra of Europe - Barbican Hall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A mostly Mozart programme brought to a close the 10th birthday series of
concerts given by the Chamber Orchestra of Europe, sponsored by The BOC
Group. That attendences have been so good throughout is hopefully due in no
little measure to the presence of a healthy number of FT readers, attracted
by a special ticket promotion.
After ten years it is possible to take stock. Although the COE players still
only come together for five or six months a year, their playing never lets
on. This is one of the finest chamber orchestras of today, less sumptuous
perhaps in tone than the Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields, but more
flexible than the conductorless Orpheus Chamber Orchestra, among its
immediate rivals. And that second comparison points to the COE's special
character.
For this young orchestra has built close relationships with some of the
world's leading conductors: Abbado, Solti, Harnoncourt (unforgettably at
this same hall two weeks ago). And, for this concert, the eminent Mozartian,
Sandor Vegh. Of all of them, he trusts most to the musicians' instincts and
does no more than necessary, though there were a few moments on Monday when
the players looked as though they would have liked a clear lead and did not
get it.
Vegh came to conducting with fine credentials as a player of chamber music
and it was that spirit of give-and-take, of music being made on an intimate
scale, that gave this evening its own flavour. The opening of Mozart's
Symphony No 29 suggested indeed that the conductor might be about to cosset
the music all too lovingly. But the performance had just enough spirit and
Vegh is always specific, not generalised, in what he wants to say.
A group of five Mozart Contredanses and Wolf's Italian Serenade, genially
smiling, opened to view intimate corners of expression. The best, though,
was Mozart's Sinfonia Concertante, K. 297b, in which four wind soloists from
the orchestra (especially the clarinet, Richard Hosford) distinguished
themselves in the solo parts.
It is that strength of solo performers that has given the COE its enviable
reputation in only a decade.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
