<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Arts: Edward II - The Pit, Barbican
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you want to see a play wrecked by a wrong choice of costume, go to the
Royal Shakespeare Company's Edward II, which has arrived at The Pit from
Stratford. To be fair to the designers, there are a lot more faults in this
production than the wardrobe, but the clothes do set a tone. If you dress
the characters in black and white leather jackets, trousers to go with them,
and heaven knows what the Queen is wearing, you are at a disadvantage from
the start.
For a number of reasons, the production never quite recovers from this
self-inflicted wound. Simon Russell Beale is an actor of great versatility;
he is not, however, one of nature's Edward IIs. The point about the part is
that he has a strong homosexual attraction to his favourites. He is also the
King of England with wars to fight, civil and foreign. To carry this off, in
the court and on the stage, requires a certain style. Beale plays the role
as someone short, fat and stupid who hops about like a bloated frog.
The message may be that you do not have to be beautiful to have homosexual
passions. Yet it would help if there were a certain style. Beale is simply
gross. He never rises to the part. Moreover, he shouts - repeatedly and
unnecessarily. So do much of the rest of the cast. This is not a production
of light and shade.
Edward II, admittedly, is not Christopher Marlowe's best play: not a patch
on Tamburlaine the Great or Dr Faustus. But it does have its moments as well
as unmistakeable affinities with Shakespeare's Richard II. Its greatest
attraction is Piers Gaveston, the King's first favourite. The RSC's
Gaveston, played by Grant Thatcher, comes into his own only when he has been
beaten up and his mouth is covered in blood - like lipstick. By then, he has
little left to say. Before that, he is dressed in his ridiculous white
leather clothes with sequins. The only surprise is that he does not wear an
earring. That is left to the King's next favourite, Spencer, whom we first
see under a sheet with a curate.
The nobles and the clerics are wooden. This may be deliberate. For if the
King does not behave like a king, even a deviant king, the court can hardly
be expected to behave like a court. The general entourage is more like that
of a rotary club faced with unseemly goings on, which cannot have been what
Marlowe intended. There ought also to be room for some humour, since most of
the characters go through a remarkable number of changes of mind. That is
not there either.
The best performance is by Ciaran Hands as the young Mortimer. By the time
he has become an accomplice to murder, his black jacket is decked with
phosphorescent green. For the rest, it is a pretty grim evening. The
direction is by Gerard Murphy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2130</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLAFHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Arts: All for Love - Almeida Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first and - if you want a really short review - only thing to be said
about All for Love is: see it] If you have neither read nor seen the play
before, you will wonder why you remained in such ignorance for so long. If
already acquainted with it, you may still be surprised by the passion that
can be put into it. Either way, you are in for a treat. Diana Rigg goes with
it.
All for Love is John Dryden's version of Antony and Cleopatra. It is not
invidious to make comparisons. Since Dryden was the foremost literary critic
of his age, and no mean poet and dramatist, he knew exactly what he was
doing. He invited the comparison himself. All for Love is not better than
Shakespeare's play; it is just totally different, though in one area I think
that it achieves something that Shakespeare never attempted - that is, frank
talking by a woman about her lovers.
Ms Rigg is not an especially queenly Cleopatra in the sense of wearing robes
and crowns, at least till the end. She plays the part by exuding passion and
not being embarrassed to admit it. True, she went first with Caesar, but
Caesar possessed her person, not her love. She knows the difference between
a wife and a mistress. There are two scenes that could never have appeared
in Shakespeare: one where she explains her feelings to Antony, the other
where she meets his wife (and Caesar's sister) Octavia. This is a kind of
modern psychological drama. Octavia, played by Angela Down emerges as a real
part.
Beside the women, James Laurenson's Antony is a curiously subdued figure.
That is the only query I have about the production. To be sure, he is pretty
down, having lost his empire and his mistress, and continues to be torn
between his love for Cleopatra and his duty to Octavia. But if you make
Antony such a dead-beat, it makes one wonder why people had such regard for
him in the first place.
The admiration for Antony extends to his general, Ventidius. For Dryden did
not write a play simply about the main characters. The lines that go with
Ventidius's suicide scene are among the best quiet dramatic verse that has
been written. Bernard Horsfall, having been slightly unconvincing at the
start, cannot fail to rise to them.
Equally, Dryden fills out the characters around Cleopatra: Charmion and the
Eunuch. Charmion, played by Pauline Jameson, is a rather elderly figure;
Alexas the Eunuch (Alan MacNaughtan) even older. Between them, they seem to
make up the queen's sole court and thus emphasise her loneliness when she is
apart from Antony.
It occurred to me that Jonathan Kent's production could be filmed as it is.
It is pure drama. So much for All for Love being an obscure, academics' play
that seldom needs to be performed. It should now takes its place in the
forefront of English theatre, which is where Dryden thought it belonged.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
