<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Arts: Manon Lescaut - Bastille, Paris
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The amount of opera available in Paris this season is astonishing. In terms
of quantity, at least, the city is currently the world's most varied
operatic emporium. Rarities and novelties of all kinds find outlets at the
Chatelet, pro the Champs-Elysees and the Opera-Comique. At the new Bastille
theatre, in its first full season, a groundplan of repertory works is being
fulfilled. After Otello, Figaro, Berio's Un re in ascolto, and Queen of
Spades comes the Puccini Manon Lescaut; Samson et Dalila, Flute and Katya
Kabanova follow shortly. The list is an intelligent piece of
bread-and-butter planning; the early Puccini opera, a copious lyrical
outpouring of youthful passions, is just the sort of work to set a large
theatre Italianately ringing the way opera audiences love it to do.
At a Manon Lescaut performance in the middle of the run, a uniquely
depressing and alarming experience, that seemed the foremost problem: the
theatre doesn't allow ringing. The acoustics have been the source of
controversy since it was opened, but there can surely be no disagreement
over the wrong-end-of-the-telescope reductive impact they are forcing on
Puccini's vocal lines. Placed anywhere but at the very front of that
incommodiously broad, deep stage, the singers are audible  - but as if their
voices were coming in on the breeze from the next quartier.
As in this unevenly shaped, narratively zigzagging opera it is in the vocal
outbursts, solo or duet, that dramatic impetus is most strongly sustained,
it is impossible to exaggerate the cumulatively disastrous effect of the
acoustics on the voices and on the opera. Puccini distanced, Puccini
prevented from hitting a listener smack in the solar plexus, is Puccini
denatured; the orchestral sound is clear, if not exactly ripe in bloom, but
from pit and stage no sort of musical blend or even balance seems possible.
As if in covert admission of all the theatre's self-generated handicaps, the
production by Robert Carsen seeks to plump out the stage with huge, glitzy
spectacle. The stage is at almost all times chock-full of supers - Mardi
Gras revellers wearing gaudy capes and carrying huge umbrellas, perruqued
and white-powdered courtiers at the stage margins, Act 2 servants in endless
formations. The designs (by Anthony Ward) suggest touches of theatrical
avant-garderie (with mirrors, huge falling drapes, skewed walls) without
making the audience nervous; the tricks of novelty in the staging do
likewise.
It's the latest form of what Brecht deemed 'culinary' entertainment. Since
the production bears surtitles in French and English, and is shared with
Antwerp, it's also, I would say, International Opera in its most worrying
incarnation: opera that looks good, means nothing, can be taken from house
to house, and is capable of supporting a procession of unrehearsed singers
without much damage. For the Manon Lescaut run the house had planned
alternate casts, but on this occasion there were substitutes - unexplained -
for those alternates: the conductor Nello Santi was replaced by Maurizio
Barbacini, the tenor Vasile Moldoveanu by Antonio Ordonez.
In the circumstances, it was something of a miracle that things held
together as well as they did (Mr Barbacini is obviously a conductor worth
trying out in better-ordered conditions); one saluted the professionalism of
Patrick Raftery (Lescaut), and the trenchant delivery of Ian Caley (Edmondo)
and Jules Bastin (Geronte): no holding their voices back] I had been looking
forward to a first hearing of Ordonez, a Spanish tenor who burst on the
European scene a few years ago; the timbre is plangently appealing, but the
loud high phrases are all in overdrive, and on this occasion he simply ran
out of them in Act 3.
The heroine was Barbara Daniels. She is what the Italians call a vero
artista: a performer who communicates warmth and engagement, a sense of the
words, a feeling for the musical style. In these disconnected circumstances
her Manon came across in eye- and ear-catching bursts, not all of a piece;
but at least she came across. It is time for those in charge at the Bastille
to stop pussyfooting about. The scale of the acoustical problems is immense,
and no earthly purpose is served by the continuing denial of their
existence.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2132</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLAFFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Management: Bata takes a step back to its roots -
Paternalism in flux / Bernard Simon talks to the chairman/founder of the
world's largest shoe manufacturer about its trading policies with its former
oppressors in Czechoslovakia and its hopes for consolidating its toehold in
the Soviet Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thomas Bata professes to be opposed to boycotts and sanctions. The company
that bears his name made shoes in Rhodesia under Ian Smith, in Uganda under
Idi Amin, and in Chile under Augusto Pinochet. It withdrew from South Africa
with the greatest reluctance.
But when it comes to dealing with Communists, the forceful chairman of the
world's biggest shoe manufacturer has different ideas. He decided against
buying a Toshiba portable computer because, he says, the Japanese company
sold submarine propellers to the Soviet Union. More significantly, Bata
avoided doing business with his native Czechoslovakia for more than 30 years
after the Communist government took over the family's factories and shops in
the late 1940s.
Now that the Communists are no longer in power in Czechoslovakia and those
in the Soviet Union need all the help they can get, the energetic
76-year-old chairman of Bata Shoe Organisation has good reason to soften his
approach.
'In North America and western Europe, shoes are coming out of people's
ears,' says Bata, whose company sells more than 300m pairs a year, some 60
per cent of them made in its own factories. 'There is only one part of the
world where there is a vacuum for footwear, and that is the Soviet Union.'
In the case of Czechoslovakia, the tug is more sentimental. 'We were not
willing to do business with the Communists because they treated some of our
people in a most disgusting and inhumane manner,' he says. Now, however, 'we
are anxious and willing to do something for the place where we have roots.'
Although Bata denies it, events in eastern Europe have brought another big
change in the family business. Despite Bata's huge presence in footwear, the
public knows little about its far-flung operations.
The family, operating the company privately, still declines to disclose
details of revenues, profits or market share. But it has recently become
much more open in discussing its business interests, especially those in
Czechoslovakia.
Bata owns 40 factories and 6,300 shoe shops in 69 countries, and has 70,000
employees. It has the franchise for Nike sneakers in Chile and for Adidas
shoes in India. It also operates tanneries in 14 countries and a number of
rubber-processing plants.
'The strength of our organisation is survival,' says Tom's soft-spoken but
steely wife Sonja who, as a director of the company, has an office next to
his at the company's modest headquarters in suburban Toronto. Bata's
business in Uganda was twice taken over by the government and twice control
was handed back to Bata. The company was forced to buy a vegetable-exporting
farm in Zambia to provide foreign exchange for imported chemicals for its
shoe factory.
A cornerstone of Bata's strategy has been to locate its factories as far
away as possible from big urban centres, thus holding down wage costs and
discouraging trade union organisers. Its main North American manufacturing
complex, in the company town of Batawa, named after the shoe company and
started in 1939, is located in a rural area between Toronto and Ottawa.
Tom Bata, who is still driven home for lunch most days with his wife when he
is in Toronto, acknowledges that the company's management style, at least
until recently, may best be described as paternalistic.
But he insists that the schools and other amenities provided by the company
were 'not done for the sake of paternalism.' It has a high proportion of
illiterate people and women in its workforce, especially in the Third World,
and Bata says it 'was all done for the sake of making people's work and
their lives easier'.
That management style and much else about Bata is now in flux. Although he
remains an active chairman of the Bata Shoe Organisation, Tom Bata handed
over the chief executive's job six years ago to his son, Thomas Jr. While
father started his working life as an apprentice in a shoe factory in Zlin,
the son is a graduate of Harvard Business School.
With his less forceful son at the helm, the company's senior management is
expected to have greater scope to tackle the business challenges of the
1990s. As a company, Bata is having to adjust to the realities of
increasingly stiff competition from countries where it has little or no
presence, notably China and Taiwan, and to a workforce more mobile (and thus
less loyal) than it used to be.
'Today, our focus is on developing products ourselves and very often having
other people make them for us,' Bata says. In the Third World, that has
meant helping entrepreneurs set up small businesses to supply uppers and
other shoe parts to Bata assembly plants. The company sent a Zambian
manufacturer of tea kettles to Germany to learn how to make the high-quality
steel toecaps needed for mining boots.
In Europe and North America, the focus has shifted to retailing and
specialised high-margin manufacturing. Many of the shoes Bata now sells are
made by other manufacturers, especially in the Far East. Bata has no
factories in the US, but owns 800 shops there. It operates four retail
chains in France, each catering to a different segment of the market.
But it is on eastern Europe that Tom Bata is focusing much of his energy. He
is most expansive when the conversation turns to Czechoslovakia. Although he
left Czechoslovakia in 1932, his emotional attachment to his homeland has
clearly never flickered.
Ten generations of Batas had made shoes in Czechoslovakia before Tom
transferred the family business to Canada in the 1930s ahead of the Nazi
occupation. He left behind one of the country's biggest industrial
conglomerates which, besides its shoe factories and shops, included hosiery,
tyre and synthetic fibre businesses, and even a small aircraft manufacturer.
Before the overthrow of the communist regime in Czechoslovakia in 1989, Tom
Bata broadcast regularly to his former countrymen over Radio Free Europe and
the Voice of America. And when he returned to a hero's welcome in December
1989, his Learjet carried 10 fax machines ordered by Civic Forum.
Bata says he is eager to help put the family's businesses, nationalised in
the late 1940s by the Czech communist government, back on their feet. In the
past year, some 15 Bata executives from other parts of the world have
travelled to Czechoslovakia to provide technical and managerial help. The
company has enrolled 150 of its Czechoslovak employees in basic business
courses, and brought several others to its own corporate seminars in western
Europe. He has lifted his self-imposed boycott and has started buying shoes
from his former factories in Czechoslovakia again.
But some sour notes have crept into the relationship between Prague and its
best-known expatriate. Although the communists never paid any compensation
for the assets they seized, the new government has so far been reluctant to
return the factories and shops to Bata.
The present Czech government is apparently concerned at the Canadian
company's economic muscle, and has up to now insisted that Bata must bid for
its former assets like any other interested investor. While the company is
still hoping that Prague will soften its line, Bata, for his part, says the
businesses have deteriorated more under a centrally-planned economy than he
suspected a year ago.
'The managers had done a marvellous job in keeping the factories going under
the most difficult circumstances,' he says. 'But I could recognise many
parts of the plant as being exactly as I had left them, except that they
were 50 years older. The production planning forms were exactly the same as
they had been 50 years ago, except that in my day there would be one piece
of paper. This time I counted seven pieces.
'The products were very pedestrian, much more like the products we would
normally make in Africa or in our simpler Far East operations. They were
mainly aimed at the Soviet market, where a shoe factory has to guarantee
that a Russian can stand in melting snow for two hours without his feet
getting wet. That is a requirement for the Soviet Union; it is not the type
of requirement which the Czechs or Slovaks would normally want.'
The dilemma for Bata as it seeks to expand its involvement in eastern Europe
again is that the Czech factories will continue for the foreseeable future
to depend heavily on eastbound exports. 'There are some parts of the
business which are not going to survive, particularly if the Soviet market
is lost,' Bata predicts.
He is trying to consolidate his toehold in the Soviet Union, although he is
under no illusions about the problems involved. Bata has started selling
shoes to the Soviets from a factory in India. Using the same skills it has
mastered in parts of Africa, it is also examining the feasibility of helping
the Soviets lengthen the shelf life of the hides of animals slaughtered at
remote abattoirs by siting tanneries close to the abattoirs.
Despite the difficulties, Tom Bata is relaxed about long-term prospects for
the shoe business in eastern Europe and elsewhere. 'From the point of view
of the world economy, we're not that worried,' he says. 'People are not
going to give up shoes the way they've given up hats.'
</TEXT>
