<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): Usdaw votes for and against pay
restraint policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTROVERSY among unions over pay policy under a Labour government was
re-kindled yesterday when the Usdaw shopworkers' union voted both for and
against rejecting any form of wage restraint.
The contradictory votes at the annual conference in Blackpool came after
Usdaw's leaders called for delegates not to rule out wage restraint under
Labour because pay would have to be discussed as part of a national economic
assessment.
Mr Syd Tierney, Usdaw president, said after the votes that he expected the
union's national executive to accept the possibility of wage restraint under
Labour. This would make Usdaw the first union explicitly not to rule out a
form of incomes policy.
The conference voted by 114,723 to 104,887 to reject opposition to 'any wage
restraint policy under this or any future government'. However, it then
voted by 112,005 to 103,821 to 'accept no wage restriction under any
government'.
Mr Tierney said: 'We are in lumber, facing ourselves coming backwards. It is
the worst possible situation we can be in.' He said the executive would take
into account the fact that more delegates voted against opposition to wage
restraint. Usdaw was among the only unions at the Scottish Trades Union
Congress last month to vote against the call to rule out wage restraint.
Mr Garfield Davies, Usdaw general secretary, said that it would be
unrealistic to exclude discussion of wage levels from an economic
assessment. He said that a national minimum wage which helped Usdaw members
would be a form of incomes policy.
Mr Davies said that blanket opposition to wage restraint before a Labour
government came to power could become a millstone around the neck of unions.
He said unions should leave their options open until after an election.
The votes came after controversy over Labour's support for an economic
assessment under which the government, employers and unions would discuss
the economy and its implications for taxation, training and wages each year.
Opposition to the idea in the TUC has been led by the AEU engineering union.
The votes at Usdaw are among the first in a series on wage policy at union
conferences.
</TEXT>
