FT  01 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Lang rejects move for assembly -
Devolution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR IAN LANG, the Scottish secretary, has underlined his continuing
opposition to any form of Scottish assembly, which he says would undermine
the stability of the United Kingdom and bring no benefits to Scotland.
His comments, in an interview with the Financial Times, came amid continuing
speculation that the Scottish Conservatives are planning a big U-turn on the
issue of devolution, which was overwhelmingly rejected at the party's
Scottish conference in 1988 but commands majority support in the Scottish
opinion polls.
A number of prominent Scottish Conservatives have recently proposed various
forms of Scottish assembly.
Mr Michael Hirst, chairman of the Scottish Conservative and Unionist
Association, has indicated that the party is prepared to listen to arguments
on the subject, although it is not down for debate at next month's party
conference.
'I have not the slightest doubt that there would be a serious crisis of
confidence leading to reduced investment and employment and the undermining
of our manufacturing base if we moved along the devolutionary path,' Mr Lang
said. The effects would be the same whether or not the assembly had
tax-raising powers, though without tax-raising powers would take longer to
become apparent.
</TEXT>
