<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Lords set to be overruled - War
Crimes Bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THE first time under a Conservative administration, procedures allowing
the House of Commons to overrule the Lords went into operation in a
confrontation between peers and the government over war crimes.
After a nine-hour debate yesterday, a cross-party alliance of peers defied
the Commons by 131 votes to 109 to reject for a second time legislation
which would enable British citizens who are alleged war criminals to be
tried in UK courts for atrocities committed during the Second World War.
They also condemned the use of the Parliament Acts 1911 and 1949, which
enable a bill passed by the Commons to become law even if the Lords has
rejected it in two successive sessions, on an issue where MPs and peers have
been allowed to vote according to their consciences.
The Lords defeated the same bill last June, by 207 votes to 74, a much
greater margin. MPs have twice approved it by substantial majorities.
The defeat for the bill came despite a last-minute concession by Lord
Waddington, the leader of the Lords. He said that the government would look
sympathetically at amendments suggested by Lord Bridge of Harwich, supported
by other law lords, to increase the prospects of a fair trial.
He also reminded peers that the bill followed an inquiry by two
distinguished prosecutors who had concluded that there were a handful of
cases where there was enough evidence to support a criminal prosecution.
Senior peers from all parties, including former Tory and Labour cabinet
ministers, argued, however, in a series of powerful speeches that the bill
was so fundamentally flawed that even if it were changed, a fair trial would
be impossible and any defendant would face insuperable difficulties in
preparing his case.
Lord Shawcross, a former attorney-general and prosecutor at the Nuremberg
trials, said: 'It is our clear duty and constitutional right to express our
independent views and vote according to conscience.'
Lord Jenkins of Hillhead, the Liberal Democrat leader in the Lords, said
that the use of the Parliament Acts procedures would be a 'constitutional
monstrosity'.
The restrictions on the powers of the Lords were used twice by the Liberal
government in 1914, and once by the Labour government in 1949.
In theory, the government could still prevent the bill becoming law, but it
has made a clear commitment to legislate.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2145</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLAE2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Mellor believes recovery is near -
Finance Bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER claim that Britain was emerging from the economic recession was
made by Mr David Mellor, chief secretary to the Treasury, in the Commons
last night.
He interpreted findings of a CBI survey published earlier in the day as a
clear signal of a 'recovery of confidence'.
Mr Mellor accused Labour MPs of 'talking the economy down' when they cast
doubt on the assertion by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, in Washington on
Monday that recovery was 'round the corner'.
MPs gave a second reading to the Finance Bill - giving effect to the March
Budget - by a majority of 101 (310-209).
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's shadow chief secretary, acknowledged that the
CBI survey showed that some businesses were 'not quite so pessimistic' as
they had been in January.
She argued that the desperate attempts by ministers to obscure their
responsibility for the recession 'fuels the optimism to which they lay
claim'.
Mr Mellor forecast that the recovery of confidence would lead to an increase
in economic activity.
He was adamant that the British economy was far better equipped to get out
of the current recession than it was from the recession in the early 1980s.
The government's optimism was also challenged by Mr Pat Duffy (Lab Sheffield
Attercliffe) who said a survey showed that there had not been a recovery of
confidence among manufacturing employers in South Yorkshire.
expressed by Mr David Winnick (Lab Walsall North) who said the West Midlands
was going through a repeat of the 1980s recession.
Undeterred, Mr Mellor suggested that part of the problem faced by the
manufacturing sector was that 'perception lagged behind reality'.
He received support from Mr Roger King (C Northfield) who stressed that in
terms of exports the British motor car industry was 'doing better than ever
before'.
Mr Mellor praised the export achievements of the car industry which, he
said, reflected the transformation which had taken place in the British
economy in the 1980s.
Mrs Beckett maintained that the government discounted 'alarming evidence'
about the depth of the recession in order to promote its claims that
recovery was at hand.
She said there was a danger that when the recovery did take place it would
prove to be 'shallow and short lived' as the balance of payments constraints
re-emerged.
Mr Ian Taylor (C Esher) criticised the high street banks for imposing a
'higher than necessary' premium when setting interest rates on loans to
their smaller corporate clients. He referred to reports that some banks were
charging more than 2 to 2 1/2 percentage points above base rates.
Mr Taylor also expressed concern that the Lloyds insurance market might be
'at the beginning of a crisis' and urged the Government to consider
permitting 'names' to claim tax relief on current year cash calls.
A warning that the bloodstock industry would be 'greatly disadvantaged' by
the new VAT regime due to come into operation in 1993 was given by Mr
William Powell (C Corby). He urged Treasury minister Mrs Gillian Shephard,
who is to meet industry representatives next week, to try to remedy the
situation.
Mr Francis Maude, financial secretary to the Treasury, defended the new
impost on mobile telephones, insisting that 'a straight forward and modest
scale charge' would reduce the burden on small businesses.
Mr Mellor rejected protests from Conservative backbenchers that the Bill
subjected building societies to double taxation. He insisted that if clause
50 were to be deleted, a number of building societies would make 'windfall
profits' from Pounds 250m tax paid on money from depositors.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10 Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
