<DOCNO>FT911-2146</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLAE1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Parties optimistic about national
poll 'rehearsal' - Local Council Elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday marked the closing stages of the local elections
campaign with a confident claim that the outcome would underline that it is
on course for a fourth general election victory - but not quite yet.
On a day when all of the main contenders in tomorrow's poll announced
advance plans to celebrate their success, Mr Chris Patten delivered an
ebullient assessment of the Conservatives' recent recovery in the opinion
polls.
In a series of characteristically eliptical statements he did nothing to
dispel the impression that Mr John Major, the prime minister, will wait at
least until the Autumn for a general election.
Although the Conservatives' appear to have a fractional lead in the opinion
polls, it is fighting tomorrow's elections from the much higher base it
achieved in 1987, when it was a full 10 points ahead. So this year, Mr
Patten can expect substantial losses in terms of council seats.
The lengthening odds against a June poll - the view at Conservative Central
Office is that the 6 to 1 against offered by the bookmakers is a fair
assessment - did nothing to diminish the energy of Labour's campaigning.
Flanked by senior members of the shadow cabinet, Mr Jack Cunningham, the
party's campaigns manager, indicated that Labour remained determined to keep
national attention focused on its chosen electoral battlegrounds.
The Labour team, which has treated the local elections as a dress-rehearsal
for a general election, produced a sheaf of new figures to reinforce its
attack on the government's handling of the economy.
Mr Tony Blair, the employment spokesman, claimed the recent rise in
unemployment was hitting Tory voters as hard as Labour, while Mr Gordon
Brown, the shadow industry spokesman, offered scores of statistics to
illustrate the decline in Britain's manufacturing base.
Mr Blair said that the rising jobless total - now presented by Labour as a
symbol of the government's wider mismanagement of the economy - demonstrated
that Mr Major had produced a 'classless' recession. White-collar employees
were as badly hit as blue-collar workers, the south as much as the north.
Labour's stance on strictly local issues was helped by another apparent
volte-face by the government on the details of its new council tax.
Whitehall officials said last week that the Government was considering
increasing the number of property bands from 7 to 9. Yesterday, however, Mr
Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, ruled out categorically any
such switch.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, offered the prediction that
his party would do much better than its opinion poll standing suggests. He
argued - correctly - that its performance in recent local elections had
consistently confounded the pundits.
</TEXT>
