<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Banking group chairman accused
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR WALLACE Duncan Smith, chairman of Wallace Smith Trust, a small London
banking and finance group, was yesterday remanded in custody for a week by
Guildhall magistrates on a charge of fraudulent trading.
He was arrested by the City of London police on Monday and held in custody
before being charged.
The police said yesterday that the charge alleged that between January 1
1985 and April 29 1991, in the City of London and elsewhere, Mr Smith was
knowingly party to the carrying on of the business of Wallace Smith Trust
with intent to defraud its creditors.
The charge, under section 458 of the 1985 Companies Act, carries a penalty
of a prison sentence, or a fine, or both. The Serious Fraud Office said
yesterday that it had taken over the case from the City police.
Provisional liquidators were appointed to Wallace Smith Trust yesterday on a
petition by the Bank of England. The company has ceased trading and the
liquidators are realising the outstanding positions. The provisional
liquidators are Mr Tim Hayward and Mr Bill Ratford of KPMG Peat Marwick
McLintock.
According to its latest annual report, the net assets of the bank are about
Pounds 13m. No deposits from the general public are believed to be at risk.
Mr Duncan Smith is one of the backers of the Bruges Group, the pressure
group opposed to European federalism.
Wallace Smith Trust is owned by a trust representing the Smith family, which
has extensive financial interests in Canada. It specialised in dealing in
the money market, and in corporate finance. Its latest accounts show that it
had assets of Pounds 370m, most of which consisted of money market
instruments. Its share capital and reserves amounted to Pounds 13.2m. The
other directors are Mr Michael Hamilton, joint managing director, and Mr JM
Bradley.
In the year ended April 30 1990, it made a profit of Pounds 175,000, down
from Pounds 1.5m the year before. An associated company, Wallace Smith Trust
Group, lost Pounds 1m in the same period.
</TEXT>
