<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Tribunal's pension ruling to face appeal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SHORT, Pensions Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HICK HARGREAVES, the Bolton-based engineering company, is to appeal against
the decision of Manchester industrial tribunal that Mr Alan Roscoe, a former
company employee, had suffered unlawful discrimination on grounds of sex by
being given a reduced pension.
The decision to appeal opens the way for the case to be referred to the
European Court of Justice for clarification of the retrospection aspects of
the Barber v Guardian Royal Exchange judgment nearly a year ago.
The European Court ruled in its Barber judgment that pensions counted as pay
under Article 119 of the Treaty of Rome. But it also stated that to avoid
upsetting the financial balance of schemes, equalisation would apply only to
pension entitlements arising after the date of the judgment - May 17 1990.
That has led to confusion over the definition of pension entitlements.
Mr John Bellis, a chairman of the Manchester industrial tribunal, upheld Mr
Roscoe's contention that as he retired after the date of the judgment he
should have received a full pension at the same level as that of a woman.
Mr Bellis disagreed with Hick Hargreaves, which took the view that it need
only equalise pension benefits accruing from the date of the judgment and
reduced his pension by 27 per cent compared with that of a woman. Mr Roscoe
retired at 60, five years earlier than the company's normal retirement age
for men. The Equal Opportunities Commission, which is backing Mr Roscoe,
hopes to secure an early hearing in the Employment Appeals Tribunal and will
ask it to refer the case to the European Court.
This is the second test case being put forward to clarify the Barber
judgment. Last week, the independent trustees of the Coloroll Group Pension
Schemes announced that they were seeking guidance from the High Court on
winding up the schemes.
</TEXT>
