<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Tokyo warns EC on audio cassette 'dumping'
duties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DULLFORCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE companies could cut their investments in the EC, if Brussels
imposes definitive anti-dumping duties on imports of audio cassettes, Tokyo
warned yesterday.
Japan reserved its right to seek redress from Gatt, should Brussels go ahead
with its plan to make definitive the duties of 14.7-22.3 per cent it imposed
provisionally last November.
The EC Commission is expected to announce its decision shortly, in a case
which has aroused doubt among some EC member states, including the UK, and
strong opposition from foreign exporters.
In sharp terms, Japan told Gatt's anti-dumping committee yesterday that a
decision to make duties on audio cassettes definitive would violate the
anti-dumping code, and have 'a serious adverse effect on inward investment'.
Brussels had failed to demonstrate any causal link between the alleged
dumping by Japanese companies and injury caused to EC industry, Japan said.
The Commission says the market share of the EC industry had fallen from 27
per cent in 1985 to 19 per cent in 1988, while the share of Japanese, Korean
and Hong Kong companies alleged to have dumped had increased from 72 to 81
per cent.
But the share of companies found to have dumped included increased output by
Japanese affiliates in the EC, Japan claimed. Also, the EC allegation of
price-cutting concerned products sold only in Germany, which could not be
construed to constitute injury to the entire EC market.
Separately, Japan complained about the way the EC Commission had been
reviewing duties imposed on electronic typewriters and urged the US to halt
an investigation into the Brother company's production of portable electric
typewriters in the US.
In reviewing the typewriter charges, the Commission had asked Japanese
companies for information on word processor production. This extension of
the investigation could have no relation to a decision on whether to
continue anti-dumping duties on typewriters. It was unnecessarily burdening
the companies and interrupting trade flows, Japan said.
The US Department of Commerce is investigating a complaint by Smith Corona
that Brother is making portable electric typewriters in the US, to
circumvent an anti-dumping duty on imports.
Japan said the percentage by value of the non-Japanese components in
Brother's portable typewriters and word processors produced in the US was
more than 50 per cent. Smith Corona was the main importer of portable
electric typewriters but produced none of its own domestically. The Commerce
Department had opened its investigation without determining whether Smith
Corona's complaint was valid.
</TEXT>
