<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / World Trade News: EC on US priority watch list in
broadcasting row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US has for the first time put the EC on its 'priority watch list' under
the Special 301 provision of its Trade Act, because of barriers to entry of
US TV programming embodied in EC broadcasting legislation.
It has begun a separate action under Title 7 of the Act which could
theoretically end in a ban on public procurement from EC sources. This is
because of alleged EC discrimination against US suppliers in its public
contracts policy.
These moves are seen by Commission officials as pouring fuel on an EC-US
trade relationship already heated by the Uruguay Round transatlantic farm
subsidy row.
The row over the broadcasting directive, which comes into effect on October
3, has been long and vexed. The legislation originally proposed limiting
transmission of non-EC programming to under half, but now merely suggests
this as a guideline.
The alleged discrimination, and the margin of discretion for member states
to implement it, has angered the US. Washington says this will not provide a
single market for US broadcasting exports. The Special 301 move is seen here
as a sign the US wants its complaints 'taken very seriously', a Commission
official said.
The EC has been moved from the 'watch' list to 'priority watch' for the
first time. Germany, Italy, Greece and Spain have separately been on this
list, kept for the most 'onerous' alleged intellectual property
infringements.
Brussels officials say the dispute should be handled within the Uruguay
Round. They say that while the broadcasting directive is not yet law, the US
has failed to implement a 1989 Gatt panel ruling requiring it to cease
discriminating against imports accused of infringing patents.
US products similarly accused got more favourable treatment, Gatt found.
Officials claim the procurement dispute should be settled within the Round,
since the 'buy Europe' provisions the US is attacking are not yet in force.
These would, from 1993, allow buyers for government-regulated utilities to
prefer bids from EC suppliers, if they are no more than 3 per cent dearer
than the best bid from a third country. If no agreement is reached with the
EC in 45 days, the US could hit back with a ban on procurement from European
suppliers.
</TEXT>
