<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Bush will need something to show for China
deal / Review of US relations with Peking as MFN trade status decision looms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By YVONNE PRESTON and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN US official Robert Kimmitt meets trade officials in Peking this week,
he is likely to tell them that his president will find it difficult to renew
China's most favoured nation (MFN) status next month without something to
show for it.
After all, US trade representative Carla Hills has just named China, along
with India and Thailand, a 'Special 301 country', whose trade policy is
'egregious' and harmful to US business. That is not very encouraging to
Peking when the trade balance between the two countries is nearing Dollars
10bn in China's favour.
Nor when human rights voices are still berating President George Bush for
renewing China's MFN status last year when the sound of gunfire in Tiananmen
Square had not long died down.
MFN status, which accords certain countries America's best trading
conditions, has been the cornerstone of US-China trade relations for the
last 10 years. As June 3, the date President Bush must make a decision,
draws nearer, Peking has been at pains to emphasise what it sees as the
serious consequences to relations that would result if MFN privileges are
withdrawn.
Premier Li Peng has warned of losses not only to China but to US companies
seeking to do business there. China's foreign minister Qian Qichen said a
decision to rescind MFN status would benefit neither side and deal a bigger
blow to Hong Kong, which re-exports a lot of Chinese-manufactured goods.
China saves hundreds of millions of dollars a year by paying the lowest
tariffs on goods it exports to the US. The loss of MFN status would be a
blow it can ill afford as the mainland recovers from the austerity measures
implemented at the end of 1988. The US is China's largest market, buying
more than 25 per cent of China's exports.
Under the terms of 'Special 301', a provision of US trade law that permits
the US administration to retaliate against named countries considered to be
particularly unfair in their trade practices, Mrs Hills said China and India
had failed to make any concessions during the past two years in negotiations
over US demands for protection of patents, copyrights, trademarks and
software.
Mrs Hills complained that China practised piracy 'across the board'. It is
the only major US trading partner that does not offer product protection for
pharmaceutical and chemicals, adequate copyright or trade protection, nor
safeguards for trade secrets. Failure to improve intellectual property
protection could evoke US sanctions after six to nine months.
The trade representative's office devoted 10 pages in the 1991 trade
estimates report to Chinese deficiencies. These include a complex import
licensing system, import bans on 80 products and materials, stringent and
excessive quality standards on foreign goods, and barriers to services and
investment.
There is further concern in Washington over China's alleged nuclear
technology transfers to countries such as Pakistan and Algeria - and this
surfaced last night when President Bush refused to approved export of US
satellite parts to China. The parts had been requested for a Chinese
domestic communications satellite, the Dong Fang Hong 3.
Peking has, however, strenuously rejected reports from Washington about
nuclear technology sales to Algeria. Yesterday Algeria offered to submit its
nuclear programme to international inspection.
Meanwhile, Peking disputes the figures that show it has a soaring surplus in
its trade with the US, claiming it is nothing like as large as Dollars 10bn.
Premier Li is reported to have said he was ready to look at statistical
methodology with the Americans and put the Chinese view of the figures.
China leaves out of its statistics of exports to the US all products
produced by US joint venture companies in China, and all goods re-exported
through Hong Kong.
This year more human rights concerns have surfaced in the US over
allegations that China exports goods made by prisoners, a charge it
repeatedly denies. The import of prison-made goods is banned in the US.
China's growing anxiety about MFN may explain why it appears to have
abandoned its longstanding position that human rights is a domestic issue by
inviting Australia to send a team of experts to study human rights in the
country. The likelihood is that the decision is related to trading concerns
and its expectation that they may continue if China cannot improve its
image.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
