<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / UK-based groups on US list alleging Libyan links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO London-based companies were among 48 groups and banks named last night
by the US Treasury as alleged agents of the Libyan government and therefore
subject to the American economic embargo against that country.
The action is part of a continuing Treasury investigation of Libyan efforts
to engage in financial transactions and to buy goods in circumvention of the
embargo.
No US companies are on the list. The majority of the companies named are
based in Arab and Mediterranean countries and many have specific links to
Libya in their title.
The 48 companies are now considered specially designated nationals or agents
of the Libyan government, bringing them under the embargo and assets freeze
put in place in January 1986. All assets of such entities within US
jurisdiction, including overseas branches of US banks, are blocked and
transactions by US persons with such entities are banned. There are criminal
penalties of fines and prison terms for breaches.
Mr Richard Newcomb, director of the US Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets
Control, said last night: 'Libya's policies and actions, including its
continued refusal to disavow terrorism as a tool of international policy,
make such a listing particularly useful in redirecting public attention to
the comprehensive sanctions programme in place against Libya.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
