<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / At last, Bush gets his first opponent: The emergence of a
Democrat presidential hopeful
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST Democrat willing to try his luck in the race next year for US
President has emerged from the political wilderness. Mr Paul Tsongas, a
former Massachusetts senator who yesterday announced his candidacy for his
party's nomination, has everything against him - except a record of beating
impossible odds.
The times do not seem propitious for any Democratic candidate, which is why
Mr Tsongas is, so far, alone in the race. Although the lustre of Operation
Desert Storm has dimmed and the recession seems inclined to linger,
President George Bush is still extraordinarily popular.
Mr Bush has also proved himself a politician who will stop at very little to
win elections; he could well make mincemeat of this unabashed idealist who
dares opponents to put their own beliefs on the table because he thinks
presidential campaigns should be a debate over issues.
Mr Tsongas's admirers say he is a deep thinker, unafraid to take unpopular
stands. He admits that he would have voted against the Gulf war had he been
in the Senate; he pushes a petrol tax and nuclear energy.
Mr Tsongas has not so much been out of the national limelight as much as he
was barely ever in it. He says he has been the underdog in every political
contest he ever entered. After serving two congressional terms and one in
the Senate, he left Washington seven years ago aged 42 with leukaemia and
little hope of surviving.
With bone marrow transplants, massive chemotherapy and radiation, he beat
the affliction into remission and emerged 'thin as a rail, bald as a
billiard ball' and with a belief that he was spared for a purpose.
Since leaving Washington, he says, 'I've travelled to places in the mind
that I'd never visited before, and things which were boring to me are now
wondrous and things which were wondrous now really don't interest me.'
His mission is his message, outlined in an 80-page book, A Call to Economic
Arms, a pro-business manifesto designed both to reform the Democratic Party
and to halt economic decline by re-invigorating the industrial sector.
Democrats must do more than seek to redistribute the national wealth, he
says, because the economic pie is shrinking. 'They are going to have to sit
down with the business community and jointly establish policies of wealth
creation.'
He would seek energy independence through conservation and nuclear power,
make selective cuts in capital gains taxes to promote competitiveness,
provide new seed money and tax credits for research and development, abolish
quarterly reports for businesses.
He decries 'demagogic appeals to protectionism' by the Democratic Party as
well as 'corporate bashing, class warfare, and ideology'. Yet he denounces
the selling of US assets to foreign interests as 'all the blood, sweat and
tears of our forebears on the auction block'.
</TEXT>
