<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Allied forces expand presence in north Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR FOREIGN STAFF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALLIED forces expanded their military presence in northern Iraq yesterday as
Britain's proposal for the United Nations to send its own police units to
protect thousands of returning Kurdish refugees appeared to gather more
support.
UN diplomats said a letter from Mr John Major, the British prime minister,
was delivered to Mr Javier Perez de Cuellar, the UN secretary-general, who
discussed the plan with Sir David Hannay, Britain's UN representative, and
other western delegates. A UN source said he saw merit in the police force
proposal and felt it could be carried out, possibly without need for a
formal Security Council resolution.
There were conflicting reports about the exact contents of the letter, with
reports in London that Mr Major had been critical of the UN's 'tardy'
approach to the relief effort.
The UN, however, said last night that the letter had not been critical and
had been supportive of the secretary-general's efforts.
While diplomatic manoeuvres continued, allied military vehicles were seen
carrying Kurdish refugee women and children from Isikveren camp on the
Turkish-Iraqi border through Kurdish guerrilla checkpoints towards the
so-called 'safe haven' on the edge of the northern town of Zakho, where UN
officials hoisted their blue-and-white flag yesterday.
British Chinook helicopters landed companies of Royal Marines on hilltops
near the village of Kani Masi, about 90km east of Zakho, while Dutch and US
troops secured bridges and mountain tracks.
The second phase of the repatriation operation, expected today, involves
allied troops establishing a perimeter around the refugee sanctuary.
Until Monday evening Kurdish guerrillas had prevented most refugees from
leaving their mountain camps for the allied zone in Iraq, saying that they
wanted to be assured of the refugees' safety.
Western diplomats at the UN in New York yesterday emphasised their view that
the secretary-general had adequate authority to deploy UN civilian police in
the area. The Soviet Union and China, the other permanent members of the
Security Council, were described as 'not negative' to Britain's suggestion.
</TEXT>
