<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Yeltsin says coal strike agreement is near
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR BORIS YELTSIN, the Russian leader, said yesterday he thought an agreement
to end the Russian miners' strike was close.
The key issue in ending the strike is the terms under which the mines will
be transferred from Soviet to Russian government control. The terms were
still being thrashed out in the Kuzbas coalfield in Siberia last night.
The miners have decided to continue their strike until the agreement to
transfer is concluded. In another Russian coalfield, Vorkuta, where all the
mines had returned to work, the strike committee said the pits had decided
to resume the strike because the terms of transfer of the Vorkuta coal
associations to Russian jurisdiction had not been defined.
Views were mixed in the Kuzbas field as Mr Yeltsin continued his talks. Mr
Alexander Aslanidi, one of the miners' leaders, said: 'Yeltsin is being well
received.'
However, Mr Alexander Smirnov of the Novokuznets committee in the Kuzbas
said: 'Our committee will raise their own proposals.'
Some pits in the area have already moved to Russian control, while others
have gone further and transformed themselves to enterprises leased to their
workers.
As Mr Yeltsin negotiated, the newspaper Izvestia published an exchange of
May Day telegrams between the Russian leader and President Mikhail Gorbachev
on the signing of the recent joint statement aimed at ending the strikes and
supporting anti-crisis measures.
Mr Yeltsin expressed 'confidence that the path of reconciliation now being
pursued by the centre and Russia . . . will bring co-ordinated actions to
lead the country out of the crisis.'
Mr Gorbachev said he was convinced that the 'constructive co-operation which
has been given new life . . . will allow the return of life in our country
to a normal pattern.'
The agreement is vague on most points, though purported leaks in recent days
point to Mr Gorbachev conceding that a new union treaty would be framed by
the republics themselves, and possibly even promising to hold an election
for the union presidency later this year.
A demonstration of how vague the statement is came when it was also endorsed
yesterday by Mr Yuri Blokhin, co-chairman of the hardline Soyuz group which
had been calling for Mr Gorbachev's resignation, or at least for a special
congress of peoples' deputies to hold him to account for the economic
crisis.
Mr Blokhin said: 'We are glad our ideas are reflected in this document, such
as observance of the constitutional order, introduction of a special regime
in basic industries and improvement of food supplies.'
Mr Yeltsin, for his part, has defined the 'special regime' as a way of
improving productivity.
</TEXT>
