<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Charged with a gentle closing of the door: The minister who
has to reverse Italy's open immigration policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MARGHERITA Boniver, Italy's new immigration minister, knows she has a tough
job ahead. In the past two years, immigration has become one of the
country's most sensitive political issues.
Moreover, her ministry, which is one of the few innovations to come out of
the government crisis last month, has no independent budget and has yet to
move into new premises. Even when it is functioning, it will have only 35-40
staff.
Yet Mrs Boniver, a Socialist well known for her role in Amnesty
International and other human rights causes, seems confident about the
unenviable, and seemingly impossible, task of co-ordinating and enforcing
the country's landmark immigration law passed in 1990.
That followed years of lax supervision and a tradition of tolerance, which
made Italy a haven for untold thousands of illegal immigrants, many of them
from poor black African states. More recently, Albanians and Yugoslavs have
swelled their ranks.
However, sentiment towards immigrants has soured sharply as their numbers
have increased and the economy has slowed. The upshot has been a tenser
atmosphere, in which violent racist incidents have become more commonplace.
'Italy considered itself a non-racist country,' says Mrs Boniver, one of two
women ministers in the new government. 'But the Italians woke up startled
one day to realise we too have a strain of racism. There is a strain of
racism in all societies. The job is to keep that under control'.
The trigger in Italy has been the apparently sudden, though unquantified,
leap in untrained black immigrants in particular. Few find jobs and most end
up on the street or the beach, pedalling trinkets, cigarettes or fake
designer goods.
Italy having been traditionally a country of emigration, 'the phenomenon of
seeing hundreds of thousands of Africans has become very evident for the
Italians all of a sudden', she explains.
Moreover, the numbers appeared out of control in a country which almost
anybody could enter without a permit. Although some control was
theoretically exercised by the ministry of the interior, there was 'nothing
planned at all', she says. 'And, you know, Italians are not particularly
talented in organisation.'
How will she cope with the new immigration law steered through parliament by
her Socialist colleague Mr Claudio Martelli?
'My first priority is to make the Martelli law work. That is an immense job
in itself, as it means co-ordinating about 12 other ministries, including
local government, the police, education and social services.'
They must join forces to establish the framework for dealing with the
250,000 immigrants who took advantage of the amnesty last year to legalise
their status.
Next comes the problem of longer-term resettlement, she says. Italian
communes have been no more willing to accept Africans and Albanians than the
small west German towns were willing to absorb thousands of east Europeans
as the Communist system collapsed.
Some 800 Albanians have been sent to Mrs Boniver's north Italian
constituency of Asti alone, causing immediate problems there, she says. 'You
can't expect local elected politicians to take on what is an extremely
unpopular task. They keep saying no.'
But while shifting responsibility for resettlement to regional, or even
national, level may take the heat off local politicians, it will not tackle
the root problem.
That involves setting further immigration quotas after the freeze during the
law's first year of operation, when immigrants taking advantage of the
amnesty were legalised and a further 50,000 expelled.
Setting next year's quota is 'one of my first priorities', she says. She
would like preference to be given to Italy's ex-colonies in Africa and to
neighbouring countries such as Albania which have Italian-speaking
communities.
But she admits that enforcing the country-by-country quotas will be all but
impossible given Italy's long coastline, relative proximity to Africa 'and
the fact that we are not a police state'. As a result, the number of illegal
immigrants, estimated at 300,000 even after the amnesty, is set to grow.
The Italians also face the additional threat posed by political instability
in neighbouring countries such as Yugoslavia and Albania. Even under the new
law, there is no visa requirement with Yugoslavia, which means the door is
open to huge inflows in the event of a crisis there.
According to Mrs Boniver, setting up the new ministry has already taken part
of the sting out of the immigration issue. Giving her responsibility for
looking after the interests of Italians abroad will further calm popular
sentiment, she thinks.
'If the new ministry had been just for immigration, it would have created a
lot of resentment' from people claiming that immigrants were getting some
sort of special treatment, she says. So establishing a joint function was
'very astute from a political point of view'.
Moreover, the big Italian communities in countries such as Brazil and
Argentina, which have traditionally come under the foreign ministry's wing,
have not always received enough attention in the past.
It will be her job to co-ordinate policies towards them and to improve the
flow of information to prevent them feeling 'abandoned'. While she stresses
she will give equal weight to both her new responsibilities, it is her
domestic task which is likely to be by far the more pressing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2 Photograph Margherita Boniver, 'There is a strain of racism in
all societies. The job is to keep that under control' (Omitted).
</PAGE>
