<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Germany gives construction equipment lift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY IS likely to lead growth in the European construction equipment
market over the next few years, and could account for almost 30 per cent of
unit sales by 1995, according to a review by London-based Corporate
Intelligence Group (CIG).
The prediction underlines the impact of unification on the German market,
Europe's largest, which accounted for 18 per cent of European unit sales in
1989 and 24 per cent last year, when the five new states were included for
the first time.
'Europe is now a region of great contrasts; the UK and Scandinavian
countries are particularly weak, while the now unified Germany is showing a
buoyancy which nobody could have predicted two years ago,' says the study.
Equipment sales in Germany rose by 25 per cent last year from 19,275 units
in 1989 to 24,273, due to a long-awaited revival of the housing market. This
was caused by cyclical factors and the arrival of large numbers of people
from the former East Germany.
Demand was particularly strong for wheeled loaders and mini-excavators, but
the report singles out 'the gallant backhoe loader salesmen who, after years
of struggling in the west (of Germany) against wheeled excavators, went east
and struck gold - about 400 units sold.'
The study says infrastructural improvements in the east are bound to come
and the potential there is enormous. It forecasts a slight dip in units sold
this year in Germany, to 22,700, but predicts sales will reach 29,200 in
1995, out of a total for Europe of 104,692.
The picture is less bright elsewhere in Europe. Unit sales fell 5 per cent
last year to 100,775 and CIG believes they could be as low as 93,700 units
this year.
One reason for the decline is the enormous number of machines bought during
1987-89, leaving fleets relatively young, and more than sufficient for
current workloads.
Another factor, says the study, is the generally unhealthy economic climate
across Europe; inflation and interest rates have hit governments' spending
plans badly, and large projects have either been cancelled or postponed.
But the study believes 1991 will be a watershed year, and equipment demand
will start to firm up by the middle of 1992. This should set the tone to the
middle of the decade, by when demand should have almost recovered to 1989
levels.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
