<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / VW agrees second joint venture in Czechoslovakia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOLKSWAGEN is to take an eventual 94 per cent stake in a small volume car
assembly and gearbox production venture with BAZ (Bratislavske Automobilove
Zavody), the Slovak automotive engineering group. It has already agreed to
take an eventual 70 per cent stake in the Czechoslovak car-maker Skoda for
DM1.4bn (Pounds 460m).
VW said the joint venture with BAZ would be named Volkswagen Bratislava. VW
will initially take an 80 per cent stake in the DM60m equity capital of the
new venture, the remainder to be owned by the Slovak government. It will
inject a further DM140m in 1992 and 1993.
VW plans to produce 30,000 cars a year (probably the Passat) from completely
knocked down kits from 1993. Until then it will make 3,000 a year from
semi-knocked down kits.
It will also establish a gearbox assembly line at BAZ with a capacity to
produce 1,300 units a day from 1994 for export to VW plants elsewhere.
</TEXT>
