<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Sunday trading may grow after appeal court ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of more stores opening on Sundays increased yesterday after a
court ruling threw doubt upon the enforceability of Sunday trading laws.
The Court of Appeal lifted injunctions banning B&amp;Q, the do-it-yourself
chain, and Wickes Building Supplies from opening stores in West Yorkshire
and Somerset on Sundays.
A lawyer for Kirklees Borough Council, one of the local authorities
involved, said after the hearing that the ruling made the Sunday trading
laws 'virtually unenforceable'.
Retailers were digesting implications of the decision last night. The
British Retailers' Association, representing the multiple chains, described
the decision as 'a further muddying of the legal water' and said it 'made it
all the more imperative for the government to grasp the nettle'.
Texas Homecare, the 230-store DIY chain owned by Ladbroke Group, said it
would open a further 20 stores on Sundays, bringing the total to about 200.
High Court injunctions were granted last May to Kirklees council forcing
Sunday closure on Wickes centres in Huddersfield and Dewsbury, West
Yorkshire, and to Mendip District Council in respect of a new B&amp;Q store at
Glastonbury, Somerset.
The Appeal Court said yesterday that neither local authority had been
willing to give undertakings that, if it eventually lost the case, it would
compensate the stores for any financial losses resulting from enforced
Sunday closure. The court ruled that, as a settled point of law, in the
absence of any such undertakings the injunctions should not have been
granted.
The maximum penalty for Sunday trading is a Pounds 1,000 fine, per store on
any one Sunday. This has not proved a sufficient deterrent to large chain
stores which can make as much as Pounds 500,000 profit a year per store from
Sunday trading. Local authorities have turned increasingly to injunctions
during the past 18 months as the only effective means of enforcing the law.
Mr David Ramsden, B&amp;Q's controller of retail services, called the decision a
'resounding victory'. Councils would have to think hard before risking
taxpayers' money on prosecutions.
Mr Roger Butterfield, senior solicitor for Kirklees, doubted if many local
authorities would give undertakings to back applications for injunctions
because of the enormous cost involved if they lost. 'This judgment has made
the Shops Act virtually unenforceable,' he said. The council has yet to
decide whether it will appeal.
Mr Bill Connor, deputy general secretary of Usdaw, the shopworkers trade
union, said the ruling was 'a technical victory for illegal Sunday traders'.
The union's annual conference passed a motion affirming its opposition to
reform of the act. Mr Connor said the act was 'all we have' to protect
workers from having their hours extended against their wishes.
B&amp;Q estimates that up to 100 stores are affected by injunctions banning them
from Sunday trading.
The company said it would be contacting local authorities involved to ask
them either to give undertakings or drop the injunctions.
The legality of the Sunday trading laws will be challenged by B&amp;Q in the
House of Lords next month. The group is appealing against a ruling by Mr
Justice Hoffmann in the High Court last July that the 1950 Shops Act does
not contravene free trade principles of European Community law.
The Law Lords may refer the issue to the European Court in Luxembourg, which
could prolong the uncertainty about the Sunday trading laws for another two
years.
Usdaw votes, Page 11
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
