<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / US discount rate cut as Fed eases monetary policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Federal Reserve yesterday moved to stimulate the flagging American
economy by unexpectedly easing monetary policy.
It cut the discount rate - the rate charged when banks borrow reserves
directly from the central bank - by half a percentage point to 5 1/2 per
cent and signalled a quarter point cut to 5.75 per cent in the federal funds
rate - the key short-term interest rate, which banks charge each other for
loans.
The cut in the discount rate, the third half-point reduction since December,
follows repeated calls from the White House for an easing of monetary policy
to combat the domestic recession. President George Bush, who has
unsuccessfully urged interest rate cuts in other industrialised economies,
praised the Fed for showing strong leadership. He said the move would
stimulate growth not only in the US but across the world.
The dollar lost more than 5 pfennigs in London to close at DM1.7170, while
against the pound it finished nearly 5 cents lower at Dollars 1.7240. In New
York it weakened further but ended above its day's lows at DM1.708 and
Dollars 1.7315.
The rate cut caught the ministers and central bank governors at the spring
meetings of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank by surprise. It
had not been discussed in Sunday's meeting of the Group of Seven leading
industrial countries or in Monday's session of the IMF's policy-making
Interim Committee.
Germany welcomed the action but made clear that there was no chance of
similar action by the Bundesbank.
Mr Norman Lamont, the UK chancellor, said the cut was good for British
recovery prospects. He added that UK interest rates would continue to be set
in accordance with the pound's position in the exchange rate mechanism of
the European Monetary System and the need to bear down on inflation.
However, the Fed action both reduced the attraction to international
investors of the dollar, which has shown persistent strength since February,
and raised the possibility of interest-rate cuts elsewhere.
Mr David Morrison, chief international economist at the London office of
Goldman Sachs, the US bank, said the move would help Italy, France and
Britain in particular. All three are keen to ease borrowing conditions as
part of their effort to bolster growth.
Cuts in the US prime rate are now likely. Yesterday Southwest Bank, a small
St Louis bank that has led industry moves in the past, took the plunge,
cutting its prime rate from 9 per cent to 8 3/4 per cent.
The Fed's move came on a 4-1 vote of the governors with Governor Wayne
Angell casting the dissenting vote. The cut follows a vigorous internal
debate about policy with some regional presidents and governors expressing
concern about the inflation outlook.
The Fed said action was taken 'in the light of continued weakness in
economic activity, especially in the industrial and capital goods areas, and
evidence of abating inflationary pressures'. It added that the reduction in
part realigned the discount rate with market interest rates.
The easing of policy follows a spate of poor economic statistics. The
Commerce Department said factory orders had fallen by 2.8 per cent in March
and durable goods orders by 6 per cent. Real GNP contracted at an annual
rate of 2.8 per cent in the first quarter, a steeper decline than
anticipated by the White House.
Early indicators for April are not encouraging. The Conference Board, a
business group based in New York, said its index of consumer confidence,
fell slightly in April after a big rise in March. Surveys show consumers
more depressed about current conditions but relatively sanguine about
longer-term trends.
Rate cut Page 6
Bonds Page 28
Money Markets Page 31
World Stocks Page 37
London Stocks Page 40
</TEXT>
