<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Falls trimmed by US interest rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON equities slipped lower yesterday in lacklustre trading, taking only
marginal comfort from an unexpected cut in US interest rates. A survey from
the Confederation of British Industry served to remind fund managers that it
is still too soon to call the bottom of the recession. Investors saw no
reason to commit themselves ahead of the UK local government elections being
held tomorrow.
The overnight fall on Wall Street led to an uninspired start to trading in
London. The dollar reversed its trend of recent days, falling a steep five
cents against sterling by the end of the session. This had the predictable
effect of weakening international stocks, whose strength had been behind
much of the previous day's market rise. Since the sector includes some of
the highest capitalisation issues in the market, the falls had a large
effect on the Footsie index.
Traders looking for a guide to sentiment found little help in the latest
Confederation of British Industry monthly survey of industrial trends.
On the one hand, the CBI confirmed that fewer UK manufacturers see output
declining in the coming months. Mr Richard Kersley at BZW said that in
previous recessions such a turning point in output forecasts indicated that
company earnings would begin to recover about six months later.
But investment plans continued to be delayed. This suggests that engineering
and capital goods companies might be left out of any third quarter earnings
recovery. Mr Kersley said that this again was to be expected; capital goods
earnings tended to be a lagging indicator in the economic cycle.
He warned that investors should be wary of optimistic interpretations of the
CBI survey, saying that new orders in the last few months had been so weak
that some hopes for recovery were based on the view that 'things cannot
continue this badly'.
The expiry of the April future contract yesterday failed to lift prices, in
spite of the efforts of at least one securities house to support the Footsie
index. In this atmosphere of uncertainty the Footsie index reached its low
point for the day of 2,475.6 just before Wall Street opened. The half
percentage point cut in the US discount rate, to 5 1/2 per cent, coincided
with the start of trading in New York.
'There seems to have been a tacit deal with the Bundesbank (at last
weekend's G7 meeting),' said Mr Robin Gilbert at Schroders. He thought that
as a result it was now unlikely that the Bundesbank would increase its
interest rates at its fortnightly meeting tomorrow.
The consequent sharp opening rise in the Dow Jones Industrial Average,
however, produced only a muted response in London. The Footsie recovered to
2,486.2, still a fall of 12 on the day. Turnover, at 413.9m shares, was only
a little higher than the previous day's dismal levels of business. Mr
Richard Lake, a chartist at Hoare Govett, said the London stock market would
continued to languish. His trigger for a rally is a level on the Footsie of
2,450.
Among individual stocks. Coats Viyella's increased offer for Tootal had been
well signalled in the press. The steady stream of rights issues continued.
Clothing and engineering group William Baird called for Pounds 39m in a
one-for-five issue. As if to underscore the CBI survey, and the market's
mood, Baird accompanied its cash call with a warning that trading conditions
would remain difficult in the short term.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 40
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2206</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLADDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EXPECTED squeeze in the equity futures market ahead of the expiry of the
April FT-SE 100 index options contract failed to materialise yesterday.
Instead, the market remained on the defensive as Wall Street reacted with a
distinct lack of enthusiasm to the reduction in US interest rates.
Barclays de Zoete Wedd was said to be short of April 2,500 FT-SE puts before
the options expiry. But when the futures market failed to hold above 2,500,
it was forced to try to buy back puts and hedge itself by selling the
futures market.
So by the time of the expiry of the April options, the Footsie futures' lead
over the cash index had been whittled away to just 10 points, which
depressed the stock market.
This was reflected in the options market turnover figures, which showed the
FT-SE contracts accounting for over 9,000 lots or a third of the day's
business. FT-SE options normally make up just under a quarter of daily
turnover.
The June FT-SE future closed at 2,509, down 12 points. Its premium to the
spot FT-SE index ended at 26 points, compared with 22 at the previous close
and fair value of 15.
British Gas options were heavily traded on news of its agreement to tough
controls on price rises. Investors sold puts and calls. The June 260 calls
had 1,900 lots traded.
</TEXT>
